<HEADLINE> Ala. Suspect Pleads Innocent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBIANA, Ala. (AP) -- A man who allegedly killed three people  
in shootings at two companies he used to work at pleaded innocent 
today by reason of mental disease or defect. 
</P>
<P>
	A judge ordered psychiatric tests for Alan Eugene Miller, 34.  
</P>
<P>
	Miller is charged with capital murder in the slayings of Lee  
Holdbrooks, 32; Christopher Scott Yancy, 28; Terry Jarvis, 39. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller worked as a truck driver at Ferguson Enterprises, where  
gunfire first erupted. Holdbrooks, a truck driver, and Yancy, a 
dispatcher, were shot there. 
</P>
<P>
	Jarvis was killed later at Post Airgas, where Miller formerly  
worked. 
</P>
<P>
	A capital murder conviction carries a penalty of either life in  
prison without parole or the death penalty. Defense attorneys have 
said Miller would be committed to a state institution if found 
innocent by reason of insanity. 
</P>
<P>
	District Attorney Robby Owens said he plans to seek the death  
penalty for the Aug 5 shootings in Pelham. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
