<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Nebiolo To Be Re-Elected IAAF Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEVILLE, Spain (AP) -- Despite rumors of poor health and repeated  
complaints about his autocratic style, Primo Nebiolo will be 
reelected president of track and field's world governing body for a 
sixth term Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	When the International Amateur Athletic Federation begins its  
two-day Congress meetings on the eve of the World Championships, 
the 76-year-old Nebiolo will be the only candidate on the ballot. 
</P>
<P>
	For more than a year, Nebiolo, who has steered the  
organization's growth for 18 years, has been rumored to be in ill 
health with prostate cancer, but he has denied the suggestions. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am well and I hope people continue to talk about my healing  
because it brings me luck,'' said the gravely voiced Nebiolo, who 
remains extremely active for someone considered to be ailing. ``I 
heard I am sick, but what can I say. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am not the fighter I once was, but I am still in perfect  
shape.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nebiolo's spokesman, Giorgio Reineri, also discounts the rumors  
about his boss' health. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe he looks tired, but his brain is working perfectly,''  
Reineri said. ``He has a terrific memory.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nebiolo certainly needs a good memory just to keep track of all  
his responsibilities. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to being chief of the IAAF, he has been president of  
the International University Sport Federation (FISU) since 1961, 
president of the Association of Summer Olympics International 
Federations (AOSIF) since 1983, a member of the International 
Olympic Committee since 1992, and president of the University 
Sports Club of Turin, his hometown, since 1948. 
</P>
<P>
	The tireless and enthusiastic Nebiolo also is chairman of  
several companies, particularly in the field of construction. In 
May 1991, he was appointed by the Italian government to the 
administrative board of Finmeccanica, one of the largest state 
holding companies in Italy, comprised of 85 companies with more 
than 95,000 employees. 
</P>
<P>
	In sports, Nebiolo's biggest impact has been with the IAAF.  
</P>
<P>
	When he took over in 1981, there were fewer than 100 members.  
Now, there are more than 200. 
</P>
<P>
	The IAAF had a one-room office in a dingy London neighborhood.  
For the past six years, it has had a sprawling layout in wealthy 
and glamorous Monte Carlo. 
</P>
<P>
	The organization's budget then was $50,000. Now, it's more than  
$50 million. 
</P>
<P>
	He has skillfully overseen the transition of the sport from  
amateur to professional. Older athletes such as 35-year-old pole 
vaulter Sergei Bubka and long sprinter Michael Johnson, 31, have 
kept competing because they can make a generous living from track 
and field. 
</P>
<P>
	Nebiolo introduced prize money, appearance fees, world-record  
bonuses, the world indoor and outdoor championships, the World Cup, 
the lucrative Grand Prix and Golden League circuits, and the world 
cross country, world marathon, world half-marathon and world junior 
championships. 
</P>
<P>
	The representatives of the member federations meet every two  
years for the IAAF Congress, which is the organization's 
decision-making body. 
</P>
<P>
	The IAAF was formed on July 17, 1912, two days after the final  
track and field event at the Stockholm Olympics. One year later, J. 
Sigfrid Edstrom of Sweden was elected president. Since then, there 
have been only three other presidents. 
</P>
<P>
	Lord Burghley of Britain and Northern Ireland, who later became  
the Marquis of Exeter, succeeded Edstrom in 1946. At the 1976 
Montreal Congress, Adriaan Paulen replaced Lord Exeter. 
</P>
<P>
	Paulen had the shortest reign, five years, before retiring in  
1981, replaced by Nebiolo. 
</P>
<P>
	Nebiolo was reelected in 1984, 1987, 1991 and 1995.  
</P>
<P>
	For the past two decades, he has been among the world's sports  
rulers, along with IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch and world 
soccer (FIFA) president Joao Havelange, who recently retired. 
</P>
<P>
	While directing the IAAF's steady growth, Nebiolo also has been  
the center of much controversy. 
</P>
<P>
	He has been called dictatorial, scheming and money grabbing,  
among other things. 
</P>
<P>
	Dave Moorcroft, the head of UK Athletics, has taken exception to  
Nebiolo's comments on the recently announced suspension of Linford 
Christie, the 1992 Olympic 100-meter gold medalist, for allegedly 
using the banned substance Nandrolone. 
</P>
<P>
	``I regret an athlete of his age (39) with having to resort to  
such tricks,'' Nebiolo said. ``If he made a mistake, he has to pay. 
We will be inflexible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Moorcroft said Nebiolo shouldn't have said anything while the  
case was being investigated by the British federation. 
</P>
<P>
	No one ever accused Nebiolo of not being outspoken.  
  	   	
</P>
