<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Daubach Has Dream Season for Red Sox </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The mail is piled waist-high next to Brian  
Daubach's locker, a leaning tower of cards and letters in danger of 
being knocked over in the next media crush. 
</P>
<P>
	And every one of them is addressed to Nomar Garciaparra.  
</P>
<P>
	Daubach? His mail fits neatly into the general delivery  
cubbyholes provided for the more mortal Boston players. But at the 
rate the rookie first baseman is going, he could join Garciaparra 
in the hearts of Red Sox fans -- and in the record book as well. 
</P>
<P>
	After nine years in the minor leagues -- and then being released  
by the lowly Florida Marlins -- Daubach is among the top contenders 
for the AL rookie of the year award, an honor his clubhouse 
neighbor won in 1997. The 27-year-old Daubach is batting .338 with 
19 homers and 68 RBIs -- driving in 15 runs one four-game stretch 
alone. 
</P>
<P>
	``The boy can hit,'' Oakland designated hitter Matt Stairs said  
Monday night after watching Daubach beat his A's with a two-out, 
full-count, three-run double. ``He's my rookie of the year, that's 
for sure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other contenders for the award voted on by the Baseball Writers  
Association of America include Kansas City outfielder Carlos 
Beltran, who's hitting .292 with 18 homers and 80 RBIs, and Toronto 
closer Billy Koch, who has 24 saves and a 2.35 ERA. 
</P>
<P>
	Originally a 19th-round pick by the New York Mets in 1990,  
Daubach bounced around the minors for nine years and filled in as a 
replacement player during the 1994-95 strike. He led the 
International League with 35 homers and 124 RBIs last season, then 
had 15 at-bats with Florida as a September callup. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once you spend a lot of time in the minor leagues, you get  
labeled a Triple-A player,'' Daubach said. ``That's what you doubt 
more than anything else: whether you'll get the opportunity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Marlins didn't give it to him, so he accepted an invitation  
to go to spring training with the Red Sox, who were looking for 
someone to play first base after Mo Vaughn signed with Anaheim as a 
free agent. Now, for just $215,000, he's outperforming his $13 
million-a-year predecessor, who has been hurt much of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``He never got a chance with the Mets,'' said teammate Butch  
Huskey. ``But he's one of those players who, when he was down 
there, he worked on his craft. Anybody can see that because he's 
doing it here now. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of guys that don't get the opportunity can come up and  
play. But you need a break. You need someone in your corner to get 
you to the big leagues. And when you get the opportunity, you need 
to make the most of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That is exactly what Daubach has done.  
</P>
<P>
	Hours after he was named the AL's player of the week for Aug.  
9-15, batting .500 with three homers and 15 RBIs, Daubach came to 
the plate with the bases loaded, two outs and the Red Sox trailing 
5-3. He worked the count to 3-1 and then fouled off five 
consecutive pitches, missing a homer down the right-field line by 
inches, before doubling off the Wall. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-5 victory held the Athletics at bay in the AL wild-card  
race. Instead of a tie, Boston led Oakland by two games after 
Monday's games. 
</P>
<P>
	``For August, this is probably the biggest series we're going to  
have,'' Daubach said. ``It's an emotional time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if it was the most important hit he ever had, Daubach said  
he was more excited when he hit his first major league homer off 
Graeme Lloyd on May 17. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's when I knew I belonged,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	With his next home run, Daubach will join Ted Williams and Fred  
Lynn as the only Red Sox left-handers to hit 20 homers in their 
rookie year. If he keeps it up, he could join Walt Dropo, Don 
Schwall, Carlton Fisk, Lynn and Garciaparra as Red Sox players to 
win the rookie of the year award. No award was given in Williams' 
time. 
</P>
<P>
	Then maybe his mail will be spilling into Garciaparra's locker.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think (the fans) appreciate where he's come from, and maybe  
they can associate with the work ethic and the time it's taken to 
get the opportunity,'' Red Sox manager Jimy Williams said. ``And 
then to be successful like that, maybe a lot of them feel that it's 
them in that uniform with him.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
