<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Immigrants in N.H. Jail Protest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) -- Immigrants being held in a New Hampshire  
jail are protesting the conditions of their confinement by refusing 
to eat. 
</P>
<P>
	The detainees claim they are locked up for 20 hours a day, get  
only half-hour visits, are verbally abused by staff and have to 
wait a week to get new clothing. They also say they do not have 
enough information about their cases and access to the court 
system. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the immigrants, Sophan Srey, 21, of Cambodia, said in a  
telephone interview that 16 people stopped eating on Monday, and by 
Tuesday night, 50 people were participating. 
</P>
<P>
	``The officers abuse us all the time, they call us names,'' he  
said. ``They tell us we have no rights in New Hampshire.'' 
</P>
<P>
	James O'Mara Jr., the jail's superintendent, said only 13  
detainees were refusing to eat. O'Mara said he would investigate 
claims that staff members had been abusive. 
</P>
<P>
	Amy Otten, a spokeswoman for the Immigration and Naturalization  
Service, said INS and county jail officials would meet with the 
inmates to try to resolve their concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	The INS detains about 16,000 people in prisons and jails, partly  
the result of the 1996 Illegal Immigration Reform and Immigrant 
Responsibility Act, which allows immigrants guilty of minor crimes 
to be deported or detained for long periods. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
