<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ill. Gov. Vetoes Umpire Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) -- Legislation that would have protected  
umpires and referees from violent fans was vetoed by Illinois Gov. 
George Ryan. 
</P>
<P>
	Ryan vetoed a bill this weekend making it illegal to attack  
sports officials and setting a minimum $1,000 fine for offenders. 
</P>
<P>
	The governor argued the bill was vague because it applied to  
attacks on ``sports officials,'' which could include coaches, 
ticket-takers or any stadium personnel. He also said it is unneeded 
because it already is a felony to attack someone -- sports official 
or not -- in a public place. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, Senate President James ``Pate'' Philip spoke against the  
bill in the Legislature, saying umpires and referees ``deserve a 
pop every once in a while.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Senators roared with laughter and quickly voted 33-16 -- with  
Philip voting ``no'' -- to advance the legislation to the House, 
where it also won passage. 
</P>
<P>
	Philip later explained he has never attacked a referee but  
considers them a problem. 
</P>
<P>
	Barry Mano, president of the Wisconsin-based National  
Association of Sports Officials, said his group gets a police 
report every week on violence against referees and umpires. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
