<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Aug. 17, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Enormity of Turkey Quake Clear  
</P>
<P>
	ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) -- Terrified earthquake survivors sought  
the safety of open ground Tuesday as the enormity of Turkey's 
tragedy became clear: more than 2,000 people killed, 10,000 injured 
and thousands more missing after an overwhelming show of nature's 
power. Geophysicists at the U.S. National Earthquake Information 
Center described the quake as one of the most powerful recorded in 
the 20th century, nearly rivaling the 7.9-magnitude tremor than 
devastated San Francisco in 1906. As many as 10,000 people could 
still be trapped in rubble around the town of Golcuk, 80 miles 
southeast of Istanbul, according to the town's mayor, Ismail Baris. 

</P>
<P>
	Feds Bust Drug Networks in 14 Cities  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal agents arrested scores of people and  
seized drugs and money in 14 cities today in an effort to break up 
what the FBI called one of the top 20 drug distribution networks in 
the country. The target of the multiagency Operation Southwest 
Express was the drug trafficking organization of Omar Rocha Soto, 
arrested with his wife, Adriana Espinoza, early Tuesday as they 
left their $649,000 home in a San Diego suburb. During the yearlong 
investigation, agents seized 4,158 pounds of marijuana, 2,727 
kilograms of cocaine and more than $1.15 million in cash. By late 
this afternoon, 77 arrests had been made, and more than 20 others 
were expected, the FBI said. 

</P>
<P>
	Bosnian Leaders May Have Stolen $1B  
</P>
<P>
	SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) -- Bosnia's Muslim president on  
Tuesday branded as lies allegations by international officials that 
top Muslim, Croat and Serbian officials may have stolen more than 
$1 billion in public funds and international aid. The allegations, 
based on findings of the anti-fraud unit of the Office of the High 
Representative, appeared in The New York Times. A spokeswoman for 
the OHR, which oversees implementation of the 1995 Dayton peace 
agreement, said the report was largely correct. 

</P>
<P>
	Iraq Has Extended Missile Range  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Iraq has extended the range of one of its best  
anti-aircraft missiles, but the retooled weapon poses no 
significant additional threat to U.S. and British pilots patrolling 
no-flight zones over Iraq, the Pentagon said today. Iraq has 
challenged the patrols since last December by attempting to shoot 
down the planes; today it fired anti-aircraft artillery and tracked 
U.S. planes with radars used by surface-to-air missiles, U.S. 
officials said. In response, U.S. planes bombed Iraqi missile 
sites. The official Iraqi News Agency in Baghdad quoted the 
military as saying eight people were killed in attacks in the 
northern zone and 11 were killed in the south. 

</P>
<P>
	US Disappointed by India Nuke Plan  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- India is ``moving in the wrong direction'' by  
trying to create a credible nuclear deterrence and the United 
States will continue efforts to encourage both India and Pakistan 
to abandon their nuclear programs, the State Department said today. 
Spokesman James P. Rubin commented in response to a draft doctrine 
released by India's National Security Advisory Board, which stated 
that India will pursue a policy of credible nuclear deterrence. 

</P>
<P>
	ETrade To Offer After-Hours Trading  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- ETrade Group Inc. plans to offer after-hours  
trading through Instinet, bringing the Internet's second biggest 
pool of investors to the busiest market for buying and selling 
stocks when regular exchanges are closed. The service is to begin 
next month. It would make ETrade the biggest online broker so far 
to let its customers react to late-breaking news, a privilege long 
enjoyed by money managers, mutual funds and other ``institutional'' 
investors. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Up 70.29 Points  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A late rally propelled stocks higher today after  
news of a mild increase in consumer prices suggested the Federal 
Reserve may raise interest rates only modestly when it meets this 
month. The Dow Jones industrial average ended up 70.29 at 
11,117.08. On the NYSE, gainers led losers 1,836-1,151. The Nasdaq 
rose 25.94 to 2,671.22. 

</P>
<P>
	Hingis Gains in du Maurier Tennis  
</P>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Martina Hingis beat Corina Marariu 6-0, 6-3 in 54  
minutes today in a second-round match of the $1.05 million du 
Maurier Open tennis tournament. ``This is one I have never won, so 
I'm kind of pumped,'' said Hingis, who lost in the semifinals to 
Monica Seles last year. Hingis will meet 16th-seeded Chandra Rubin 
in the third round. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY FOSS  
  	   	
</P>
