<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Giuliani Hedges on Abortion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Republican Rudolph Giuliani, weighing a bid  
for the U.S. Senate and perhaps courting support from New York's 
Conservative Party, appears to be hedging on past strong support 
for abortion rights. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's something I think that I'll address myself to if and  
when I announce and I get a chance to think out all of those 
positions,'' the New York City mayor said when asked about his past 
opposition to a ban on what critics call partial-birth abortions. 
</P>
<P>
	The mayor's opposition to such a ban has put him at odds with  
Gov. George Pataki and other top New York Republicans and with the 
state's small but politically influential Conservative Party. 
</P>
<P>
	No Republican has won statewide office in New York without  
Conservative support since the third party was founded more than 25 
years ago. The party's vote gave Pataki the governorship in 1994 
over Democratic incumbent Mario Cuomo. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate race in New York, for the seat being vacated next  
year by Democrat Daniel Patrick Moynihan, could pit Giuliani 
against Hillary Rodham Clinton, an abortion rights supporter who 
opposes any ban on the late-term abortion procedure. 
</P>
<P>
	Told Tuesday about Giuliani's noncommittal comment, abortion  
rights activist Kelli Conlin expressed surprise. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's been so strong on this issue, ... it would just be very  
shocking to me if this was something he switched on,'' said Conlin, 
of the National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League, who 
served on Giuliani's mayoral transition committee in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, as he ran for a second term, Giuliani told the league  
he would ``oppose legislation that would make criminals of doctors 
who perform intact D&AMP;X abortions.'' Intact dilation and extraction 
abortion is the technical term for what abortion opponents call 
partial-birth abortions. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
