<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Woman on Trial in Daughter's Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- An elderly woman on trial for shooting and  
paralyzing her daughter -- who eventually died after winning the 
right to be taken off life support -- was briefly removed from the 
courtroom today after shouting at the judge. 
</P>
<P>
	The outburst from 68-year-old Shirley Egan came with jurors out  
of the courtroom during a hearing on whether to allow a detective 
to testify. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sorry. I'm so confused,'' Ms. Egan shouted. ``I've had  
memory loss since I was a child. This isn't fair. I didn't do it. I 
loved my daughter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Circuit Judge Thomas Mihok ordered Ms. Egan out of the courtroom  
and warned her that she would be removed permanently if she had 
another outburst. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Egan was wheeled back in about five minutes later and  
apologized to the judge. Mihok ruled that Orange County Sheriff's 
Office Detective Riggs Gay could testify. 
</P>
<P>
	The outburst from Ms. Egan on the second day of her trial was a  
sharp departure from her demeanor the previous day. The feeble 
woman, who is blind in one eye, sat slumped in her wheelchair and 
spent most of the day with her face buried in a sheet. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said Ms. Egan opened fire March 8 after overhearing her  
42-year-old daughter, Georgette Smith, and Ms. Smith's boyfriend 
talking about putting her in a nursing home. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Smith was shot in the neck and paralyzed from the neck down,  
barely able to speak and incapable of swallowing or controlling her 
bladder. Saying she couldn't bear to live in that condition, Ms. 
Smith won the right in May to be taken off life support, and died. 
</P>
<P>
	In opening statements Monday, defense attorney Bob Wesley told  
the jury that his client was on medication that altered her 
sensibilities at the time of the shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	``Shirley Egan was not responsible for her actions,'' Wesley  
said, calling her ``angry, crazy and irrational'' from taking 
Prozac and medication to relieve pain from a 1997 accident. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Wesley and prosecutor Pam Smith told jurors they would see  
a videotaped deposition taken a day before Ms. Smith died in which 
Ms. Smith said she thought the shooting was accidental. 
</P>
<P>
	``She does not want to believe that her mother shot her,'' the  
prosecutor said. ``She wants to believe it was an accident.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In testimony Monday, paramedic Tiffany Rinehart, who treated Ms.  
Egan after the shooting, said that the elderly woman said she had 
retrieved her gun to scare Ms. Smith and the boyfriend, Larry 
Videlock. 
</P>
<P>
	``She said she was tired of them harassing her and telling her  
they were going to put her in a nursing home,'' Rinehart said. 
``She said she meant to shoot it over her head.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The paramedic also testified Ms. Egan said she had $7,300 in the  
apartment that she intended to give to a charity but Ms. Smith and 
Videlock wanted the money for themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Egan was charged with two counts of attempted murder, for  
wounding her daughter and shooting at Videlock, who was not hurt. 
After her daughter died, prosecutors considered bringing murder 
charges, but decided against it, citing Ms. Egan's failing health 
and her relationship to the victim. Wesley said Ms. Smith did not 
want her mother charged with murder. 
</P>
<P>
	The trial was broadcast live over the Internet by the Florida  
Circuit Court. It was believed to be the first criminal trial in 
the nation to be broadcast online by a court, said Valerie Taylor, 
a spokeswoman for the Virginia-based National Center for State 
Courts. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
