<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets closed lower Tuesday  
as many investors took profits ahead of the release later in the 
day of the U.S. consumer price index, a widely watched gauge of 
inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Bucking the trend was the Tokyo Stock Exchange, where the key  
index rose for the seventh straight session as investors bought 
select international blue chip shares. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 34.06 points,  
or 0.19 percent, to close at 17,860.09. On Monday, the average 
finished up 390.86 points, or 2.24 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``Blue-chip stocks continue to lead the market, and we may see  
further polarization of stronger and weaker shares,'' said Ken 
Yamano, general manager of the equities section at Taiheiyo 
Securities Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading was subdued as market players waited for the price data  
for clues on the direction of U.S. markets. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the U.S. dollar was quoted at 114.60 yen in  
late-afternoon trading, down 0.24 yen from late Monday in Tokyo and 
below its level late Monday in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	In Manila, heavy selling of Philippine Long Distance Telephone  
Co., a weaker peso and rising domestic interest rates sent share 
prices plunging to their lowest level in four months. 
</P>
<P>
	The Philippine Stock Exchange Index of 30 selected companies  
fell 88.17 points, or 4.1 percent, to 2,087.13 after rising 4.31 
points Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Leading the decliners was PLDT, which reported a 64 percent drop  
in its first half net profits to 1.61 billion pesos ($41 million). 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the dollar closed at 39.620 pesos, up from 39.425  
pesos on Monday. It averaged 39.589 pesos, up from Monday's 39.315 
pesos. 
</P>
<P>
	South Korean shares also closed sharply lower, pushed down by  
doubts over whether the financially troubled Daewoo Group will be 
able to carry out its restructuring plans agreed upon with creditor 
banks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Korea Composite Stock Price Index fell 33.58 points, or 3.7  
percent, to 873.70. 
</P>
<P>
	Profit-taking pushed prices on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange  
lower. 
</P>
<P>
	The blue-chip Hang Seng Index fell 111.62 points, or 0.9  
percent, to close at 12,783.16. On Monday, the index had surged 
286.60 points, or 2.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading remained thin as many investors stayed on the sidelines  
ahead of the release later Tuesday in the United States of the July 
consumer price index, which could determine the direction of U.S. 
interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The market was closed in Indonesia for national day  
celebrations. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Share prices closed higher as Morgan Stanley Capital  
International's decision to double the weighting of Taiwan stocks 
in its global indexes continued to spur buying. The market key's 
Weighted Stock Price Index rose 64.96 points, or 0.8 percent, to 
8,083.43. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed mixed. The benchmark  
NZSE-40 Capital Index rose 1.84 points, or 0.08 percent, to 
2,188.39. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: The Australian stock market closed broadly lower. The  
benchmark All Ordinaries Index fell 29.9 points, or 0.9 percent, to 
2,988.0. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian share prices closed lower as investors  
continued to sell stocks ahead of September 1, when foreign 
investors will be able to repatriate their funds from the country 
without paying tax. The Composite Index fell 14.94 points, or 1.9 
percent, to 751.47. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Share prices closed lower as investors stayed on the  
sidelines ahead of U.S. economic data. The Straits Times Index fell 
15.07 points, or 0.7 percent, to 1,983.52. 
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai share prices closed lower. The Stock Exchange of  
Thailand index fell 6.80 points, or 1.6 percent, to 411.31. 


  	   	
</P>
