<HEADLINE> Clinton Offers Help to Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As U.S. search and rescue teams headed to  
Turkey, President Clinton today offered his thoughts and prayers to 
survivors of that nation's deadly earthquake. 
</P>
<P>
	``We must stand with them and do whatever we can to help them to  
get through this terrible crisis,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	The president noted that the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of  
Staff, Gen. Henry Shelton, was in Ankara for military meetings, and 
has offered military support for recovery efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will continue to determine what further help is needed,''  
he said. ``You can only imagine how difficult this is for them and 
we will do what we can to help.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Energy Secretary Bill Richardson also was in Turkey, and was  
asleep in an Istanbul hotel room when the quake hit at about 3 a.m. 
local time. 
</P>
<P>
	Both U.S. officials were unhurt and there were no reports of  
Americans hurt or of damage to U.S. buildings, said White House 
spokesman David Leavy. 
</P>
<P>
	The Turkish prime minister, Bulent Ecevit, previously scheduled  
a meeting with Clinton at the White House for Sept. 28. The two 
leaders plan to discuss security in the region, and the tussle 
between Turkey and Greece over control of the island of Cyprus. 
</P>
<P>
	Search and rescue teams from Miami and Fairfax, Va., are headed  
to Turkey as part of an Agency for International Development 
delegation, the White House said. The U.S searchers will advise and 
help train local and European teams, Leavy said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
