<HEADLINE> Grain, Soybean Prices Advances / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices were higher in  
early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn prices received a big boost from another decline in the  
U.S. Agriculture Department's weekly crop rating. The corn crop is 
in particularly bad condition in Ohio, where 27 percent of the crop 
is considered in poor or very poor condition. At this point in the 
season, experts say they do not expect to see much improvement in 
the condition of the crop. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures prices received a boost on the export front.  
Egypt, Algeria and Taiwan have entered the market for U.S. wheat. 
The USDA also has announced the sale of 140,000 metric tons of 
wheat to Peru. 
</P>
<P>
	A 4 percent decline in the wheat crop rating also is giving a  
lift to prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean prices were higher on National Weather Service forecasts  
of limited rainfall in the Midwest and Great Plains over the next 
10 days. The USDA also lowered the rating of the soybean crop, 
saying on 51 percent of the crop was in good-to-excellent 
condition. 
</P>
<P>
	In early trading, wheat for September delivery was 3 1/2 cents  
higher at $2.72 1/4 a bushel; September corn was 4 1/2 cents higher at 
$2.18 1/2 a bushel; September oats were 1 1/2 cents higher at $1.10 1/2 a 
bushel; August soybeans were 15 cents higher at $4.71 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Cattle and hog futures prices were mixed in early trading on the  
Chicago Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle were .10 cent higher at 66.45 cents a pound.  
August feeder cattle were .03 cent lower at 77.17 cents a pound; 
October lean hogs were .43 cent higher at 45.85 cents a pound; 
August frozen pork bellies were 1.40 cents lower at 51.90 cents a 
pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
