<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grain, Soybean Futures Gain / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices were higher in  
trading Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade as the market reacted 
to the government's latest crop condition reports. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures prices surged at the start of trading in response  
to the U.S. Department of Agriculture's rating of the crop as 58 
percent good to excellent, a decline from the previous week. There 
also was concern that below normal precipitation in coming days 
could further hurt the crop. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean futures prices surged early in the day in reaction to  
weather forecasts and the USDA's weekly soybean update, which 
indicates the poor condition of some of the corn could mean a drop 
in the 2.87 billion bushels forecast Aug. 12. But the early gains 
were trimmed by profit-taking. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures were higher as the market reacted to news Algeria,  
Egypt and Tunisia are in the market for U.S. wheat. The USDA also 
announced the sale of 140,000 metric tons of wheat to Peru. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat prices also got a boost from an unexpected decline in the  
condition of the wheat crop. The USDA estimates 58 percent of the 
crop is in good to excellent condition. Ideas the dry weather will 
help with the harvest trimmed the early gains. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for September delivery was a 1/4 cent higher at $2.69 a  
bushel; September corn was 2 1/2 cents higher at $2.16 1/2 a bushel; 
September oats were 1 3/4 cents lower at 1.07 1/4 a bushel; August 
soybeans were 8 1/2 cents higher at $4.64 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Cattle and hog futures prices were mixed in trading on the  
Chicago Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Hog futures prices were lower as supplies remain strong as  
consumer demand wanes. Pork belly futures prices were lower on the 
expectation the USDA's monthly cold storage report, out Friday, 
will show more pork bellies in storage than had been anticipated. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle were unchanged at 66.35 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle were .17 cent higher at 77.37 cents a pound; October 
lean hogs were 1.57 cents lower at 43.85 cents a pound; August pork 
bellies were 1.90 cents lower at 51.40 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
