<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Son of Sam Killer in CNN Interview </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Son of Sam killer David Berkowitz never meant to  
threaten Spike Lee's family and has only good wishes for the maker 
of a film that reminded the public of his infamous crimes, 
Berkowitz said in an interview broadcast Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	When Berkowitz mentioned Lee's wife and family by name in a  
recent New York Times article, Lee said he read the comments as a 
veiled threat against his wife and children. 
</P>
<P>
	``Concerning Mr. Lee's family, I was misquoted totally,''  
Berkowitz said in an hourlong prison interview on ``Larry King 
Live'' on CNN. ``I don't monitor anything about his family, I pray 
for them, I have absolutely nothing against Mr. Lee, and I never 
said anything bad about him. I pray that God blesses him in every 
area of his life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A call to a spokeswoman for The New York Times Monday night was  
not immediately returned. A call to the office of Lee's film 
company also was not returned. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee's movie ``Summer of Sam'' recreated the steamy, turbulent  
summer of 1977, when New Yorkers sweated through a record-setting 
heat wave, endured a citywide blackout and read tabloid stories 
about a serial killer who sent taunting notes signed ``Son of 
Sam.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Berkowitz killed six people and wounded seven in his yearlong  
crime spree, which ended that July. He confessed after his arrest 
and claimed he'd been ordered to kill by the dog of a neighbor 
named Sam. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he had not seen Lee's movie and was pleased that the  
flurry of media attention it brought him had subsided. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm glad that's out of my life, at least for a while,'' he  
said. ``I'm not living in the past anymore.'' The interview was 
taped last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Now serving his life sentence at the Sullivan Correctional  
Facility in the Catskill Mountains, Berkowitz, 46, helps counsel 
other inmates and tries to teach them religion. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
