<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tagliabue Monitoring Jets Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. (AP) -- NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue, visiting  
the New York Jets' training camp Tuesday, said he is keeping close 
tabs on the pending sale of the team but isn't sure how long it 
will take for a deal to be completed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to try to get an update this week when I meet with  
John Hess and get a status report of where they are,'' Tagliabue 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hess, the son of the club's late owner, Leon Hess, is helping  
supervise the sale. Leon Hess died in May. 
</P>
<P>
	Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., which is handling the screening of  
prospective buyers, has been working to finalize a prospectus for 
interested investors. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jets are expected to be sold for more than $500 million.  
</P>
<P>
	``With this team, and with other teams, you're looking for  
someone with a vision of the future who is looking for the 
long-term,'' Tagliabue said. ``You need someone coming in for the 
long-term with a vision for what the Jets could be in New York, and 
for New York sports fans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of the peripheral issues surrounding the sale is where the  
Jets will play once the club's lease with Giants Stadium in East 
Rutherford, N.J., expires in 2007. Several groups have appealed to 
potential owners to return the franchise to New York, specifically 
Long Island. 
</P>
<P>
	``Leon Hess talked to me about that early this spring,''  
Tagliabue said. ``Obviously, anytime you can get a new stadium and 
one that would be really convenient to Jets' fans and a facility 
for the Jets, it would be attractive. But you also have to be 
realistic and know how it's going to be. In all likelihood, it 
would be a part of something bigger like a convention complex or 
some other multipurpose complex.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jets president Steve Gutman is representing the Hess family in  
dealing with Goldman Sachs on the ballclub's sale. Gutman declined 
to comment Monday on the situation. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Jets have been, as you would expect, very cooperative and  
we've had a good working relationship with Steve Gutman,'' 
Tagliabue said. ``We've also had a number of good discussions with 
John Hess. Everyone understands that if this process goes smoothly, 
it will be important to the league and important for the Jets. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would say that with an executive like John Hess in the mix,  
representing the family in effect, and Steve Gutman representing 
the team, we think that this will work very smoothly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tagliabue also addressed the pending legal action against  
veteran Jets offensive tackle Jumbo Elliott, who faces criminal 
charges stemming from a brawl at a Long Beach, N.Y., bar in July. 
Elliott, arrested for disorderly conduct, public lewdness, 
second-degree harassment and third-degree assault, is scheduled to 
be in court at Long Beach on Sept. 13. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anytime a player like Jumbo Elliott and other players get  
involved in these types of allegations, you are disappointed 
because you don't want that type of allegation made about a 
player,'' said Tagliabue, who may discipline Elliott under the 
league's new violent crime policy. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of it, at this stage, seems to depend on how the civil  
authorities will deal with it, and then our timetable (for 
disciplinary action) would have to kick in after that.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
