<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Aug. 17, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	1,000 Said Dead in Turkey Quake  
</P>
<P>
	ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) -- Turkish government officials say 1,000  
people are dead and thousands injured after a powerful earthquake 
rocked western Turkey early this morning. The quake, measured at 
7.8, struck at 3 a.m. local time (8 p.m. EDT Monday), catching most 
people asleep in their beds. Some ran into the street in panic, 
others were crushed in the rubble. Dozens of buildings and highway 
overpasses collapsed in Istanbul, state TV said. Private NTV 
television said 160 sailors were reported dead from the collapse of 
two navy buildings in the town of Golcuk. Authorities said at least 
156 people were killed in Istanbul alone. 

</P>
<P>
	Photographers Not Blamed for Diana  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- France's state prosecutor's office said today it  
found no evidence to prove that chasing photographers were directly 
responsible for the car crash that killed Princess Diana. The 
prosecutor's office said it sent a recommendation to the 
investigating judge that charges be dismissed against the nine 
photographers and a press motorcyclist implicated in the crash. The 
photographers and the motorcyclist were placed under investigation 
shortly after the Aug. 31, 1997, crash that killed Diana, her 
boyfriend Dodi Fayed and their driver, Henri Paul. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Unveils School Violence Ad  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Three new public service announcements urging  
parents to talk to their children about violence will be unveiled 
today by President Clinton. The messages, to debut tomorrow on 
major broadcast and cable television networks, include a toll-free 
number to call for a free booklet on how to talk to children, 
especially those aged 8 to 12, about safety and the dangers of 
weapons and of gang violence. One TV ad begins with a school bell 
ringing. It ends with Clinton saying, ``Our children need our 
help.'' In between, students chat about knives in book bags and 
their personal safety at school. 

</P>
<P>
	Scores Hold Steady on College Test  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Scores on one of the key college entrance  
exams held steady this year. A report on the 1999 ACT exam finds 
the average score was 21 out of a possible 36, the same as last 
year. A decade ago, the average score was 20.6. The ACT measures 
English, math, reading and science skills. It's taken by 1 million 
American high school students, mostly in the west and south. 
Results from the other major college entrance exam, the SAT, will 
be released later this month. 

</P>
<P>
	Poll: Many OK With Racial Separation  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- About half the young adults in a recent poll  
said racial separation in America is all right ``as long as 
everyone has equal opportunity.'' The poll, released yesterday by 
Hamilton College, also found that 56 percent said the federal 
government should make sure black people receive fair treatment in 
jobs, and about 57 percent agreed that generations of slavery and 
discrimination have created conditions that make it difficult for 
blacks to work their way out of the lower class. 

</P>
<P>
	New Home Construction Rebounds  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Construction of new homes and apartments,  
which fell 5.8 percent in June, rebounded in July, reflecting 
continued strength in the U.S. housing sector despite rising 
mortgage rates. The Commerce Department reported today that new 
home construction rose 5.7 percent. Meanwhile, rates on a 30-year 
fixed mortgage soared to 8.15 percent, the highest in more than two 
years. The National Association of Home Builders said that some 
builders are concerned that rising interest rates are starting to 
affect buyer demand, which had been robust earlier this year. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 37  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 11 a.m. EDT, the Dow industrials  
were up 37.68 to 11,084.47. Advancing issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led decliners 1,425-985. The Nasdaq was up 12.60 to 
2,657.88. 

</P>
<P>
	Suzuki To Sponsor Heisman Trophy  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Fans will be able to have a say, albeit a small  
say, in next year's Heisman Trophy voting. The Downtown Athletic 
Club, which presents college football's most prestigious individual 
award, entered into a three-year $1.5 million deal with American 
Suzuki in a deal that allows fans to vote by visiting Suzuki 
dealers. The votes won't count for much, though. All Suzuki voters 
together will get just one vote. Sports writers, sports 
broadcasters, some coaches and former Heisman Trophy winners get 
992. The Japanese car maker will spend $35 million over three years 
with Time Warner in a marketing partnership to promote the award. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
