<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-17 21:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex Mich St. Football Player Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- Dimitrius Underwood, the first-round  
draft pick from Michigan State who left the Minnesota Vikings 
training camp and was later released, was arrested and briefly held 
Tuesday on a warrant over a parking ticket, campus police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood, 22, was arrested about 2:20 a.m. on the Michigan  
State campus for a traffic violation, said Lt. John McCandless of 
the campus Department of Public Safety. 
</P>
<P>
	Campus police learned that warrants issued in Lansing were  
pending against Underwood and a passenger in his vehicle. Both were 
turned over to Lansing police, McCandless said. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood paid a $150 fine and was released from the city jail  
shortly afterward, Lansing police Lt. Ray Hall told television 
station WLAJ. Neither McCandless nor Hall would identify the person 
arrested with Underwood or say what that person was charged with. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite missing his entire senior season with a sprained ankle,  
the Vikings made Underwood their top draft pick, and 29th overall, 
in April. 
</P>
<P>
	He signed a five-year, $5.3 million contract with the Vikings on  
Aug. 1, but walked out of training camp the next day. Underwood, 
who couldn't be located for days, met Aug. 10 with Minnesota coach 
Dennis Green and, according to the club, ``told Coach Green that he 
has no desire to play football and has decided not to play for the 
Vikings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Miami Dolphins claimed Underwood off waivers Monday,  
although team officials said they weren't sure if he would play 
this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood explained his departure from the Vikings' camp by  
saying he was torn between a desire to pursue the ministry and the 
need to support his family, including his 16-month-old twins who 
live in Michigan with his former girlfriend. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
