<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990817.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-17 01:30:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Island Evacuated As Hurricane Nears </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JOHNSTON ISLAND (AP) -- Anticipating a direct hit from a  
weakening hurricane, the U.S. Army evacuated most of the 1,300 
military and civilian personnel from this small central Pacific 
island where a chemical weapons incineration facility is located. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials closed tanks and lines in the incinerator and secured  
the rest of the weapons in storm-proof bunkers as Hurricane Dora 
approached the island, part of a four-island atoll located 825 
miles southwest of Honolulu. 
</P>
<P>
	The storm was expected to pass 7 miles north of the island later  
tonight, close enough for National Weather Service forecaster Jeff 
Powell to call it a direct hit. 
</P>
<P>
	The Army was to decide today whether to remove about 200 workers  
who were not evacuated Monday, said spokesman John Fairbank. 
</P>
<P>
	Evacuees were taken to Hickam Air Force Base near Honolulu.  
</P>
<P>
	Also being evacuated were workers from the U.S. Fish and  
Wildlife Service, which operates a bird refuge on the atoll. 
</P>
<P>
	Hurricane Dora has maximum sustained winds of about 85 miles per  
hour with some higher gusts, but further weakening was expected 
before the storm hits the island, said weather service forecaster 
Hans Rosendal. 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasters predicted waves of up to 12 feet, raising concerns  
about flooding on the island, which has a high point of 7 feet. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're not worried so much about winds as they are concerned  
about storm surge and seas,'' Powell said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
