<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Aug. 17, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	1,100 Said Dead in Turkey Quake  
</P>
<P>
	ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) -- The worst recorded earthquake to hit  
western Turkey killed at least 1,100 people and injured thousands 
today, destroying buildings and cutting off power and water to 
millions living along the heavily populated Bosporus Strait. By 
late afternoon, the crisis center at the prime minister's office 
had tallied 1,169 dead and 5,550 injured. The numbers were expected 
to rise. The quake struck at 3 a.m. local time (8 p.m. EDT Monday), 
catching most people asleep. Dozens of buildings and highway 
overpasses collapsed in Istanbul, state TV said. Many roads were 
severely damaged and unpassable. ``There could be as many as 10,000 
people under the debris,'' said Mayor Ismail Baris. 

</P>
<P>
	FDA Restricts Blood Donations  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Food and Drug Administration ruled today  
that Americans who visited Britain frequently at the height of that 
country's mad-cow-disease scare will be banned from donating blood 
back home. The FDA decision affects Americans who have spent a 
total of six months in Britain since 1980. There is no evidence 
that any mad-cow-type illness has been spread through blood 
transfusions. But because mad-cow disease has been linked to a 
human brain destroyer in Britain, federal health officials decided 
the blood donor ban was an appropriate precaution. 

</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gorbachev's Slightly Better  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Raisa Gorbachev, the wife of former Soviet leader  
Mikhail Gorbachev, was in slightly better condition today at the 
hospital where she is being treated for leukemia, a spokesman at 
her husband's foundation said. Mrs. Gorbachev, 67, is undergoing 
chemotherapy. Mrs. Gorbachev, 67, was one of the most unpopular 
figures of the former Soviet Union, widely resented for her 
perceived flamboyance. 

</P>
<P>
	South Korea Conducts Air Raid Drill  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- With North Korea threatening to test a  
new long-range missile, South Korea conducted an air raid drill 
today and the military simulated a response to a chemical attack. 
During the exercise, a dozen military helicopters and vehicles 
rushed to wash down an eight-lane boulevard in southern Seoul that 
was ``contaminated'' in the simulated attack. Others rescued 
injured civilians while special forces troops recovered a 
government building supposedly occupied by a group of North Korean 
soldiers. Some U.S. and South Korean officials believe North Korea 
is using the threat of a missile launch to extract economic and 
other concessions in exchange for shelving the test. 

</P>
<P>
	State Won't Have To Defend Nichols  
</P>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- A judge ruled today that the Oklahoma's  
state public defender agency won't have to defend Terry Nichols in 
a state bombing trial and said private attorneys should be hired to 
represent Nichols with payment from the state court fund. Nichols 
already is serving a life prison sentence on federal convictions 
stemming from the April 1995 blast at the Alfred P. Murrah Federal 
Building, which killed 168 people. In the state trial, he could 
face the death penalty. Jim Bednar, executive director of the 
Oklahoma Indigent Defense System, had asked to be let out of 
representing Nichols because the agency didn't have the money to 
defend him. 

</P>
<P>
	Ford Tests Hydrogen-Powered Engine  
</P>
<P>
	DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) -- Ford is working on a hydrogen-powered  
internal combustion engine that it says could be a cleaner-burning 
alternative to the gasoline engine until automakers perfect a 
fuel-cell powertrain. Ford officials say the engine, a modified 
version of Ford's 2-liter Zetec four-cylinder gasoline engine, 
promises 25 percent to 30 percent better fuel efficiency. The 
company plans to begin road-testing later this year. The fuel-cell 
powertrain engine produce electricity from an electrochemical 
reaction between hydrogen and oxygen; the only emission is water. 
Experts say a breakthrough on fuel-cell production is at least a 
decade off. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 1.58  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 2 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
down 1.58 to 11,045.21. Advancing issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led decliners 1,545-1,326. The Nasdaq was up 6.60 to 
2,651.88. 

</P>
<P>
	Eagles Sign Kicker Norm Johnson  
</P>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The Philadelphia Eagles today released  
kicker Chris Boniol and signed veteran Norm Johnson to a two-year 
contract. Johnson, 39, played the last four years with Pittsburgh. 
The 18-year veteran enters the 1999 season having made an 
NFL-record 276 consecutive extra-point attempts, and is sixth on 
the NFL's all-time scoring list with 1,657 points. Boniol hit 14 of 
21 FGs last season. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  
  	   	
</P>
