<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley Touts Gun, Hate Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Tougher gun and hate-crime laws coupled with  
greater social responsibility are needed to fight the kind of 
violence that overtook parts of Los Angeles last week, Democratic 
presidential candidate Bill Bradley said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to see it in a broader context,'' Bradley said.  
``There are too many places this could strike if we don't have a 
broader social response.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley spoke from New Jersey via video teleconferencing  
devices. He joined a dozen political, community and religious 
leaders on a panel at a town hall meeting titled ``Seeking 
Solutions: When Hate Turns into Violence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The forum, which was broadcast live on radio, was sparked by the  
shooting rampage Aug. 10 at the North Valley Jewish Community 
Center where three children attending day camp, a 16-year-old 
counselor and a 68-year-old receptionist were wounded. 
</P>
<P>
	The suspect, white supremacist Buford O. Furrow, 37, was  
arrested in the center shooting and the killing of a postal worker 
the following day in Las Vegas. He remained jailed Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley said he supports new gun laws that would require taking  
a safety course before purchasing a gun and would prohibit gun 
dealers in residential neighborhoods. His suggestion that new laws 
are needed drew boos from several crowd members. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
