<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Many OK With Racial Separation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- About half the young adults in a recent poll  
said racial separation in America is all right ``as long as 
everyone has equal opportunity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The poll released Monday in Washington by Hamilton College of  
Clinton, N.Y., found 50 percent of respondents strongly or somewhat 
agreed with the statement: ``It's OK if the races are basically 
separate from one another as long as everyone has equal 
opportunities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, 47 percent of those polled disagreed strongly  
or somewhat with the statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll, co-sponsored by the NAACP and Zogby International,  
surveyed 1001 randomly selected people ages 18 to 29 over one week 
in April and had a margin of error of plus or minus 3 percentage 
points. 
</P>
<P>
	Among other poll findings:  
</P>
<P>
	--Some 56 percent said the federal government should make sure  
black people receive fair treatment in jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	--About 57 percent agreed that generations of slavery and  
discrimination have created conditions that make it difficult for 
blacks to work their way out of the lower class. 
</P>
<P>
	--Some 54 percent said it was unlikely the United States would  
elect a black president in the near future. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
