<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-17 07:40:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  700 May Be Dead in Turkey Quake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) -- Rescuers dug frantically with their bare  
hands today to free people trapped in the rubble of a massive 
earthquake that rocked western Turkey's biggest cities, with 
unofficial estimates saying at least 700 people were killed and 
thousands injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Private NTV television said 160 sailors were reported dead from  
the collapse of two navy buildings in the town of Golcuk. 
Authorities said at least 156 people were killed in Istanbul alone, 
where 3,721 people were injured, the semi-official Anatolia news 
agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	The quake struck at 3 a.m. local time (8 p.m. EDT Monday),  
catching most people asleep in their beds. The lucky ones ran into 
the street in panic, others were crushed in the rubble. 
</P>
<P>
	Many people fled their homes in night clothes and without shoes.  
Later they walked through the glass-strewn streets with cloth 
wrapped around their feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Dozens of buildings and highway overpasses collapsed in  
Istanbul, state TV said. 
</P>
<P>
	Residents used car headlights to work in the predawn hours,  
while the young and elderly slept in the open. One elderly man was 
filmed by Turkish television reading from the Koran, the Muslim 
holy book, in front of a truck. 
</P>
<P>
	The hardest-hit area appeared to be around the industrial city  
of Izmit, where an oil refinery was in flames. Thick black smoke 
filled the morning sky as firefighters struggled to contain the 
huge flames. 
</P>
<P>
	Ali Pinar, an official from the Istanbul-based Kandilli  
observatory, said Izmit, also known as Kocaeli, is located on a 
quake-prone fault line. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 100 people in addition to the 160 sailors were believed  
killed in Golcuk, near Izmit and 80 miles southeast of Istanbul. 
</P>
<P>
	``We fear that there are many more under the rubble,'' said  
Mayor Ismail Baris. 
</P>
<P>
	With the city's resources exhausted, it was mostly neighbors and  
relatives that fought to pull people from the wreckage. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe that the loss of lives will be huge,'' Prime  
Minister Bulent Ecevit said. But he added: ``God willing, we will 
not be faced with a picture as bad as we fear.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The National Earthquake Information Center in Golden, Colo.,  
said the quake had a magnitude of 7.8, making it nearly as powerful 
as the 7.9-magnitude San Francisco quake in 1906, which killed 700 
people. The quake occurred at a relatively shallow six miles below 
the surface. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 250 aftershocks followed, the Kandilli observatory  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, who was in Istanbul for  
talks on Caspian Sea oil and gas pipeline projects, was unhurt, as 
was Gen. Henry Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, who 
was visiting Ankara. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson told reporters the United States had offered  
assistance and was waiting for Turkey to assess what it needs. He 
called the quake ``devastating.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Forty-five seconds worth of very violent shaking in our hotel  
room, myself and my staff. It was very violent shaking and we were 
able to observe the darkness of the earthquake, people streaming 
into the streets. Lights going out in Istanbul,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan and Switzerland immediately dispatched teams to help with  
the rescue operation, NTV said. Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy 
said its army rescue unit was on alert and told Turkish authorities 
it could be sent immediately. 
</P>
<P>
	In a show of support for its traditional rival, Greek Premier  
Costas Simitis ordered his nation's emergency services to be placed 
on alert today to help Turkey deal with the earthquake. 
</P>
<P>
	An air force cargo plane was being loaded with special  
earthquake rescue and medical teams -- including sniffer dogs -- and 
emergency supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	Turkish television showed rescuers digging with their bare hands  
in the rubble, trying to free survivors. Hospitals were 
overwhelmed. 
</P>
<P>
	``They can hear the voices of my mother and sister but know  
nothing about my father and brother,'' said Arsu Yilmaz as she 
watched rescue workers digging at a building in Avcilar district. A 
5-year-old girl was extracted from the rubble unharmed. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirty people were reported dead in the western city of Bolu,  
Anatolia said. 
</P>
<P>
	NTV said hospitals were turning away people with minor injuries  
in Izmit and treating people on sidewalks. Medical workers were 
reportedly breaking pharmacy windows to get supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	When the temblor struck, thousands headed for the relative  
safety of the open street. 
</P>
<P>
	``We saw the floor move, we all ran out of the house,'' said  
Ramazan Aydeniz, sitting in front of his ice cream shop in 
Istanbul. ``The kids, the elder were all in a panic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There was no visible damage to Istanbul's treasured historic  
sites, including the Blue Mosque, the nearly 1,500-year-old Saint 
Sophia or Topkapi Palace, the seat of the Ottoman sultans. Tens of 
thousands of tourists visit them each summer. 
</P>
<P>
	``We stayed in bed while everybody else got out. Then there were  
aftershocks and they asked us to evacuate the hotel,'' said Fiona 
Spearman, a British tourist from Oxford, as she sipped tea at an 
outdoor cafe across from the Blue Mosque. 
</P>
<P>
	The quake also shook the capital Ankara, 270 miles to the east.  
There were no immediate reports of damage or injury there, although 
power outages were experienced in some areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Telephone and electrical service was cut in several areas as the  
quake struck, broadcast reports said. Vehicles on the main highway 
linking Istanbul and Ankara reportedly slammed into each other 
during the earthquake. 
</P>
<P>
	A 6.3-magnitude quake that hit Turkey on June 27, 1998, killed  
144 people and injured more than 1,500 in and around the southern 
city of Adana. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990817.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-17 07:40:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
