<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Broncos' Elam Still Seeks Shoe Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREELEY, Colo. (AP) -- It appears Jason Elam still needs to pad  
his resume. Maybe fudge a few numbers. Drop a few names. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite an NFL record-tying 63-yard field goal, two Super Bowl  
rings, two Pro Bowl trips and six game-winning kicks, the Denver 
Broncos kicker can't find anybody to endorse his phenomenal foot. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't even get a shoe deal,'' Elam said Tuesday. ``I'm not  
with Nike anymore. Adidas won't even return my phone calls. I can 
get hat deals and all these other kind of deals. You'd think the 
most logical one would be a shoe deal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Elam has only himself to blame. Had he not kicked his way into  
the record book against Jacksonville last Oct. 25, Elam would still 
be using the kangaroo-skin Nike Tiempos he has favored since high 
school. 
</P>
<P>
	Nike has since redesigned the Tiempo, and Elam's last pair of  
originals went to the Pro Football Hall of Fame, along with the 
ball he kicked through the uprights to tie Tom Dempsey for the 
longest field goal in NFL history. 
</P>
<P>
	``The timing was perfect, and he ended up crushing it,'' said  
Tom Rouen, Elam's holder. ``I just remember the sound it made. It 
had that definite thud to it. When I looked up, it was heading 
straight down the pipe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wayward kicks have been rare for Elam. In six NFL seasons, he  
has made 115 of 120 field goal attempts inside 40 yards, and he has 
converted 259 of 260 point-after attempts in the regular season. 
</P>
<P>
	The streak of PATs currently stands at a franchise-record 235  
and means nearly as much to Elam as his memorable field goal. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to make every kick inside of 40, and the ones over 40,  
I'm not going to get that upset with myself if I miss from time to 
time,'' he said. ``I want to be consistent. I don't really care 
about making a 63 and coming back and missing a 28. I don't want to 
be that kind of kicker.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Accuracy aside, Elam will be best remembered for 63 yards just  
as Mark McGwire is known for 70 home runs. 
</P>
<P>
	``People that didn't know me before probably heard about it,''  
Elam said. ``Anybody that I meet now, that's usually the first 
thing out of their mouth. `Nice 63-yarder.' It's fun, though. I've 
enjoyed it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Like McGwire being chased by Sammy Sosa, Elam has his own  
pursuers and doesn't expect his record to stand alone like 
Dempsey's did for 28 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Among Elam's choices to go long sometime soon: John Hall of the  
New York Jets, Brad Daluiso of the New York Giants and John Kasay 
of the Carolina Panthers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be broken. It's not going to be another 28 years  
before it's broken,'' Elam said. ``There's just too many good guys 
that are capable of doing it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rouen wouldn't be surprised if it is his teammate who rewrites  
the record book. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think there's definitely a possibility,'' Rouen said. ``This  
time, if we do it, I think we'd back it up a yard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even if they don't get another historic chance, Elam and Rouen  
at least have the memory of watching the ball sail through the 
uprights in the north end zone at Mile High Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I'm walking out on the field, I'll just kind of gaze at  
that spot on the left hash mark at the 47-yard line,'' Elam said. 
``I think about it a lot, but I think about a lot of the ones that 
I missed, too.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990817.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-17 16:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rockies Owners Sued Over Trustee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- A lawsuit filed in U.S. Bankruptcy Court accuses  
the Colorado Rockies of failing to cooperate with a bankrupt 
trustee who is trying to sell a multimillion-dollar stake in the 
team. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit was filed Monday on behalf of the trust liquidating  
the assets of Oren Benton, a former Denver uranium trader and 
former Rockies partner. The defendants are Rockies managing general 
partner Jerry McMorris and general partners Dick and Charlie 
Monfort. 
</P>
<P>
	Trustee David Beckman cited several complaints against McMorris  
and the Monforts, the most crucial being their decision to reject, 
on the grounds of conflicts of interest, a number of individuals or 
groups considering buying the 23.7 percent stake once owned by 
Benton. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have been overly patient making sincere efforts to work  
with the other owners to sell our significant ownership in the 
team,'' Beckman said in a statement. ``Unfortunately, we have 
concluded that McMorris and the Monforts have at every turn been 
aggressively uncooperative, seemingly in an attempt to force a sale 
of our ownership share back to them at a ridiculously low price.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The suit accuses McMorris and the Monforts of failing to pay any  
annual profits to the two Benton trusts and of providing only 
sparse and late information about the team's finances. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm as confident as I'm standing here that our cooperation has  
been 100 percent,'' McMorris said. 
</P>
<P>
	Both sides acknowledge McMorris made an offer to buy the Benton  
stake two years ago. Seeking more money for the trusts, Beckman 
hired the investment banking firm Warburg Dillon Read to seek 
prospective bidders. 
</P>
<P>
	McMorris said one of the bidders had ties to Ascent  
Entertainment Group, the Denver pay-per-view company that recently 
agreed to sell the Denver Nuggets, the Colorado Avalanche and the 
Pepsi Center for $461 million to Denver telecommunications magnate 
Donald Sturm. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990817.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-17 11:50:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ravens Sign Quarterback Stoney Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WESTMINSTER, Md. (AP) -- The Baltimore Ravens signed quarterback  
Stoney Case to a one-year, $400,000 contract Tuesday and promised 
him ample opportunity to move up from No. 4 on the depth chart. 
</P>
<P>
	Case, 29, was cut last week by the Indianapolis Colts. He went  
through his first practice with the Ravens on Tuesday, working 
behind quarterbacks Scott Mitchell, Tony Banks and Wally 
Richardson. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had a couple other opportunities, but I like this team and  
the direction they're going in,'' Case said. ``It's one of those 
things where I had to make a good decision, and hopefully this is 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Case was drafted in the third round in 1995 by the Arizona  
Cardinals. He has played in four games, starting one, and has not 
thrown a pass in an NFL game since 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Case was the third-string quarterback in Arizona last season. He  
signed a two-year, $2 million contract with Indianapolis that 
included a $500,000 signing bonus, but the Colts released him last 
Wednesday after signing Steve Walsh as a backup to Peyton Manning. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990817.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-17 10:22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Israeli Soldiers Killed in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MARKABA, Lebanon (AP) -- Hezbollah guerrillas clashed with  
Israeli troops in southern Lebanon today, killing two Israeli 
soldiers and wounding six others in retaliation for the death of a 
Hezbollah commander, security officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Israel sent its air force on two bombing runs during the fierce  
artillery, mortar and rocket battles, which raged for nearly four 
hours in Wadi Slouki, a valley in a no-man's land across from the 
Israeli-occupied zone in southern Lebanon. 
</P>
<P>
	Israeli jets fired two missiles at the area, which is believed  
to be used by Hezbollah guerrillas as a base to launch attacks on 
Israeli troops and their allied Lebanese militiamen in the occupied 
zone. There was no word on casualties from the airstrikes. 
</P>
<P>
	Wadi Slouki lies between the village of Khirbet Silim and the  
villages of Houla and Markaba, about two miles from the Israeli 
border. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no immediate confirmation from Israel on its  
casualties or on the fighting, the most serious since Israeli air 
raids killed 10 Lebanese people in June. 
</P>
<P>
	If confirmed, the Israeli combat fatalities would be the first  
in Lebanon since Prime Minister Ehud Barak took office in July 
would certainly increase calls in Israel for a withdrawal. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking in the southern Israeli town of Beersheba, Barak  
referred to the escalation in Lebanon and suggested the fighting 
``will be what makes it possible in the end to remove the Israeli 
army from Lebanon by agreement and deploy it on the international 
border.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barak has pledged to pull the army out of Lebanon within a year.  
</P>
<P>
	An Israeli army spokesman in Jerusalem said its jets attacked  
guerrilla targets, destroying a Hezbollah gun and towing vehicle. 
There was no independent confirmation that any guerrilla targets 
were hit. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lebanese security officials, speaking on customary condition  
of anonymity, said the Israeli casualties were airlifted by 
military helicopter to Israel. 
</P>
<P>
	The exchanges started several bush fires in nearby hills and  
valleys, sending clouds of heavy smoke in the air. 
</P>
<P>
	The Iranian-backed Hezbollah group said its guerrillas launched  
a series of attacks on Israeli troops and allied militiamen in Wadi 
Slouki to retaliate for the death of Hezbollah commander Ali Hassan 
Deeb, better known as Abu Hassan, who was killed in a roadside bomb 
explosion in the southern port city of Sidon on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hezbollah and the Lebanese government blamed Israel for the  
bombing, although no one has claimed responsibility. 
</P>
<P>
	``This crime will not go unpunished. The enemy will regret his  
action,'' Sheik Nabil Kaouk, the Hezbollah commander in southern 
Lebanon, said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The blood of martyred commanders will only boost the Islamic  
Resistance (Hezbollah's) determination, strength and 
effectiveness,'' said a Hezbollah statement today. 
</P>
<P>
	Israeli television said Monday that Abu Hassan was on the top of  
Israel's most wanted list for carrying out attacks against Israeli 
soldiers in southern Lebanon. 
</P>
<P>
	Israel's army chief of staff, Lt. Gen. Shaul Mofaz, suggested  
today that Abu Hassan's death was the result of a power struggle 
among the guerrillas themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not in the habit of interfering in the internal rivalry  
between the terrorist organizations in Lebanon,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy, asked whether Israel played  
any role in the killing, said: ``Things happen there every day, and 
Israel does not have to comment on everything that happens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the English-language Daily Star reported today that a  
Lebanese army soldier assigned to protect Parliament Speaker Nabih 
Berri, has been detained on suspicion of spying for Israel. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper quoted unnamed security sources as saying adjutant  
Hussein Olayan was apprehended Aug. 9 for his contacts with agents 
of Israel's Mossad intelligence service. 
</P>
<P>
	A statement from Berri's Amal militia movement said Olayan was  
called in for questioning after a surveillance operation ``reached 
a stage of confirming suspicions'' about him. 
</P>
<P>
	Lebanese army officials have not confirmed the arrest.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
