<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-17 12:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton Presents School Violence Ad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton introduced three new public  
service announcements Tuesday urging parents to talk with their 
children about violence. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our children need our help to deal with tough issues like  
violence. Please talk with your kids,'' Clinton says in one of the 
spots. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton used an event announcing the ads to renew his call for  
new gun control laws. 
</P>
<P>
	No law can stop every madman with a gun, he said, but sensible  
gun control will save lives and make children safer at school. 
Reducing the ``appalling ease'' with which young people can get 
guns is essential to cutting youth violence, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gun control opponents in Congress and the National Rifle  
Association claim it would be ineffective to require trigger locks 
or to close what the Clinton administration calls ``the gun-show 
loophole'' that allows for no-questions-asked purchases of some 
guns. 
</P>
<P>
	``No law can stop every disturbed person from committing a  
violent act with a gun, but we would never do anything as a people 
if we gave in to our objections that all of our actions would have 
less than a 100 percent impact,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	The president and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton presented  
the three frank back-to-school messages in the aftermath of 
shooting sprees in high schools in Colorado and Georgia and copycat 
threats and violence that followed in schools elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration also pledged $15 million in Justice  
Department community policing grants to focus on crime and violence 
in or near schools. 
</P>
<P>
	The messages, debuting Wednesday on major broadcast and cable  
television networks, include a toll-free number to call for a free 
booklet on how to talk to children, especially those ages 8 to 12, 
about safety and the dangers of weapons and gang violence. Similar 
radio ads are to air later this month. 
</P>
<P>
	The ads were paid for by the Henry J. Kaiser Family Foundation,  
an independent health care philanthropy based in Menlo Park, 
Calif., and Children Now, an independent advocacy group for 
children in Oakland, Calif. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990817.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-17 18:10:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Browns, Fans Impressed With New Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- The Cleveland Browns packed up their equipment,  
boarded buses and went on their shortest trip of the season Tuesday 
-- just up the road to play in their brand new home. 
</P>
<P>
	Actually, it took them three years to get there.  
</P>
<P>
	The players got to practice in the new Cleveland Browns Stadium  
for the first time on Tuesday, a dress rehearsal for Saturday 
night's exhibition game against the Minnesota Vikings. 
</P>
<P>
	As workers continued putting the finishing touches on the  
state-of-the-art, 72,000-seat facility, the Browns took the field 
for their afternoon practice after working out in the morning at 
their training facility in Berea. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's beautiful,'' linebacker Chris Spielman said after coming  
off the Browns' home field. ``I can't believe there's this many 
people here for a practice. The turf is great and I can't wait 
until we can get started for real.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neither can Browns fans.  
</P>
<P>
	A crowd estimated at 25,000 watched the team run through its  
drills for two hours. They roared as the Browns defense jogged 
toward the famed Dawg Pound, Cleveland's rabid bleacher section of 
10,000 which has been replicated and remodeled in the new stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Cornerback Corey Fuller and safety Tim McTyer even christened  
the Dawg Pound by diving over the 7-foot-walls into the crowd, 
giving a Cleveland twist to Green Bay's Lambeau Leap. 
</P>
<P>
	The team used the day, dubbed ``Stadium Sneak Preview'' as a dry  
run for Saturday's game, the first NFL game in Cleveland since Dec. 
17, 1995, just before owner Art Modell took his team to Baltimore. 
</P>
<P>
	Season-ticket holders were invited to the event to check out  
their new seats. Concession areas served hot dogs, burgers and 
beers. Videos were shown on the stadium's two giant scoreboards and 
a high school marching band provided pre-practice entertainment as 
if it were a football Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	For Cleveland fans, Saturday's game will be more than a  
preseason game. It will be a homecoming and the completion of a 
three-year drive to return their beloved Browns to their Lake Erie 
shoreline home. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's gorgeous,'' Browns coach Chris Palmer said.  
``It's a monument to the city of Cleveland for what they've done, 
how they built the stadium and how they brought their team back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Palmer wanted his team to have a test run in the new stadium  
before Saturday's game. He didn't want opening night to overwhelm 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the Browns had not seen the new $283 million stadium,  
built on the same site as the old Cleveland Stadium. Some had 
played in the dingy, dilapidated ballpark, which after being torn 
down was dumped in the lake and is now a reef. 
</P>
<P>
	When the Browns arrived, workers were still affixing the letters  
for the stadium's name on the north side, which as of Tuesday 
afternoon said: CLEV LAND BROWN. 
</P>
<P>
	But once inside, the team and its fans got their first glimpse  
of posh suites, roomy seats -- complete with cup holders -- and 
pristine locker rooms that look like they belong at the local 
country club. 
</P>
<P>
	``You should have heard all the oohs and aahs when the players  
walked in,'' said Dwight Clark, Cleveland's director of football 
operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the Browns were amazed by the home locker room, an  
11,000-square foot space which is the largest in the NFL and has 
multi-colored mosaic tiles in the showers. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're used to a dirty, grungy type atmosphere. It's great in  
there,'' quarterback Ty Detmer said. ``You go in there and there's 
plenty of space for everybody. It's really a great place. You don't 
want to get things dirty.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990817.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-17 07:50:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> racing </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Hostages Said Doing Well </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DUBAI, United Arab Emirates (AP) -- A Spanish hostage held in  
Iran by suspected drug smugglers has called police to say he and 
the other four captives were doing well, a newspaper reported 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The hostage first spoke in Spanish and then in English, the  
Entekhab newspaper said, quoting Mohammad Ali Karimi, a security 
official in the central Iranian province of Kerman where the 
kidnapping took place Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The paper did not give the captive's name.  
</P>
<P>
	The official Islamic Republic News Agency said the kidnappers  
are members of the Baluchi Shah Bakhsh clan. Tribal elders are 
trying to get the five tourists -- three Spaniards, an Italian and 
their Iranian guide -- released, Karimi told IRNA, monitored in 
Dubai. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jomhuri Eslami newspaper said the leader of the kidnappers,  
Nazar Shah Bakhsh, was demanding the release of his brother Ghader 
from prison. The paper quoted Kerman security chief Abbas Doagooie 
as saying the brother was arrested when police smashed a drug ring 
in the area Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Kerman lies on the main route for drug smugglers heading from  
Pakistan and Afghanistan to Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Iran, isolated after its Islamic revolution in 1979, has been  
trying in recent years to promote tourism to boost its faltering 
economy. Hundreds of visitors arrived last week because Iran was 
considered one of the best spots from which to view the last solar 
eclipse of the millennium. 
</P>
<P>
	According to IRNA, Iranian lawmakers are planning to propose a  
law that would toughen punishment for those who attack foreign 
tourists. The report did not provide any further details. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990817.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-17 10:40:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former Cavs Coach Hired by Turner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Mike Fratello, who was fired as coach of the  
Cleveland Cavaliers in June, signed a multi-year deal to return to 
broadcasting with Turner Sports. 
</P>
<P>
	Fratello replaces Doc Rivers, who left Turner to become head  
coach for the Orlando Magic. 
</P>
<P>
	Fratello spent the last six seasons with Cleveland and compiled  
a 248-212 mark before being replaced by Randy Wittman. Fratello led 
the Cavs to the playoffs four times, but had just a 2-12 record in 
the postseason and was unable to advance past the first round. 
</P>
<P>
	Fratello was an NBA analyst for NBC from 1990-93 and worked for  
Turner during the playoffs from 1994-96. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mike is a proven commodity as a television broadcaster,'' said  
Turner executive producer Mike Pearl. ``His 13 years of coaching in 
the NBA give Mike a unique insight into the game that is essential 
in an analyst. He is the perfect addition to our NBA broadcast 
team. 
</P>
<P>
	Fratello was also head coach of the Atlanta Hawks for seven  
seasons, from 1983-1990, compiling a 324-250 record. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990817.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-17 12:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
