<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-17 15:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Soar / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices soared Tuesday, driving yields to  
their lowest point in nearly a month, after a government inflation 
report appeared to reduce the need for the Federal Reserve to hike 
interest rates significantly to cool off the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the 30-year Treasury bond rose 1 1/16 point, or  
$10.62 1/2 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the 
opposite direction, fell to 6.01 percent from 6.08 percent late 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Just a week ago, the 30-year bond yields had moved to 6.27.  
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Department's Consumer Price Index rose 0.3 percent in  
July, boosted by another rise in energy prices. Excluding food and 
energy, core consumer prices rose a more benign 0.2 percent. Both 
increases matched economists' inflation forecasts. 
</P>
<P>
	The modest rise in consumer prices eased concerns that had been  
building in the market that Federal Reserve policy makers would 
raise short-term interest rates by a half-point when they meet next 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	With inflation remaining dormant, more traders now believe the  
Fed will be content to raise the federal funds target rate by a 
quarter-point to 5.25 percent and leave it there through the end of 
the year. Investors previously were anticipating the Fed to raise 
rates twice more this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders don't like higher interest rates because they make fixed  
rate investments like bonds less attractive to investors. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader secondary market, prices of short-term Treasury  
securities were up between up 3/32 point and 5/32 point, and 
intermediate maturities ranged from 1/4 point higher to 21/32 point 
higher, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.81 percent with a  
discount of 4.68 percent, down 0.01 percentage point from late 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Six-month yields were 5.11 percent while the discount was 4.91  
percent, up 0.02 percentage point from late Monday. One-year yields 
were 5.20 percent with a discount of 4.93 percent, down 0.02 
percentage point from Tuesday's Treasury auction. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, fell to 4.93 3/4 percent from 5.19 percent late Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds rose 12/32 point to 113. The average yield 
to maturity was 5.86 percent, down from 5.88 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
