<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-17 09:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Allegedly Preyed on Widows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- A convicted rapist who picked his first  
string of victims from a magazine article chose more recent victims 
by looking at newspaper obituaries for women who had just been 
widowed, prosecutors said. 
</P>
<P>
	In opening statements Monday, Douglas County prosecutor Don  
Kleine said physical evidence, witness testimony and testimony from 
three victims of the previous attacks would prove David Burdette 
raped a 34-year-old woman in Bennington. 
</P>
<P>
	Burdette broke into her home last October, gagged her with her  
late husband's tie and raped her in front of her two young 
children, Kleine said. Her husband had died less than a week 
earlier in a motorcycle accident. 
</P>
<P>
	Burdette, 44, was released from prison last year after serving  
more than 15 years for rape in a series of attacks in 1982. The 
case gained notoriety when officials revealed he had picked his 
victims from an article on Omaha's ``10 Most Eligible Women,'' 
which profiled successful single professional women. 
</P>
<P>
	In the latest case, Burdette is charged with first-degree sexual  
assault, robbery and burglary. He also is being tried on charges of 
attempted sexual assault and burglary in a break-in last fall at a 
home in Omaha. 
</P>
<P>
	If convicted, Burdette faces a mandatory minimum sentence of 25  
years. 
</P>
<P>
	In his opening statement Monday, public defender Tim Burns  
argued that officials had no forensic evidence or fingerprints 
linking Burdette to the assault on the Bennington widow. 
</P>
<P>
	In the other break-in, sheriff's deputies were inside the home  
when they say Burdette entered through an unlocked sliding glass 
door. They believed Burdette had been stalking the woman who lived 
there. She also was a recent widow. 
</P>
<P>
	In that case, Burns said Burdette, who lives in Omaha, was  
trying to burglarize the woman's house and did not intend to 
assault her. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Michael McGill has ruled that three victims in the 1982  
attacks may testify for prosecutors in Burdette's trial, to show 
his pattern of behavior. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, Burdette was found innocent of an assault on a  
31-year-old Bellevue woman in July 1998. The judge in that case 
said police were overzealous, and the woman's identification of 
Burdette as her attacker was tainted. Prosecutors had said he had 
found her through an ad for a moving sale in a local shopper that 
included her address. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990817.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-17 12:40:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Penguins Can Stay Afloat Until Aug. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Mario Lemieux doesn't have to close on his  
plan to buy the bankrupt team by the end of the week because the 
Penguins have enough money to stay afloat through the end of 
August. 
</P>
<P>
	The team's line of credit with a French bank runs out Friday,  
but the Penguins can borrow enough money to keep running if 
Lemieux's deal doesn't close by the end of this week, said James 
Walsh, a bankruptcy lawyer representing the Penguins. 
</P>
<P>
	The team could get more money from Societe Generale, the French  
bank that has financed the team since it filed for bankruptcy in 
October, Walsh said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some loose ends of the financial plan could be tied up Tuesday  
night. The Allegheny Regional Asset District Board was slated to 
vote on whether to earmark sales tax revenue to help the city and 
county pay $16 million in bond debt on the Civic Arena, where the 
Penguins play. 
</P>
<P>
	Two months ago, the Public Auditorium Authority agreed to take  
over debt payments on the Civic Arena owed by the team and the 
arena's landlord, SMG. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Allegheny County Commissioner Bob Cranmer has balked at  
that plan, and his opposition could stall the project. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything is moving in a very positive direction with both  
investors and SMG to bring this deal to completion,'' said Lemieux 
spokesman John Brabender. ``The only concern still ahead is working 
out a new deal with the county that will be to Cranmer's 
satisfaction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gordon St. Denis, director of the sports advisory group at SG  
Cowen, the French bank's subsidiary, said lending officials were 
aware that the deal might not be finalized by the end of the week. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to do whatever is in the best interest to keep the  
franchise in Pittsburgh and maintain the franchise value,'' St. 
Denis said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux needs $50 million in outside private investments to  
finance his takeover. A list circulated to prospective investors 
showed $51.4 million in commitments, but listed $5 million coming 
from a party ``to be announced,'' the Pittsburgh Post-Gazette 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Brabender said that money was in escrow with Lemieux's group and  
represents an actual investor. He was not sure why the investor's 
name had not been listed. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Rooney, nephew of late Pittsburgh Steelers founder Art  
Rooney, Sr., is a candidate to run the Penguins' business 
operations when Lemieux's deal closes. 
</P>
<P>
	Rooney told the Pittsburgh Tribune-Review that he recently  
interviewed with Lemieux. His job title with the team would likely 
be chief operating officer. General manager Craig Patrick would 
continue to run the hockey side of the operation. Lemieux's lawyer, 
Chuck Greenberg, declined comment. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
