<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Declares Law Unconstitutional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- The Ohio Supreme Court has invalidated a  
sweeping overhaul of the state's civil justice system that was 
intended to curb frivolous lawsuits and runaway jury verdicts. 
</P>
<P>
	In a 4-3 decision Monday, the court said the state law that took  
effect in 1977 violates the constitutional separation of powers 
among the three branches of government. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ohio reforms were some of the most far-reaching that have  
been adopted by states under the banner of so-called tort reform. 
</P>
<P>
	The state Legislature ``boldly seized the power of  
constitutional adjudication, appropriated the authority to 
establish rules of court and overruled judicial declarations of 
unconstitutionality,'' Justice Alice Robie Resnick wrote for the 
majority. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents of the law called it an opportunity for businesses,  
hospitals and manufacturers to evade their responsibilities to 
provide safe goods and services. They also said huge jury awards 
attract headlines but are so rare that the law wasn't necessary. 
</P>
<P>
	Backers said the law would lead to lower insurance premiums and  
product costs. Injured Ohioans still would be able to recover the 
costs of medical care, lost wages and other quantifiable damages, 
they said. 
</P>
<P>
	The law limited most non-economic damages at $500,000 and  
punitive damages at $250,000 or three times compensatory damages, 
whichever is greater. Punitive damages are designed to punish a 
defendant's misconduct. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a terrible law, terribly conceived and should never  
have been passed,'' said William Burga, president of the Ohio 
AFL-CIO. The state AFL-CIO and the Ohio Academy of Trial Lawyers 
brought the lawsuit that challenged the law. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrew Doehrel, president of the Ohio Chamber of Commerce, said  
he was ``disappointed and angered'' by the decision and promised to 
make it a campaign issue. 
</P>
<P>
	``This court has simply said, `We're going to run public policy  
in this state,''' he added. ``That's ridiculous.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
