<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jurors See Video of Woman's Daughter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Jurors were riveted Tuesday by a videotape  
deposition of a paralyzed woman, taken just before the removal of 
life support, in which she said her mother didn't mean to shoot her 
when she opened fire. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure it was an accident,'' 42-year-old Georgette Smith  
said in the videotape. ``I know it was. She can't see that good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shirley Egan clasped a wrinkled hand over her mouth and looked  
down in horror Tuesday as the videotape of her daughter was played. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said Ms. Egan opened fire March 8 after hearing her  
daughter and Ms. Smith's boyfriend talking about putting her in a 
nursing home. Ms. Smith was shot in the neck and paralyzed from the 
neck down, left barely able to speak and incapable of swallowing or 
controlling her bladder. 
</P>
<P>
	The hospital-bed deposition of Ms. Smith was taken in May, one  
day before she was taken off life support at her request and died. 
</P>
<P>
	In the deposition, Ms. Smith struggled to pronounce each word,  
but her message was clear. She didn't think her mother had intended 
to shoot her. 
</P>
<P>
	During the 20-minute deposition, a nurse wiped foam from Ms.  
Smith's mouth and a noise from her respirator was audible. Jurors 
watched riveted and glanced at Ms. Egan when Ms. Smith said she 
loved her 68-year-old mother, who sat with her hand over her mouth. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love her dearly,'' Ms. Smith said on the tape. ``She is the  
best friend.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Egan was charged with two counts of attempted murder, for  
wounding her daughter and shooting at the boyfriend, Larry 
Videlock, who was not hit. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys for both sides rested their cases Tuesday. Closing  
arguments were scheduled for Wednesday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Egan's attorney has argued she was on medication that made  
her ``angry, crazy and irrational'' and didn't intend to kill her 
daughter and Videlock. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990817.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-17 19:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Games Pitched Record Set by Oriole </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Jesse Orosco set a major league record Tuesday  
night by pitching in his 1,072nd game, breaking a tie with Dennis 
Eckersley atop the career list. 
</P>
<P>
	Orosco, 42, received a standing ovation from the crowd of 40,485  
at Camden Yards as he stepped to the mound with two outs in the 
seventh inning of the Baltimore Orioles' game against the Minnesota 
Twins. 
</P>
<P>
	Before facing Todd Walker, he waved his cap to the appreciative  
crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just a little bit better having it happen at our own  
ballpark,'' he said before the game. 
</P>
<P>
	Walker, a left-handed batter and the only hitter Orosco faced,  
popped a lazy flyball to center. 
</P>
<P>
	Orosco waved his cap to the crowd upon leaving the mound and  
greeted his family in the front row of the box seats. He was then 
presented the baseball by center fielder Brady Anderson. 
</P>
<P>
	Ironically, Orosco signed with the Twins in 1978 after being  
selected in the second round of the amateur draft. The left-hander 
made his first appearance in the majors the following season with 
the New York Mets and played for the Los Angeles Dodgers, Cleveland 
and Milwaukee before being signed by the Orioles as a free agent in 
April 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Orosco has appeared in 47 games this season, all in relief. He  
hasn't started a game since 1982, for the Mets. Over the past 
several seasons he has been used primarily against left-handed 
batters and usually lasts no more than an inning. 
</P>
<P>
	But that doesn't detract from a feat that represents more than  
two decades of work. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a pretty remarkable record, that's for sure,'' Orioles  
manager Ray Miller said. ``It's something to be proud of, 
especially when you think of how many times he warmed up and didn't 
even get into the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this season, Orosco broke Kent Tekulve's record of  
pitching in 1,050 games in relief. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm definitely proud of both records,'' Orosco said. ``The  
first one meant a lot to me because I'm a reliever. But it's a real 
nice milestone, being the guy with the most games pitched.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although he took a 6.29 ERA into Tuesday's game, Orosco has  
retired 21 of the last 24 batters he faced over 15 appearances. 
</P>
<P>
	His contract runs though next season, and on opening day he will  
become one of a handful of players whose career spanned parts of 
four decades. 
</P>
<P>
	``Until somebody says, `Jess, it's time to hang up the cleats,'  
I'll keep pitching,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
