<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-17 13:10:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> French Banking Deadlock Discussed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- With little hope for a quick settlement, French  
banking officials met Tuesday to try to break a takeover deadlock 
between hostile bidder Banque Nationale de Paris and its unwilling 
target, Societe Generale. 
</P>
<P>
	The meeting, led by Bank of France chairman Jean-Claude Trichet,  
ended without a decision. The officials said in a statement they 
would meet again next week and issue a ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	Three possible scenarios were on the table:  
</P>
<P>
	--BNP, which has a one-third stake in Societe Generale, would be  
allowed to keep its shares and proceed with plans to create the 
world's largest bank in a three-way merger that would also include 
the French bank Paribas 
</P>
<P>
	--BNP would be forced to give up its Societe Generale shares or  
</P>
<P>
	--The big banks would be ordered to the negotiating table.  
</P>
<P>
	BNP had hoped to take over both Paribas and Societe Generale to  
create the world's largest bank with assets of more than $1 
trillion. But it gained only a third of Societe Generale's shares 
and 31.5 percent of its voting rights in a tender offer that ended 
on Friday. BNP did win a clear majority stake in Paribas. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said there were no easy answers to the situation.  
</P>
<P>
	``A quick solution is looking less and less likely,'' said  
Elisabeth Grandin, a banking analyst at Standard and Poor's in 
Paris. ``The authorities will have trouble forcing the banks 
together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Societe Generale Chairman Daniel Bouton said in an interview  
with RTL radio he will continue to resist BNP's unwelcome 
overtures. 
</P>
<P>
	But if regulators side with Societe Generale, they could face  
criticism for having left France's banking system on the sidelines 
of a worldwide wave of consolidation. Siding with BNP also creates 
problems -- officials could be seen as imposing a solution that 
shareholders didn't clearly choose. 
</P>
<P>
	Allowing BNP to retain its stake could also pave the way for a  
lengthy stock market fight. 
</P>
<P>
	French authorities, including Finance Minister Dominique  
Strauss-Kahn, were said to favor BNP's three-way plan because it 
would discourage a takeover by a foreign bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, market players were speculating that BNP might make a  
sweetened offer to Societe Generale's reluctant shareholders, or, 
alternatively, that Societe Generale might line up a white knight, 
or a more acceptable suitor, to ward off BNP. 
</P>
<P>
	Prior to its BNP's $37 billion hostile bid in March, Societe  
Generale and Paribas were heading smoothly toward a merger of their 
own. The takeover battle is the latest example of the rush among 
European businesses to cut merger deals as they try to become more 
competitive in the global market. 
</P>
<P>
	Societe Generale is the largest private-sector bank in France,  
with assets of about $412 billion. BNP is No. 2 at about $349 
billion. Paribas has assets of about $284 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	BNP chairman Michel Pebereau, who argues BNP's stake in Societe  
Generale gives it effective control of the bank, suggested he and 
Bouton should ``sit calmly around a table'' to iron out their 
differences. 
</P>
<P>
	Societe Generale's board said late Tuesday it backed Bouton.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990817.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-17 23:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Project Overstated Savings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Some of the cost savings claimed by Vice  
President Al Gore's project to streamline government were 
overstated, and other cuts in expenses can't be substantiated, 
according to auditors who looked at changes in three agencies. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore's ``reinventing government'' project claimed $21.8 billion  
in savings it lacked evidence to support, inflated savings by 
double-counting cost cuts and took credit for savings that may have 
been the result of other efforts to cut government bureaucracy, the 
General Accounting Office report said. 
</P>
<P>
	Project officials also neglected to take into account expenses  
that offset some of the savings, said the GAO, Congress' auditing 
and investigative arm. 
</P>
<P>
	White House officials disputed the GAO findings and said offsets  
to the savings were accounted for. They acknowledged that savings 
were overstated by several hundred million dollars but said the 
reinventing project is on track to save an estimated $137 billion 
and characterized the GAO's findings as ``an arcane debate about 
accounting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``What really matters is that government is smaller than it's  
been since the Kennedy administration, and it operates better, more 
efficiently and is saving taxpayers money,'' said Linda Ricci, 
spokeswoman at the White House Office of Management and Budget, 
which calculated the savings estimates for Gore's project. 
</P>
<P>
	A House Republican who requested the report seized on its  
findings to criticize Gore, the front-running Democratic 
presidential candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., chairman of the House Government Reform  
Committee, said the report released Monday shows that Gore 
``greatly exaggerated the success of his National Partnership for 
Reinventing Government.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It looks like they were reinventing accounting rules,'' Burton  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore launched the reinventing project in 1993, promising to make  
government ``work better and cost less'' by reducing bureaucracy, 
cutting contracting costs and relying more on technology. Project 
officials claim $107 billion in savings and say they have ``locked 
into place'' another $29.6 billion in savings. 
</P>
<P>
	GAO looked at almost $30 billion in claimed savings from  
reinvention initiatives at NASA and the departments of Agriculture 
and Energy. They found several problems: 
</P>
<P>
	--OMB did not keep records supporting $21.8 billion in claimed  
savings. Ricci said OMB did not save worksheets from the 
calculations, some of which were done six years ago. But she said 
that OMB budget specialists could reconstruct how they calculated 
the savings. 
</P>
<P>
	--OMB double-counted estimated savings in at least two instances,  
thereby inflating cost cuts. Ricci disputed GAO's findings and said 
OMB analysts inadvertently double-counted in only one case, leading 
to an overstatement of about $770 million in savings. She said that 
was more than offset by another counting error in which OMB 
underestimated about $2 billion in savings. 
</P>
<P>
	--The project claimed savings that ``could not be fully  
attributed to its efforts'' and actually resulted from separate 
efforts, said GAO. For example, Gore's project took full credit for 
savings at Energy Department weapons laboratories that would have 
occurred anyway because of the end of the Cold War, GAO noted. 
</P>
<P>
	Ricci said that NPR's estimate of $137 billion in savings will  
pan out. 
</P>
<P>
	``While I won't predict down to the dollar,'' Ricci said, ``we  
will be comfortably within that range.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
