<HEADLINE> NAACP Demands Apology From Bennett </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Sen. Bob Bennett should apologize for  
using a race-specific scenario to describe what he believes it 
would take to prevent George W. Bush from winning the Republican 
presidential nomination, Utah's NAACP leaders say. 
</P>
<P>
	Bennett, R-Utah, said during an Aug. 13 meeting with the  
editorial board of the Standard-Examiner of Ogden that Bush seems 
to have a lock on the nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unless George W. steps in front of a bus or some woman comes  
forward, let's say some black woman comes forward with an 
illegitimate child that he fathered within the last 18 months, or 
some other scenario that you could be equally creative in thinking 
of, George W. Bush will be the nominee,'' Bennett told the 
newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	NAACP Salt Lake branch President Jeanetta Williams said Bennett  
``owes the community and the nation a public apology.'' But she 
said she didn't think he should resign. 
</P>
<P>
	Edward Lewis Jr., president of the National Association for the  
Advancement of Colored People's tri-state conference for Idaho, 
Nevada and Utah, said Bennett ``felt very comfortable in his 
whiteness'' to make the remark. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement issued by his office, Bennett said he ``certainly  
regrets'' making the comment. ``Those who heard his remark 
firsthand, including the publisher of the Ogden Standard-Examiner, 
have said that they interpreted no racial overtones,'' the 
statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bennett said he plans to meet with NAACP representatives to  
``express these sentiments personally.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Ogden newspaper's publisher, W. Scott Trundle, was out of  
the office Monday and unavailable. Don Porter, editorial page 
editor, said he had no comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Blacks make up less than 1 percent of voters in Utah. Lewis  
called on Bennett to consider the needs of all his constituents, 
``not just the white population.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
