<HEADLINE> NY Board Wants Gun-Toting Judge Gone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- A judge who once carried a gun into court  
should be removed for making slurs about Italians and lying under 
oath, the state's judicial misconduct board ruled. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commission on Judicial Conduct ruled Monday against Onondaga  
County Judge J. Kevin Mulroy, who said he will appeal to the State 
Court of Appeals. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission said Mulroy, 47, lied as a character witness in  
the forgery and larceny trial of a lawyer, who was acquitted. He 
was also punished for telling a prosecutor of Italian descent at a 
1996 charity dinner: ``You know how you Italian types are with your 
Mafia connections.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Soon after becoming a judge in 1987, Mulroy carried a 9mm  
semiautomatic gun under his robe during the trial of William Blake. 
Blake was convicted of killing a sheriff's deputy and wounding 
another during an escape attempt and Mulroy said he carried the 
weapon after receiving death threats. 
</P>
<P>
	At Blake's sentencing, Mulroy told the defendant that ``about  
six bucks of electricity would solve the problem'' and chastised 
then-Gov. Mario Cuomo for his opposition to the death penalty. His 
comments prompted an investigation by the judicial commission, 
which reprimanded him in a letter. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1992, Mulroy described a rape victim as ``the kind that work  
'em into a frenzy, and then cut 'em off and watch 'em squirm.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
