<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Mixed in Volatile Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- With no surprises in the latest inflation data,  
the dollar turned in a mixed performance in volatile trading 
Tuesday, gaining against the euro but losing ground to the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0509, down  
from $1.0575 late Monday. The dollar also was quoted at 114.05 
Japanese yen, down from 114.68. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign exchange analysts said a seesaw session for the dollar  
began early in the day, when Japanese traders sold large amounts of 
euros for yen. The selloff weakened the euro against the dollar, 
but strengthened the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	``The euro fell apart against everything,'' said Kevin Harris,  
an international economist at MCM Currencywatch in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar regained some ground against the yen later in the day  
after the Labor Department released its consumer price data, which 
indicated that inflation remained in check. The Consumer Price 
Index, a closely watched gauge of inflation, rose 0.3 percent in 
July, matching analysts' expectations and raising hopes that the 
Fed will take a moderate course in setting interest rates when it 
meets Aug. 24. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders are expecting the Fed, which already nudged up rates on  
June 30, would raise rates modestly next week. 
</P>
<P>
	There have been worries that fresh signs of inflation would lead  
to a third rate increase later this year. Tuesday's figures reduced 
those jitters. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. stock and bond markets both moved higher on the benign  
inflation news, setting the stage for the dollar to gain back some 
of the ground it lost earlier to the yen. But it was not enough for 
a broad gain for the U.S. currency. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.5228 Swiss francs, up from  
1.5154, and 1.4786 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4835. The British 
pound rose to $1.6044 from $1.6013. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
