<HEADLINE> Cardinals' Dye in Critical Condition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Arizona Cardinals offensive lineman Ernest Dye  
was in critical condition today following extensive surgery to 
repair his right arm. 
</P>
<P>
	Dye, 28, was injured Monday in a single-car rollover accident  
while traveling to the Cardinals' camp in Flagstaff with defensive 
end Carl Simpson and guard Lester Holmes for a team meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Dye suffered a fractured humerus - the bone between the shoulder  
and the elbow - and damaged at least one of the arteries that 
supplies blood to the hand. 
</P>
<P>
	Surgeons at Flagstaff Medical Center spent Monday afternoon and  
much of Monday night working to save Dye's arm. 
</P>
<P>
	Dye was originally listed in fair condition. The change to  
critical condition is standard procedure for someone recovering 
from such extensive surgery, Cardinals spokesman Greg Gladysiewski 
said today. ``His life is not in danger.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The accident happened about 25 miles south of Flagstaff on a  
rain-slicked section of Interstate 17. Holmes was driving Dye's 
black 1995 Mercedes when it veered into the median and rolled. 
</P>
<P>
	Dye and Simpson were thrown from the car. Holmes was the only  
one wearing a seat belt. 
</P>
<P>
	Holmes severely cut his forehead in the accident. He remained at  
Flagstaff Medical Center this morning in good condition. Simpson 
was checked for pain in the hip and released Monday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
