<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sears Dumps Softer Side in New Ads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- After taking a beating from both discount and  
specialty retailers, Sears, Roebuck and Co.'s is shelving its 
``softer side'' and battling back with a harder pitch as the 
nation's largest department store chain looks to revive flagging 
sales. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hoffman Estates, Ill.-based company on Tuesday unveiled a  
much-awaited, more value-focused advertising tag: ``The Good Life 
At A Great Price. Guaranteed. Sears.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Whether we like it or not, we're in a price-game war, a value  
shootout with all our competition,'' said Mark A. Cohen, Sears' 
executive vice president of marketing. ``With the Softer Side 
campaign, the customer feedback has been 'We love the commercials, 
imagery and models, but we don't find those goods at Sears.' 
</P>
<P>
	``But we are far more competitive than customers give us credit  
for,'' he said. ``The fact is, shame on us, we've been avoiding 
shouting about price, shouting about our quality guarantees and the 
products we offer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To that end, Sears forced its two advertising agencies into  
unprecedented cooperation to come up with the new tagline and to 
develop 40 television commercials set to debut in September that 
emphasize Sears as a place to shop. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sears sells across the country an enormous amount of products  
that are components of a customer's lifestyle. We sell four out of 
10 kitchen and laundry appliances. We sell an enormous number of 
tools, and Sears has been clothing families for 100 years,'' Cohen 
said. ``Now we're saying Sears is the place you have to go to make 
all of these products pay off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The campaign is the final piece in a series of changes the  
retailer announced early this year, including a move toward more 
trendy clothing, remodeling its stores and selling merchandise on 
the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Sears would not reveal the cost of the new campaign, which also  
will involve print and radio advertising, but the effort clearly is 
aimed at reviving the fortunes for a company that appears to have 
lost its way recently. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics have said Sears chairman Arthur Martinez's rescue of the  
company from the brink of bankruptcy in 1992 only delayed the 
inevitable as middle-priced stores such as Sears, J.C. Penney and 
Montgomery Ward are squeezed from both ends, by higher priced 
competitors such as Macy's and Bloomingdales and discount and 
specialty shops such as Wal-Mart, the Gap and Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch. 
</P>
<P>
	But analyst Kurt Barnard, president of the consulting firm  
Barnard's Retail Trend Report, warned against counting Sears out 
just yet, calling its new campaign ``extremely effective.'' The ads 
will highlight nice-looking clothes and other merchandise, while 
stressing to much sought-after younger shoppers that they can 
attain the ``good life'' at reasonable prices from Sears, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is intended very clearly to challenge everyone, namely the  
conventional department stores as well as the discount stores,'' 
Barnard said. ``The tagline is a worthy replacement of the Softer 
Side tagline, which worked so well but which has lost its edge to 
overexposure. 
</P>
<P>
	``All that Sears needs now to do is to make its stores live up  
to the expectations the tagline raises,'' he said. ``In other 
words, they need to have a store where people walk in and say 'Hey, 
this is my store, they know me and buy merchandise for me.' '' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
