<DOCNO> APW19990817.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-17 03:50:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fla To Alter Congresional Districts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- Florida officials have agreed to alter  
the shape of several congressional districts in a plan critics say 
could dilute the voting power of minorities in those areas. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, approved by lawyers for Gov. Jeb Bush, still must be  
approved by a panel of three federal judges. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan would change the boundaries of seats now held by two  
black Democrats -- Alcee Hastings and Carrie Meek -- and a Hispanic 
Republican, Ileana Ros-Lehtinen, along with five neighboring 
districts. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan was devised to settle a lawsuit filed last year by a  
white candidate, Tom Fouts, who lost a bid for a state Senate seat 
held by a black incumbent. Under the terms of the settlement, Fouts 
dropped any challenge over state districts. 
</P>
<P>
	Hastings' existing district ties together black neighborhoods in  
seven counties in southern Florida, yielding a black voting 
constituency of 44 percent. The proposed settlement, to be filed 
today in Miami, would reduce that number to nearly 37 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Hastings' attorney, Terry Anderson, said Monday night he was  
still reviewing the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``Frankly, Alcee could probably win any district they could  
carve up at this stage,'' Anderson said. ``His concern is that he 
leave behind a district in which African-Americans have a fair 
opportunity to win a seat in Congress. ... My preliminary reaction 
is that this doesn't do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hastings' district was one of three designed to give black  
voters a better opportunity to elect a candidate of their choice 
when it was drawn by a panel of federal judges in 1992. That year, 
Florida elected its first blacks to Congress since Reconstruction: 
Corrine Brown, Meek and Hastings. 
</P>
<P>
	But the U.S. Supreme Court has since ruled that race cannot be  
the predominant factor in drawing political boundaries. That has 
forced changes in congressional and legislative districts across 
the country. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
