<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CNNfn Executive Dismissed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The executive vice president of CNNfn was  
dismissed and asked to leave the network's Manhattan headquarters. 
</P>
<P>
	The ouster Monday of David Bohrman came more than two months  
after the departure of Lou Dobbs as CNNfn chief executive. 
</P>
<P>
	Plans were announced last month to give CNN 3 1/2 hours of new  
financial and business news programming, to be simulcast on CNNfn 
and use some of CNNfn's staff. The programs were to be under the 
control of Jeff Gralnick, executive vice president of financial 
news at CNN, and not Bohrman, who objected to the plan. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were unable to reach a decision with David concerning the  
scope of his responsibilities as they would relate to the new 
business news programming,'' said Steve Korn, vice chairman and 
chief operating officer of CNN News Group. 
</P>
<P>
	Bohrman and Gralnick reported to Dobbs, who had overseen  
financial news coverage for all of CNN's news networks and 
engineered the launch of CNNfn. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Times reported today that while both executives  
were hired by Dobbs, it was Bohrman, not Gralnick, who was seen as 
closer to him. But Korn insisted this had nothing to do with the 
decision to dismiss Bohrman. 
</P>
<P>
	``Absolutely not,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	While CNN reaches 76 million homes, CNNfn reaches just 12  
million homes, a fraction of the 68 million homes that can receive 
its financial-news rival, CNBC. 
</P>
<P>
	Dobbs left to start an Internet venture. His position as  
president of CNNfn remains unfilled. 
</P>
<P>
	Named as Bohrman's replacement was Teya Ryan, a 10-year CNN  
veteran who most recently served as executive producer of the 
weekly prime-time magazine show ``Newsstand: CNN &AMP; Fortune.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
