<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Military Depots Living On </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHAMBERSBURG, Pa. (AP) -- As commander of the Letterkenny Army  
Depot, Col. Henry W. Suchting III knows that every time there's a 
threat of more layoffs the installation's union representatives 
will call their congressional contacts. 
</P>
<P>
	Like Suchting, commanders of the military's maintenance and  
repair depots from Virginia to Hawaii look the other way -- or 
quietly encourage those contacts with the powerful House group that 
works to keep the depots open. 
</P>
<P>
	The 77 lawmakers call themselves the Depot Caucus, and their  
mission is to fight the Pentagon's drive to let more private 
contractors maintain and overhaul the nation's weapons of war. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the 18 major depots and shipyards -- and numerous smaller  
maintenance and repair operations -- have suffered increased layoffs 
and shuttered buildings as the Pentagon tries to save billions of 
dollars to serve a much smaller military. 
</P>
<P>
	The caucus members stick together in classic  
protect-your-district politics, standing guard to ensure depots 
keep their gates open. The Pentagon cannot close any major military 
facilities without congressional approval. 
</P>
<P>
	The group includes members of defense and appropriations  
committees that control spending and military policy, and they can 
exercise great influence over their colleagues on Capitol Hill. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm aware of it,'' Suchting said of the union-Depot Caucus  
contacts, pointing out that depot commanders are obligated to make 
their points with the military chain of command. ``Far be it for me 
to try to stop it. It's rather benign with me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Defense Department spends about $13 billion a year to store,  
repair and modernize its equipment. Most of that work was done at 
the depots in years past; now $6 billion of that money goes to 
private industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The figure would be higher, but the Depot Caucus lawmakers  
pushed through legislation that requires the Defense Department to 
keep at least 50 percent of maintenance work within the military. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Pentagon could get rid of unneeded facilities, ``We could  
take that money for weapons modernization and quality of life 
issues like family housing,'' said Randall Yim, the Defense 
Department's deputy undersecretary for installations. ``We don't 
need massive warehouses anymore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The depots still perform valuable functions, and some have  
proven they can do work cheaper than private industry. 
</P>
<P>
	At Letterkenny, in south central Pennsylvania, the cavernous  
maintenance building where civilian workers once overhauled tanks 
now sits mostly idle. Although the depot still uses 
state-of-the-art equipment for missile repair, its work force has 
dropped to 1,320 from 6,200 at its peak in the 1960s. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's kind of like a ghost town now,'' said Tom Cohenour, who  
supervises mechanics at Letterkenny. ``There were three shifts 
here. It's sad, really sad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Letterkenny and the Red River Army Depot in Texarkana, Texas,  
have suffered some of the largest losses since the last base 
closings in 1995. Defense Department figures show Letterkenny is 
operating at 73 percent of its capacity; Red River is at only 37 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Air Force logistics center in Ogden, Utah, is at 53 percent.  
In the Navy, the Portsmouth, N.H., shipyard is operating at 52 
percent capacity; the shipyard at Pearl Harbor, Hawaii, at 56 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Caucus members protecting the depots argue that it is unwise to  
shut facilities that are essential in wartime. A private business 
can be hit with a strike or have financial problems that could harm 
the nation in time of crisis, these lawmakers say. 
</P>
<P>
	The caucus boasts several influential members, including Rep.  
Bud Shuster, R-Pa., chairman of the House Transportation and 
Infrastructure Committee, who holds sway over road and 
transportation projects in every member's district, and Rep. Tillie 
Fowler, R-Fla., a member of the House Republican leadership and the 
Armed Services Committee.	   Few want to tangle with them. Rep. Terry Everett, R-Ala., said 
he was threatened with losing a place on a key House-Senate 
conference committee when he opposed the group in a 1997 
legislative battle. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would say they use no-holds-barred tactics verging on being  
ruthless,'' Everett said in an interview. 
</P>
<P>
	But Mrs. Fowler said the caucus doesn't bully opponents, and is  
simply trying to educate colleagues on the importance of the 
depots. 
</P>
<P>
	``I worry that in five years, 10 years, they'll get rid of the  
depots. We learned that in these battles, we better be prepared,'' 
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats also are prominent in the depot-saving effort.  
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Norm Dicks, D-Wash., who serves on the Appropriations  
defense and military construction subcommittees, is a caucus 
member. And Rep. Solomon Ortiz of Texas, ranking Democrat on the 
Armed Services readiness subcommittee, is co-chairman of the 
caucus. 
</P>
<P>
	Ortiz said the group has contacts throughout depots so it can be  
alerted to any efforts to cut work. ``We are like the CIA,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Pentagon officials say they're not trying to starve the depots  
by sending more work to the private sector, but rather are trying 
to save money. 
</P>
<P>
	``The overall policy is to outsource to the extent allowed by  
law, where it could make sense,'' said Robert Mason, the Pentagon's 
assistant deputy secretary who specializes in depot issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Letterkenny, a 57-year-old installation, was built to service a  
much larger military. Until recently, a huge chunk of its business, 
in partnership with a private contractor, was converting old tanks 
into modern, self-propelled howitzers called the Paladin. 
</P>
<P>
	Suchting, the commander, isn't willing to stand by and watch his  
facility crumble. He pursues work -- even from nonmilitary sources -- 
in a manner that would have been unthinkable for an Army officer 
years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	He researches whether private companies would pay to use his  
facility's huge tank painting sheds, chrome-plating equipment, or 
his air conditioning repairmen. 
</P>
<P>
	Ranae Coheley, 46, a program analyst at the Army depot in  
Anniston, Ala., said the Depot Caucus is fighting for the system 
that ``supported me my entire lifetime.'' Her father worked there 
for nearly 40 years, her crane-operator husband has been there for 
27 and she has put in 23. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just hope the depot will stay open until we have enough  
years to retire,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	If the caucus has a say, it might.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's life or death as they see it,'' said former Rep. Vic  
Fazio, D-Calif., who went against the caucus in 1997 to save jobs 
in his Sacramento district. ``Their dedication probably increases 
as they get closer and closer to the grim reaper.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
