<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Aug. 17, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Dell Profits Rise 47 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Dell Computer Corp. posted a 47 percent  
increase in second-quarter profit today, beating Wall Street 
expectations with strong sales of computers to small businesses, 
home users and over the Internet. Dell, the largest seller of 
computer directly to customers, said it earned $507 million, or 19 
cents per share, in the quarter that ended July 30. That was up 
from a profit of $346 million, or 12 cents a share in the same 
period last year. Revenues rose 42 percent to $6.14 billion from 
$4.33 billion. Dell stock closed down 5/16 at 41 1/8. 

</P>
<P>
	After-Hours Trading Coming to ETrade  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- ETrade Group Inc. plans to offer after-hours  
trading through Instinet, bringing the Internet's second biggest 
pool of investors to the busiest market for buying and selling 
stocks when regular exchanges are closed. The service, set to begin 
next month, would make ETrade the biggest online broker so far to 
let its customers react to late-breaking news, a privilege long 
enjoyed by money managers, mutual funds and other ``institutional'' 
investors. ETrade shares finished up 3 3/8 at 30 1/4. 

</P>
<P>
	Consumer Price Report Favorable  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Consumer prices edged up just 0.3 percent in  
July despite big increases for energy and airline fares. At the 
same time, construction of new homes staged a solid rebound and the 
nation's factories boosted production at the fastest pace this 
year. All three government reports, released today, provided fresh 
evidence that the U.S. economy continues to power ahead without 
triggering worrisome inflation pressures. The mild 0.3 percent gain 
came after two straight months of flat prices. 

</P>
<P>
	Retailers' Earnings Top Estimates  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Retailers reported better-than-expected earnings  
today as the robust U.S. economy continued to encourage Americans 
to shop. Strong sales at its Target discount stores boosted 
second-quarter profits at Dayton Hudson Corp. by 33 percent from a 
year ago. Profit at J.C. Penney Co. Inc. rose 14 percent, boosted 
by demand for its private-label clothes. The Limited Inc.'s 
earnings doubled from a year ago, amid strength in its Express, 
Lerner New York, Lane Bryant and Intimate Brands Inc. chains. Home 
Depot's profits also rose sharply, while Tiffany &AMP; Co.'s earnings 
gained as shoppers snapped up luxury items. 

</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T-MediaOne Merger Protested  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Consumer groups are asking federal regulators  
to block AT&AMP;T's bid to buy MediaOne, saying the cable merger would 
give the company too much control in the markets for cable TV and 
high-speed cable Internet services. The groups joined today in 
opposing the deal on grounds that it violates existing antitrust 
laws and federal rules that restrict the number of cable customers 
a single company can control. With such a large percentage of the 
market, AT&AMP;T could block new companies from getting into the cable 
business. AT&AMP;T stock gained 11/16 to 49 3/4. 

</P>
<P>
	PC Makers Seek Bigger Business  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Major makers of personal computers are uniting  
with computer chip giant Intel Corp. as they seek to crack the 
market for business machines that manage heavy-duty computing 
tasks. Compaq Computer Corp. unveiled a new type of powerful 
computer today that uses less expensive Intel chips and runs on 
Microsoft Windows operating software. The machine ties together 
eight microprocessors to match the performance of the higher-priced 
computers. Dell Computer Corp., Hewlett-Packard Co. and IBM are 
expected to follow with similar products. Compaq shares gained 3/4 to 
24 5/8. 

</P>
<P>
	Ford Explorer Combines SUV, Pickup  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. displayed its latest attempt to  
carve a new niche out of the highly profitable light-truck segment 
today: a combination sport utility vehicle and pickup called the 
Explorer Sport Trac. The Sport Trac combines the front end and cab 
of a four-door, five-passenger Explorer SUV with a 4-foot cargo 
bed. The idea is to provide the room and comfort of an SUV with the 
cargo utility of a pickup. Other automakers plan to follow in the 
search for the next hit product in the increasingly crowded U.S. 
truck market. Shares in Ford ended up 5/8 at 49 1/4. 

</P>
<P>
	HP Stock Drops After Solid Report  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Hewlett-Packard Co. stock, which shot up  
4 percent yesterday in advance of a strong quarterly profit report 
and gained even more in after-hours trading, slumped today to give 
up those gains. Stock in Hewlett-Packard closed down 6 1/4, or 5.66 
percent, at 104 a share on the New York Stock Exchange. HP, the 
world's second largest computer company, yesterday credited a 37 
percent rise in quarterly profit to its new efforts to focus on 
revenue growth. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Rally Late; Dow Gains 70.29  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Another late afternoon rally propelled stocks  
higher today after news of a mild increase in consumer prices 
suggested that the Federal Reserve may raise interest rates only 
modestly when it meets this month. At the close of trading on Wall 
Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was up 70.29 at 11,117.08. 
Broader stock indicators ended higher after trading in a narrow 
range for most of the day. The technology-heavy Nasdaq composite 
index gained 25.95 points to 2,671.23, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 
500 advanced 11.92 to 1,342.69. 

