<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls, Tokyo Stocks Rise / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar fell slightly against the yen today as  
many market participants stayed sidelined ahead of the release of 
U.S. consumer price data. Tokyo stocks rose slightly. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 114.60 yen in late afternoon trading, down  
0.24 yen from late Monday in Tokyo and below its level late Monday 
in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 34.06 points, or 0.19  
percent, to close at 17,860.09. On Monday, the average finished up 
390.86 points, or 2.24 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders were waiting for the release on today of the U.S.  
consumer price index, a key measure of inflation, for an indication 
of the dollar's prospects. Benign inflation numbers could stoke 
U.S. markets and boost the dollar, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 120.66 yen, down  
from 121.58 yen late Monday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, the Nikkei rose for the seventh straight  
session as investors bought select international blue chip shares. 
</P>
<P>
	``Blue chip stocks continue to lead the market, and we may see  
further polarization of stronger and weaker shares,'' said Ken 
Yamano, general manager of the equities section at Taiheiyo 
Securities Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading was subdued as market players waited for the U.S. price  
data for clues on the direction of U.S. markets. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section rose 5.63 points, or 0.38 percent, to 1,474.14. The 
TOPIX closed up 26.02 points, or 1.80 percent, on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading on the exchange's main section was estimated at 386.80  
million shares, nearly unchanged from 378.65 million shares Monday. 
Declines outnumbered advances 732 to 448, while 134 issues were 
unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 214 10-year Japanese government  
bond yield fell to 1.9150 percent from its close Monday of 1.9250 
percent, driving its price up to 99.02 yen from 98.94 yen Monday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
