<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pentagon Reviews Papers About Diana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon is re-examining U.S. intelligence  
documents containing references to the late Princess Diana at the 
request of Mohamed Al Fayed, the father of her boyfriend Dodi 
Fayed. 
</P>
<P>
	Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said Tuesday an initial review  
of the documents last May yielded no information useful to the 
investigation of the Paris car accident that killed Diana and Fayed 
in August 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	At Mohamed Al Fayed's request, Robert Tyrer, the chief of staff  
to Defense Secretary William Cohen, agreed to review the papers 
again, Bacon said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I do not anticipate that a re-review of the documents will  
reach a different conclusion than we've already reached, which is 
there is nothing in these documents that relates in any way to 
information explaining the circumstances of the death of Princess 
Diana,'' Bacon said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bacon declined to discuss the nature of the documents except to  
say they number ``several dozen'' and were generated ``in ordinary 
operations.'' He said, for example, that they may include reports 
from American embassies on the public reception received by Diana 
and Prince Charles on trips abroad. 
</P>
<P>
	Last December, the U.S. government acknowledged that  
intelligence documents compiled by the National Security Agency 
over many years include mention of Diana on 1,056 pages. They said 
the references were incidental and that she was never a target of 
U.S. intelligence operations. 
</P>
<P>
	The fact that NSA agents picked up mentions of Diana in  
international electronic monitoring was disclosed when the agency 
denied an Internet news service's Freedom of Information Act 
request for any intercepts mentioning her, but acknowledged in the 
process that such intercepts exist. 
</P>
<P>
	The NSA, which monitors electronic communications abroad and  
protects U.S. communications from foreign intercepts, is under the 
control of the secretary of defense. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
