<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Mostly Higher, Gold Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar fell against the yen but was  
otherwise stronger in European trading today. Gold prices rose. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0502 in late European trading, down  
from $1.0567 Monday. Later, in midday trading in New York, the euro 
traded at $1.0510. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Monday,  
included 114.33 Japanese yen, down from 114.81; 1.5239 Swiss 
francs, up from 1.5153; 1.4758 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4793. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.5976, down from $1.6024.  
</P>
<P>
	In midday trading in New York, the dollar bought 114.22 yen, and  
the pound was worth $1.6006. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth 1.8623 German marks, up from 1.8509; 
6.2460 French francs, up from 6.2076; 2.0984 Dutch guilders, up 
from 2.0855; 1,843.76 Italian lire, up from 1,832.37. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $260.80 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$258.80 Monday. In Zurich gold traded at $260.75, up from $258.55. 
Gold fell 10 cents in Hong Kong to $259.25. 
</P>
