<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> HP's Quarter Profits Rise 37 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- After several years of tough competition  
and disappointing earnings, Hewlett-Packard Co. credited a 37 
percent rise in quarterly profit to its new efforts to focus on 
revenue growth. 
</P>
<P>
	HP, the world's second largest computer company, said Monday it  
earned $853 million, or 81 cents a share in the fiscal third 
quarter ended July 31. That was up from a profit of $621 million, 
or 58 cents a share, in the same period last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Excluding one-time costs of separating into two companies, HP  
would have earned 85 cents a share, handily beating the 80 cents 
share expected by analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson 
Financial. 
</P>
<P>
	Hewlett-Packard stock, which shot up 4 percent on Monday in  
advance of the release of the figures and gained even more in 
after-hours trading, slumped today to give up those gains. In 
midday trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Hewlett-Packard was 
down 5.6 percent, or by $6.12 1/2, at $104.12 1/2 a share. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue rose to $12.23 billion, from $10.98 billion in the  
year-ago quarter. HP cited a 12 percent increase in sales of 
computer and imaging products, buoyed by strength in Unix business 
computers, desktop machines, scanners and printers. 
</P>
<P>
	Net revenue in the U.S. was $5.6 billion, up 8 percent from a  
year ago. Revenue from outside the U.S. rose 14 percent to $6.6 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	In March, HP split into two separate ventures -- a computer and  
imaging business, and a testing and measurement business dubbed 
Agilent Technologies -- in an effort to revitalize underperforming 
divisions and improve sagging profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, HP named Carleton Fiorina, the former president of  
Lucent Technologies' telecommunications network services business, 
as its new CEO and president to replace retiring president Lewis 
Platt. 
</P>
<P>
	Platt, who remains chairman, said the company is beginning to  
see the results of efforts to convert orders for products and 
services into stronger revenue growth. He said the profits were a 
nice surprise. 
</P>
<P>
	``A number of businesses improved their profitability, with  
overall profitability exceeding our expectations,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Fiorina said the strong quarter is an indicator of HP's new  
commitment to making money. 
</P>
<P>
	``We must become more aggressive and much more focused, and we  
are resolved to do so,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue growth in the businesses that will make up Agilent  
Technologies was up 8 percent over the same period last year, with 
broad-based growth across all its businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	In the nine months ended July 31, HP earned $2.73 billion, or  
$2.61 a share, up from a profit of $2.24 billion, or $2.09 a share, 
in the year-ago period. Revenues rose to $36.59 billion from $34.84 
billion. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
