<HEADLINE> Dalai Lama Promotes Warmheartedness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BLOOMINGTON, Ind. (AP) -- Violence among today's youth may stem  
from society's failure to promote a sense of ``warmheartedness'' in 
children, the Dalai Lama said Tuesday during a panel discussion at 
Indiana University. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today there is more violence in society, particularly the  
younger generation,'' the exiled Tibetan leader said. ``This 
happened because of many decades of negligence about basic human 
values.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The discussion, which wrapped up a weekend-long violence  
prevention conference, reached far beyond the bounds of the IU 
conference room as it was broadcast live on the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dalai Lama was joined by William Sessions, former director  
of the Federal Bureau of Investigation; Chief Judge Sarah Evans 
Barker of the U.S. District Court in Indianapolis; and Richard 
Kimberly, vice president of government relations for the 
Kimberly-Clark Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dalai Lama said he feels education has not focused enough on  
morals, and that a lack of ``warmheartedness'' in young people can 
lead to a lack of contentment, and then to violence. 
</P>
<P>
	He stressed the need for all people to have a moral  
counterbalance in their lives, something that won't let their 
desires drive them too far. To reach the younger generation, he 
said, will require effort by educators, families and religious 
leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nonviolence does not mean we remain indifferent,'' he said.  
``We must remain fully engaged.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sessions, whose zeal for the subject matter lead him to  
occasionally cut off the Dalai Lama in midsentence, spoke of the 
need to empower children by teaching them how to mediate problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps summing up the panel's thoughts with his well-known  
sense of spiritual simplicity, the Dalai Lama said: ``We simply 
want happiness or a happy life. We don't want pain or suffering. 
Violence brings suffering, pain.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 64-year-old monk is the 14th Dalai Lama and as such is  
considered a reincarnation of the Buddha of compassion. He won the 
Nobel Prize in 1989 for his nonviolent efforts to win autonomy for 
Tibet, which has been under Chinese control since 1950. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dalai Lama is being reunited with his brother Thubten Norbu,  
a retired Indiana University professor and founder of the Tibetan 
Cultural Center, where the Dalai Lama will perform the Kalachakra 
Initiation -- a series of rituals and teachings intended to help 
believers on the path to enlightenment. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
