<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Scores Hold Steady on ACTs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Although the 1990s have produced a generation  
of high school students who seem better prepared for college than 
their predecessors, scores have leveled off on a major 
college-entrance exam, according to a report Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The average composite ACT score for 1999 was 21 of a possible 36  
for the 1 million high school students who took the set of tests, 
formerly known as the American College Testing assessments. It was 
the third year in a row at the same level. 
</P>
<P>
	Results from the tests -- which measure student skills in  
English, math, reading and science -- have become an annual 
barometer of high school achievement. 
</P>
<P>
	The average 1999 composite score is the same as last year, when  
995,000 students took the test, and the 1997 average, according to 
the Iowa City, Iowa-based organization. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1990s have ended, however, with the highest-ever rise in the  
average score, four-tenths of a point from 20.6 in 1989 to 21 in 
1999. 
</P>
<P>
	Scores rose over the '80s decade by just one-tenth of a point.  
</P>
<P>
	During the 1960s, national scores decreased on average a full  
point, and in the 1970s, the average score fell an additional 1.3 
points. 
</P>
<P>
	Educators praised the 1990s increases, because scores usually  
decline as test participation rises, but the number of students 
taking the test has grown by nearly 200,000 since the decade began. 
</P>
<P>
	``This combination of trends -- more students preparing for  
college while achieving higher entrance-exam scores -- should be 
welcomed by those concerned about American education,'' ACT 
President Richard L. Ferguson said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The ACT report also surveys what courses college-bound seniors  
are taking and what careers they plan. It reflects the skills of 36 
percent of the nation's estimated 2.3 million high school graduates 
and 60 percent of America's entering college freshmen. The test is 
one of two major entrance examinations. Results from the other, the 
SAT, also will be released this month. 
</P>
<P>
	The ACT is given mainly in Western and Southern states.  
</P>
<P>
	Of the states where more than half of graduating seniors take  
the test, the highest average composite scores were in Wisconsin 
(22.3), Minnesota (22.1) and Iowa (22). The highest average score 
overall was in Rhode Island (22.7 with 3 percent high school 
graduates tested), the lowest in the District of Columbia (18.6, 
with 13 percent of graduates tested). Mississippi, which had the 
highest share of ACT test-takers at 82 percent, had the 
second-lowest average score, 18.7. 
</P>
<P>
	Ferguson said overall performance is improving because more  
students took higher-level courses in subjects covered by the ACT. 
Ten years ago, 46 percent of the test-takers reported preparing 
themselves for college with the appropriate classes. This year, 63 
percent have taken core courses. 
</P>
<P>
	As companies demand higher-skilled, better-educated employees,  
students are being encouraged to take classes that will prepare 
them for college. The American Federation of Teachers union 
launched a campaign Tuesday to advise middle-school students -- 
seventh-graders to ninth-graders -- on how to prepare for college 
and the work force. Thousands of businesses nationwide say they 
will rely on student course work in future entry-level hiring. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's students still have a way to go. The ACT report  
indicates that less than half are prepared for college classes. 
Typically students who score under 16 points on any part of the ACT 
will need extra help in their freshman year; even scores up to 19 
suggest minimal readiness. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, on the ACT English test for 1999, 48 percent of  
students scored 21 points or higher, indicating they are ready to 
do well in college composition courses, and 47 percent scored 22 
points or higher on the reading test, meaning good preparation for 
entry-level history or psychology courses. 
</P>
<P>
	The report also showed that just 4 percent of college-bound  
graduates plan careers in computer and information sciences, 
despite strong job growth and an increasingly computer-literate 
society. 
</P>
<P>
	The gender gap has closed to its closest point ever, but the  
boys' average score slipped a tenth of a point, from 21.2 to 21.1, 
while the average score for girls held steady at 20.9. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
