<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lutherans Weigh Unity Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Challenging his listeners to ``make history,'' a  
noted historian today presented a controversial proposal for close 
unity, but not full-fledged merger, between the Episcopal Church 
and the Evangelical Lutheran Church in America. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin E. Marty, a Lutheran pastor and recently retired  
University of Chicago professor, was co-chair of the panel that 
wrote the proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	``Through your vote, you can make history,'' Marty told the  
Lutheran church's national assembly. 
</P>
<P>
	The Episcopal co-chair, Bishop Christopher Epting of Iowa, told  
the assembly ``we may not have this opportunity again. I pray that 
we will not miss it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``What a step into the new millennium,'' Lutheran Presiding  
Bishop H. George Anderson, who also favors the pact, said today. 
</P>
<P>
	But in his sermon at opening worship Monday, Anderson said he  
faced the week's deliberations with ``fear of boiling frustrations, 
of misunderstood arguments, of tempers out of control, of conflict 
that seems unresolvable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson's prepared text said some have talked about ``an  
ecumenical train wreck'' here, but he omitted that remark. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the proposed pact, scheduled for a vote Thursday, the 5.2  
million Lutherans and 2.3 million Episcopalians would recognize and 
share each other's clergy and sacraments, cooperate in mission 
projects and make joint decisions on important issues. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rev. Daniel Perry, the ecumenical officer for the  
Episcopalians, said the pact would help both denominations because 
they could share clergy and mission work in urban and rural areas 
where their resources are spread thin. 
</P>
<P>
	The pact needs two-thirds approval from the 1,039 delegates. Two  
years ago, the Episcopal Church gave overwhelming approval but the 
Lutheran assembly's vote fell just short of two-thirds. The pact 
has been slightly reworked since. 
</P>
<P>
	The sticking point is that in the future Lutherans must follow  
the Episcopal practice known as the ``historic episcopate.'' Each 
Lutheran bishop will be installed by three predecessor bishops in a 
line believed to extend back to Christ's apostles, and all clergy 
will be ordained by such bishops. 
</P>
<P>
	Catholic and Orthodox churches, like the Episcopalians and other  
Anglicans, follow this procedure. But Lutheran teaching does not 
require it and many Lutheran bodies, including those in the U.S., 
have never followed it. 
</P>
<P>
	Hours before the assembly opening, a meeting of Lutheran bishops  
shared worries about this week's deliberations and the aftermath. 
</P>
<P>
	Bishop Richard Foss of Fargo, N.D., a staunch foe, assured his  
colleagues that no schism will occur if the Episcopal pact passes. 
``There is zero chance of a breakaway church. That's just not on 
the table.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But several of his colleagues warned there will be hard feelings  
among members whichever side wins. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're a divided church on this issue,'' said Bishop Peter  
Rogness of Milwaukee. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1982, when the Lutherans and Episcopalians first declared  
a preliminary level of fellowship, the Episcopal Church has seen a 
net loss of 455,000 members, or 16 per cent. The Evangelical 
Lutheran Church in America has lost membership, too, but far less 
drastically. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990817.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-17 16:10:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Retailers' Earnings Top Estimates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Some of the nation's biggest retailers reported  
better-than-expected earnings Tuesday as the robust U.S. economy 
continued to encourage Americans to shop. 
</P>
<P>
	Strong sales at its Target discount stores boosted  
second-quarter profits at Dayton Hudson Corp. by 33 percent from a 
year ago. Profit at J.C. Penney Co. Inc. rose 14 percent, boosted 
by demand for its private-label clothes. 
</P>
<P>
	The Limited Inc.'s earnings doubled from a year ago, amid  
strength in its Express, Lerner New York, Lane Bryant and Intimate 
Brands Inc. chains. 
</P>
<P>
	Home Depot's profits also rose sharply as consumers continue to  
spend money to fix up their homes, while Tiffany &AMP; Co.'s earnings 
gained as shoppers eagerly spent on luxury items such as jewelry 
and china. 
</P>
<P>
	While the earnings reported Tuesday topped Wall Street analysts'  
expectations, most of their stocks failed to post big gains amid 
concerns that retailers could be hit hard if the robust U.S. 
economy slows its pace in the coming months. 
</P>
<P>
	Saks Inc. which also reported strong earnings, issued a warning  
that its profits for the remainder of the year will be weaker than 
expected. Its shares fell nearly 20 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Results were reported for the quarter ended July 31 for all of  
the companies except for Home Depot, which reported for a quarter 
ended Aug. 1. All stocks trade on the New York Stock Exchange. 

</P>
<P>
                        *Dayton Hudson Corp.    	
</P>
<P>
	The Minneapolis-based retailer earned $224 million, or 48 cents  
a share, in the quarter vs. $172 million, or 36 cents a share, a 
year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue increased 9.9 percent to $7.75 billion, compared with  
$7.06 billion last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Wall Street analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial  
had expected Dayton Hudson to report earnings of 46 cents a share. 
Dayton Hudson stock rose 62 1/2 cents to $61.87 1/2 in trading. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said that its strong performance was driven by its  
Target division, where pretax profit rose 27 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Dayton Hudson operates 881 Target stores, 267 Mervyn's  
moderately priced department stores and 64 department stores. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first half, Dayton Hudson earned $418 million, or 89  
cents a share, compared with $330 million, or 69 cents a share a 
year ago. Sales rose to $14.97 billion from $13.52 billion. 

</P>
<P>
                        *J. C. Penney Co. Inc.    	
</P>
<P>
	The Plano, Texas-based company reported operating earnings of  
about $112 million, or 40 cents a share, compared with $97 million, 
or 35 cents a share, a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's results topped Wall Street analysts' estimates of  
34 cents a share. But Penney's stock fell 43 3/4 cents to $42.56 1/4 in 
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales rose to $7.3 billion from $6.76 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	Sales at department stores opened at least a year, which is  
considered an industry gauge of performance, rose 1 percent in the 
quarter. The company said that sales of its private-label apparel, 
such as St. John's Bay, were strong, while sales of athletic 
sportswear and basic jeans were weak. 
</P>
<P>
	Same-store sales at Eckerd drugstores increased 10.5 percent  
over the second quarter a year ago. But Penney still said that the 
results at Eckerd were disappointing as the process of integrating 
Eckerd into its business has taken longer than expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Catalog sales dipped 2.8 percent.  
</P>
<P>
	For the first half, Penney reported operating earnings of $279  
million, or $1.01 a share, compared with $273 million, or 99 cents 
a share, a year ago. Sales rose to $14.88 billion from $13.81 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	J. C. Penney operates nearly 1,150 J.C. Penney department stores  
and 2,900 Eckerd drugstores. It also operates 23 Renner department 
stores in Brazil. 

</P>
<P>
                          *The Limited Inc.    	
</P>
<P>
	The Columbus, Ohio-based specialty clothing retailer earned  
$60.44 million, or 26 cents a share, compared with $31.8 million, 
or 13 cents a share, a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The healthy second-quarter results further confirmed that the  
giant retailer is on track to turn its business around from the 
slump that began in the early 1990s. In recent years, the company 
has undergone a major restructuring, including closing 300 stores 
and creating a design team for each of its divisions to better keep 
pace with fashion trends. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales rose 9 percent to $2.27 billion from $2.08 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, the Limited let Wall Street know that its  
results would be better than the 18 cents a share that the company 
had expected to make in the quarter, and Tuesday's results 
confirmed that. It was the second time this year that the Limited 
has topped analysts' estimates. 
</P>
<P>
	Limited shares were fell 43 3/4 cents to $44.37 1/2 in trading.  
</P>
<P>
	The Limited attributed the profit gain to strong performances at  
the company's Express, Lerner New York, Lane Bryant and Intimate 
Brands Inc. -- which owns Victoria's Secret and Bath &AMP; Body Works -- 
chains. 
</P>
<P>
	The earnings were calculated as if the Limited's spinoff of  
Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch casual apparel chain had occurred at the 
beginning of 1998. Abercrombie became a public company in May 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first half, the Limited earned $94 million, or 40 cents  
a share, compared with $52.3 million, or 22 cents a share. Sales 
rose to $4.37 billion from $4.09 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Limited operates 3,373 specialty stores. The company also owns  
about 84 percent of Intimate Brands, which operates more than 1,800 
stores. 

</P>
<P>
                           *The Home Depot    	
</P>
<P>
	Home Depot earned $679 million, or 44 cents a share, for the  
quarter, compared with $467 million, or 31 cents a share, in the 
same period a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The results exceeded Wall Street's expectations. Analysts  
surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial had predicted earnings of 
41 cents per share. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Home Depot shares fell 93 3/4 cents to $63.06 1/4 in trading.  
</P>
<P>
	Sales rose 28 percent to $10.4 billion from $8.1 billion. Arthur  
M. Blank, president of the Atlanta-based chain, credited the gains 
to increased demand for home improvement items. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first half, Home Depot reported net income of $1.17  
billion, or 76 cents a share, compared with $804 million, or 53 
cents a share, in the same 1998 period. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales rose 27 percent to $19.4 billion from $15.3 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	Home Depot opened 49 new stores and relocated four others during  
the most recent quarter. By the end of the quarter, it had 846 
stores in the United States, Canada, Chile and Puerto Rico. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Tiffany &AMP; Co.    	
</P>
<P>
	New York-based Tiffany earned $23 million, or 31 cents a share,  
for the quarter, compared with $13.5 million, or 19 cents a share, 
a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The results exceeded Wall Street's expectations of 24 cents a  
share, and Tiffany's shares rose $6.31 1/4 to $53 in trading, 
surpassing its previous 52-week high of $51.25. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales rose 23 percent to $307.1 million from $247.7 million.  
</P>
<P>
	Michael J. Kowalski, President and Chief Executive Officer of  
the New York-based luxury goods retailer, said the gains came from 
the company's push to open more stores in the United States and 
abroad. International sales rose 30 percent, while domestic sales 
climbed upward by 23 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's direct-marketing sales rose 5 percent, fueled  
mostly by customers ordering through catalogs. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first six months of the fiscal year, Tiffany reported  
net income of $39.1 million, or 53 cents a share, compared with 
$24.6 million, or 34 cents a share, in the same period of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales rose 17 percent to $579.3 million from $473.9 million.  

</P>
<P>
                             *Saks Inc.    	
</P>
<P>
	Saks, based in Birmingham, Ala., earned $26.6 million, or 18  
cents per share, excluding expenses the department store chain made 
to pay off debt early and make its computers year-2000 compliant. 
</P>
<P>
	The results compared with profits of $12.1 million, or 8 cents  
per share, in the same period a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The figures matched Wall Street's expectations of 18 cents per  
share. 
</P>
<P>
	However, R. Brad Martin, chairman and chief executive of the  
Birmingham, Ala.-based company, revised its estimate for annual 
profits down to $1.80 per share. Analysts surveyed by First 
Call/Thomson Financial had been predicting $2.16. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin blamed that on lackluster sales from the Mercantile  
department store chain, which was bought last year, lower earnings 
from Saks' credit card division, and unexpected expenses from its 
e-commerce operation. 
</P>
<P>
	After his announcement, Saks shares closed down sharply, falling  
$4.68 3/4 to $19 on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales for the most recent quarter totaled $1.43 billion, up 12  
percent from $1.28 billion a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first six months of the fiscal year, Saks reported  
earnings of $66.4 million, or 45 cents per share, excluding the 
one-time expenses. That's 57 percent from $42.3 million, or 29 
cents per share, in the same period of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Six-month sales were up 10 percent, from $2.97 billion to $2.7  
billion. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
