<DOCNO> APW19990817.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-17 23:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Death Row Inmate Wins Reprieve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HUNTSVILLE, Texas (AP) -- Larry Robison never expected to wake up  
this morning in his death row cell. 
</P>
<P>
	``Such is life,'' the inmate said Tuesday after an appeals court  
halted his execution four hours before it was to begin. ``I'm going 
to get off death row one way or another. Maybe it's the Lord 
working.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Death penalty opponents had portrayed Robison's case as a test  
of Gov. George W. Bush's ``compassionate conservatism.'' But the 
judicial reprieve also spared the Republican presidential hopeful 
from having to decide whether to delay the execution of an admitted 
killer who has been diagnosed as a paranoid schizophrenic. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no appropriate action for Gov. Bush to take in this  
case at this time,'' the governor's office said in a statement 
after the ruling. ``This is a legal issue to be decided by the 
courts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Any reprieve from Bush would have been unprecedented. The  
governor, in his 4 1/2 years in office, never has stopped an execution 
-- a span that has seen 98 executions in Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Robison, 42, had said he was looking forward to dying by  
injection. His relatives and death penalty opponents contended he 
was mentally ill and should not be executed for a rampage in which 
five people were slain near Fort Worth 17 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that the citizens of your state and now all  
American voters are entitled to know just how real and deep your 
sense of `compassion' reaches,'' wrote death penalty opponent 
William Moffitt, president of the National Association of Criminal 
Defense Lawyers. 
</P>
<P>
	Moffitt and others clamored for Bush to grant a one-time 30-day  
reprieve as allowed under Texas law. But the Texas Court of 
Criminal Appeals made the request moot. In a 5-4 ruling, the court 
agreed with Robison's attorneys that the inmate's mental problems 
deserved review. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Supreme Court ruled in 1986 that mentally ill people  
could be executed -- as long as they understood the punishment that 
awaited them and why they were being put to death. 
</P>
<P>
	It could be weeks, if not months, before the case is resolved.  
The former construction worker will undergo testing by 
psychiatrists, and then a trial court must decide if Robison is 
sufficiently fit to comprehend his execution. 
</P>
<P>
	His case was considered by many critics an example of the  
problems with the state's treatment of the mentally ill. Robison 
had been diagnosed as a schizophrenic before the killings, but he 
was not considered violent and was released from several public 
hospitals. 
</P>
<P>
	The slayings happened in neighboring cottages near Lake Worth in  
1982. One of the victims was Rickey Lee Bryant, 31, Robison's lover 
and roommate, who was shot twice in the head, decapitated, slashed 
eight times and stabbed. Robison said he ate the man's testicles. 
</P>
<P>
	Robison pleaded innocent by reason of insanity, but a jury  
convicted him of capital murder. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, the Texas Board of Pardons and Paroles voted 17-0  
against recommending that Robison's sentence be commuted to life. 
That meant that Bush could do no more than grant the 30-day 
reprieve to allow him more time to appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	Lois Robison celebrated word of her son's reprieve with hugs.  
She has led the fight to have her son spared and treated. 
</P>
<P>
	But the delay was a bitter blow to relatives of the five  
victims. 
</P>
<P>
	``After 17 years of trials and multiple appeals, we feel  
betrayed that the Texas courts have again allowed Larry Robison to 
manipulate the legal system to postpone justice,'' said Melissa 
Estes, whose cousin, Bruce Gardner, 33, was one of the victims. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
