<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Networks Invest in Personalized TV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Looking to gain a foothold in a technology  
that could shake up their revenue structure, several television 
networks are investing $57 million in a company that makes personal 
video recorders, digital devices expected to replace VCRs. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal with Mountain View-based Replay Networks Inc., to be  
announced today, involves Time Warner Co., The Walt Disney Co., 
Showtime Networks Inc., the Tribune Co. and Liberty Media Group, 
among others. The arrangement follows a smaller investment by some 
of the same companies in TiVo, a Sunnyvale firm that is the other 
leading maker of PVRs. 
</P>
<P>
	PVRs are essentially set-top boxes that can search channels and  
line up many hours of shows that fit an individual viewer's tastes. 
They also allow instant replays of live television, and promise to 
be much easier to use than VCRs. 
</P>
<P>
	But there's one major selling point customers won't hear so much  
about when PVRs appear in stores in the coming months -- a 
quick-skip feature that allows viewers to zip past commercials in a 
few seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're going to cease promotion of the quick-skip button.  
They're definitely going to re-evaluate that,'' said Peg Murphy, 
vice president of business development for NBC Interactive, one of 
a half-dozen investors in both TiVo and Replay Networks. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Murphy wouldn't say whether the investors extracted a  
promise to remove the quick-skip button entirely in exchange for 
their money. 
</P>
<P>
	Replay Networks spokesman Jim Plant said during an interview  
Tuesday, ``It's not our goal to destroy an advertising-based 
business model. We know there will be people who want to skip 
commercials. The goal for us is to find other ways for companies to 
deliver their messages.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The technology has the potential to further fracture advertising  
markets once entirely dominated by the TV networks, by letting 
third parties, such as Replay Networks and TiVo, take a share of 
the profits. 
</P>
<P>
	This prospect led a consortium including Time Warner Inc., Walt  
Disney Co., Discovery Communications Inc., CBS Corp. and News 
Corp., to threaten last week to sue any PVR makers for copyright 
infringement unless they deal with the networks first. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not just TiVo and Replay -- companies like WebTV are doing  
similar things,'' Ms. Murphy said. ``It opens up new opportunities 
for advertising revenues, but remains to be seen how that will be 
divided up. It's better to have everyone talking.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both Replay Networks and TiVo products have a high-capacity  
computer disk that can store up to 30 hours of shows without a 
videotape and play them on demand. Both companies' recorders are 
already being sold on the Internet and should be in stores well in 
advance of the holiday shopping season. 
</P>
<P>
	TiVo's PVR costs $499 to $999, depending on storage capacity and  
customers pay a $9.95 monthly service fee. Replay's device costs 
between $699 and $1,499, and there is no monthly service fee. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
