<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Rally Late; Dow Gains 70.29 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Another late afternoon rally propelled stocks  
higher Tuesday after news of a mild increase in consumer prices 
suggested that the Federal Reserve might raise interest rates only 
modestly when it meets this month. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average rose 70.29 to close at  
11,117.08. Earlier in the session, the blue-chip index fell as much 
as 35 points from Monday's close, but traders blamed Hewlett 
Packard for most of the decline. The nation's No. 2 computer maker 
fell as investors took profits following a solid earnings report. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators ended higher after trading in a narrow  
range for most of the day. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 rose 13.39 to 
1,344.16, and the Nasdaq composite index rose 25.94 to 2,671.22. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks initially rose after the Labor Department said its  
Consumer Price Index, a closely watched gauge of inflation, rose 
0.3 percent in July. That matched analysts' expectations, and 
raised hopes that the Fed will take a moderate course in setting 
interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed raised short-term rates in June, and has indicated it  
would be willing to do so again if policy-makers determine higher 
rates would keep inflation at bay. The threat of higher rates -- and 
in turn, lower corporate profits -- has kept many on Wall Street 
tightly focused on each new economic indicator. 
</P>
<P>
	While the CPI report suggested inflation is not accelerating,  
the good news was somewhat tempered by two separate reports that 
showed a surge in new home construction in July and a strong 
advance in output at the nation's factories, mines and utilities. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, many analysts were reassured that the Fed would perceive  
the data as grounds for one small increase, probably when its Open 
Market Committee meets on Aug. 24. 
</P>
<P>
	``The biggest concern before today was that the Fed would keep  
pushing that interest rate lever, raising rates higher and 
higher,'' said Joseph V. Battipaglia, chief investment strategist 
at Gruntal &AMP; Co. ``That no longer seems to be the case.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ultimately, stocks regained momentum as investors took their  
cues from the inflation-sensitive bond market. The CPI report 
boosted prices, pushing the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond down 
to 6.01 percent from 6.08 percent late Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial services stocks, among the first to be affected by  
interest rate fluctuations, rose Tuesday. American Express led the 
Dow's gains, rising 4 3/8 to 140 1/4 and Chase Manhattan rose 2 3/4 to 83. 
</P>
<P>
	Those gains were outweighed by some major losses in the  
technology sector. 
</P>
<P>
	Hewlett Packard, which helped the Dow to a 73-point gain Monday,  
plunged 5 3/4 to 104 1/2 Tuesday. After the close of trading Monday, the 
company reported earnings that beat analysts' expectations, and 
many investors chose to lock in profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Chip maker Micron Technology fell 2 13/16 to 57 3/4. But online  
brokerage ETrade rose 3 3/8 to 30 1/4 after announcing it will offer 
individual investors access to after-hours trading through 
Instinet. 
</P>
<P>
	The retail sector proved that strong earnings don't always  
guarantee a stock bounce. J.C. Penney slipped 7/16 to 42 9/16 and 
Ann Taylor fell 1 3/4 to 35 7/8 after both companies beat analysts' 
predictions for second-quarter results. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow has now closed higher for five consecutive sessions, its  
longest rally since the beginning of July. However, low volume and 
a pattern of late-day rallies suggested to some analysts that 
investors have not truly determined their own course of action, and 
may trade tentatively until the Fed's meeting is over. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market has rallied over the past few days, but on very  
light volume,'' said Ned Collins, a trader at Daiwa Securities 
America. ``There are some questions about whether this is the start 
of something major, or just a sucker's rally.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by an 8-to-5 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange. Composite volume totaled 829.61 
million shares, compared with 720.01 million in the previous 
session. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index rose 5.82 to 628.71, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index rose 3.01 to 782.51. The Russell 
2000 index of smaller companies rose 2.18 to 436.00. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.19 percent.  
Germany's DAX index rose 0.05 percent, France's CAC-40 rose 0.5 
percent, and Britain's FT-SE 100 closed 1.1 percent lower. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
