<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rubin Helps With Treasury Building </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Former Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, viewed  
on Wall Street as the golden boy of the U.S. economy, is hoping he 
still has the Midas touch. This time, he is focusing on gold leaf. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin on Tuesday joined a fund-raising drive sponsored by the  
Treasury Historical Association to raise money to restore the 
Treasury Department's historic Cash Room to the way it looked when 
Ulysses S. Grant used it for his Inaugural reception in 1869. 
</P>
<P>
	The $200,000 the association hopes to raise will provide for  
gold leaf in the Cash Room's ornate ceiling and two nearby 
staircase domes. That section of the Treasury, the third oldest 
government building in Washington after the Capitol and White 
House, was heavily damaged in a 1996 fire. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress appropriated the money to restore the building's office  
functions but left it to private donors to raise the money needed 
to replace 19th century architectural features that have been lost 
through the years. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin, who held many of his news conferences in the Cash Room,  
said he was happy to do what he could to support the restoration 
effort ``in a room with so much history.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas O'Malley, chairman of the association's board, said that  
so far $136,000 has been raised in an effort that has the support 
of nine other former Treasury secretaries. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin, who left the Cabinet in early July, said he is still  
examining his options now that he is back in private life. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it will be at least two or three months before I sort  
through what I am going to do,'' he said. Rubin said he is ruling 
out any run for public office. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
