<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Yorker Completes Magazine Move </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New Yorker magazine occupied spanking new  
quarters in a glitzy Times Square skyscraper on Monday after a 
weekend move from its old haunt on West 43rd Street. Many staff 
members celebrated -- or eased the pain -- by going on vacation. 
</P>
<P>
	The venerable literary and current affairs magazine was the last  
of 14 publications to make the move to the $500 million, 48-story 
Conde Nast building at 4 Times Square -- a structure already noted 
for a troubled construction history that cost at least two lives 
and forced the shutdown of a hit Broadway musical. 
</P>
<P>
	Considering the view from The New Yorker's new 21st floor digs,  
its haughty masthead figure, Eustace Tilley, might wish to swap his 
monocle for a pair of binoculars. 
</P>
<P>
	But whether the new state-of-the-art building passes aesthetic  
muster with the magazine that is self-appointed arbiter of what's 
good, bad and tasteful in Gotham remained to be seen; no mention of 
the move appeared in the fat August double-issue that hit 
newsstands Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	As for the staff, ``some people probably were more excited than  
others,'' said Maurie Perl, spokeswoman for Conde Nast. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Times said some staffers were ``both nostalgic and  
nervous'' and one unnamed editor described himself as ``in complete 
denial'' about the move. 
</P>
<P>
	New Yorker editor David Remnick told his staff that the  
magazine's spirit would not change just because the address did. 
``The soul (of the magazine) is its writers and artists and 
everyone who contributes to it,'' The Times quoted Remnick as 
saying. 
</P>
<P>
	The editor was among those on vacation and was not available for  
comment, Perl said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, those staffers not on vacation were unpacking boxes  
and files, some of which dated back to the magazine's original West 
43rd Street offices. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the artifacts, prized enough to be kept under guard, were  
Plexiglas-encased pieces of plaster wall with sketches by humorist 
James Thurber, who drew large because of near-blindness. 
</P>
<P>
	The New Yorker, which had moved once before, in 1991, joins such  
publications as Vanity Fair, Vogue, Glamour, GQ, House and Garden 
and Allure, most of which moved from the former Conde Nast building 
on Madison Avenue. 
</P>
<P>
	Three of the company's publications, Wired, Architectural Digest  
and Bon Appetit, are based in California but have business offices 
at 4 Times Square, Ms. Perl said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
