<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ending a Car Lease Is No Easy Chore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                        *AP Business Analyst    	
</P>
<P>
	Q: The lease on my car is about to expire. Is ending a lease as  
easy as beginning one? 

</P>
<P>
	A: Hardly.  
</P>
<P>
	The rules for returning a car at the end of a lease are  
clear-cut, but very involved. One problem faced by many lessees is 
that some of the precise details about returning a car aren't 
always spelled out in the lease document, and are not clarified 
until termination time. 
</P>
<P>
	Some details are clearly stated up front, of course, mainly the  
``termination or disposition'' fee, which generally can total 
several hundred dollars. Over the course of the lease, lessees 
sometimes overlook this final cost. 
</P>
<P>
	Understandably, any past due payments or charges, such as  
property taxes, must also be paid. And, as one termination lease 
puts it, any ``official fees and taxes due in connection with the 
termination of the lease.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Excess mileage charges will be assessed, but generally speaking,  
the lessor grants no rebate for mileage left unused, even though 
this might make the car more marketable for the lessor. 
</P>
<P>
	The area of greatest controversy might involve the lease clause  
about ``excessive wear and tear,'' which unfortunately may involve 
subjective determinations and require negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	One lease, for example, makes the lessee responsible for any  
dents, scratches or chips, and any peeling or chipping of paints 
that exceeds $100 to repair or refinish. The same standard applies 
to substandard repairs and ``damage from elements'' like sand. 
</P>
<P>
	Also added to charges under this lease are repairs for stains,  
holes, tears, rips or burns that exceed $50. Also, the estimated 
cost to repair or replace parts to meet manufacturers' standards. 
</P>
<P>
	Tire tread is measured. The detail in one common lease calls for  
the cost of replacing ``any tire tread which is less than 4/32 (or 
an eighth) of an inch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Generally, you have the choice or making repairs or leaving them  
for the lessor. If repairs are made by the lessee, the lessor may 
appraise them in accordance with its guidelines. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990817.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-17 22:30:11 </DATE_TIME>
