<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cards' Dye Has Condition Upgraded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. (AP) -- Extensive surgery to repair the right  
arm of Arizona Cardinals offensive lineman Ernest Dye produced a 
pulse on Tuesday, prompting doctors to upgrade his condition to 
serious from critical. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ernest's situation is day to day, then week to week,'' said  
Dr. Jerry Mohr, one of the surgeon's who operated on Dye for more 
than eight hours Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors reconnected the bone between the shoulder and elbow,  
then went about the precise work of repairing nerves, arteries, 
veins and other tissue. 
</P>
<P>
	After surgery, doctors could detect a pulse in Dye's arm, which  
means blood was flowing to the repaired limb. 
</P>
<P>
	``Their primary concern is to get the blood flowing and maintain  
it,'' Cardinals spokesman Greg Gladysiewski said. 
</P>
<P>
	It isn't known how long Dye will have to remain in the hospital,  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dye, defensive end Carl Simpson and offensive guard Lester  
Holmes were injured when their car overturned as they were driving 
to a team meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Dye and Simpson were thrown from the car. Holmes was the only  
one wearing a seat belt. 
</P>
<P>
	Simpson was checked for pain in his hip and released. Holmes  
received a severe cut to the forehead and was released from the 
hospital Tuesday afternoon. He returned to his Phoenix home with 
his wife and 3-week-old daughter. 
</P>
<P>
	Cardinals owner Bill Bidwell arranged for Dye's mother and wife  
to fly to Flagstaff on Tuesday and they spent much of the day at 
the hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Vince Tobin also visited the players.  
</P>
<P>
	``There was some warmth in his (Dye's) hand,'' Tobin said.  
``That means the circulation and the blood flow was restored, so 
that's good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Offensive line coach George Warhop said Dye was upbeat when he  
met with him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't sense he was in any pain,'' Warhop said. ``Ernest is  
a tough guy. They were shaken up. They were just in a huge 
accident. They weren't acting like it was Christmas or anything, 
but they were positive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The accident was the latest in a string of setbacks for Dye.  
</P>
<P>
	Dye was the Cardinals' first-round draft pick out of South  
Carolina in 1993, but was plagued by injuries. The 340-pound tackle 
left the team as a free agent in 1997 and signed with the St. Louis 
Rams. He was out of football last year following the deaths of his 
brother and father. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
