<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> PETA Steps Up Pressure on McDonald's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NORFOLK, Va. (AP) -- A group of animal rights activists is  
stepping up public pressure against McDonald's in an attempt to 
pressure the fast food chain to prevent cruelty to animals. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement came as People for the Ethical Treatment of  
Animals gave up on a two year campaign of trying to persuade 
McDonalds to ensure that the animals used for its food are killed 
without prolonged suffering and that chickens are uncaged and 
allowed to roam free. 
</P>
<P>
	The 600,000-member group accused McDonald's of a lack of  
commitment to talks between the two that is ``sad and insulting.'' 
So PETA plans to organize demonstrations, produce leaflets and take 
out advertisements to pressure the company, said Bruce Friedrich, a 
spokesman at PETA headquarters in Norfolk. 
</P>
<P>
	``McDonald's animals lead short, miserable, painful lives and  
they die violent, bloody, gruesome deaths,'' said Friedrich, PETA's 
vegetarian campaign coordinator. ``We're going to be shouting that 
from the rooftops.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A McDonald's spokesman said Tuesday that the Oak Brook,  
Ill.-based company remains committed to animal welfare, with or 
without PETA's input. 
</P>
<P>
	McDonald's already has made reforms, such as implementing  
training at suppliers' slaughterhouses and changing procedures to 
keep the animals calm before they are killed, spokesman Walt Riker 
said. The company also hired Temple Grandin, an animal welfare 
expert at Colorado State University, as a consultant. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel like we're making really good progress,'' Riker said.  
``Unfortunately, PETA apparently seems to be more interested in 
media and criticism. That's their game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	PETA also wants McDonald's to sell veggie burgers. Riker said  
some McDonald's restaurants in New York do but there are no plans 
to expand that nationwide. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
