<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Drought Dries Up Athletic Fields </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VILLANOVA, Pa. (AP) -- As Villanova football players prepare for  
their season-opener, they're stepping all over one of the hardest 
opponents they've ever faced in training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	The playing field.  
</P>
<P>
	They, and other colleges and high schools in the Northeast are  
practicing on fields as hard as concrete and scorched by one of the 
century's worst droughts. Coaches and athletic directors are 
worried that the rock-hard fields will cause injuries to players as 
they run, tackle and slide during drills. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just the pounding. The grass right now is even harder  
than the turf is,'' said Villanova coach Andy Talley. ``It's not 
the best surface to play on, but you've got to play the hand that's 
dealt to you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The hard fields prompted officials in the Philadelphia area to  
delay the start of high school football practice for two weeks, 
unless the area receives more rain soon. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, groundskeepers are brainstorming for unique solutions  
to keep their fields in tip-top condition with no more significant 
rainfall on the horizon. 
</P>
<P>
	At the University of Maryland, coaches check the fields daily to  
make sure players can use them; Maryland regulations call for 50 
percent less water to be used to water the fields. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the soil begins to crack, you get potholes that are a  
footing hazard,'' school spokesman George Cathcart said. 
</P>
<P>
	There are other worries for returning athletes, said Charlie  
Thompson, head athletic trainer at Princeton University. The 
surface will be harder on all the body's joints since the turf will 
have less of a ``bounce-back cushion'' for athletes who may be 
working through two-a-day practices under the summer sun. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fields are absolutely solid; it's just dust,'' Thompson  
said. ``It's the worst I've seen it in the 20 years I've been an 
athletic trainer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The pressure is perhaps greatest at Penn State's Beaver Stadium,  
where in less than two weeks the third-ranked Nittany Lions play 
host to No. 4 Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	While school officials say the hallowed field will stay green  
and healthy for the Aug. 28 opener, they are turning to unique 
measures to keep it that way, using treated wastewater as well as 
water first used to cool a nearby nuclear reactor. 
</P>
<P>
	``That water is not radioactive. It's not water used in the  
reactor,'' said Bill Anderson, an assistant vice president at the 
school. 
</P>
<P>
	On the high school level, most officials say it's up to  
individual schools, and not a state athletic association, to 
determine if practices should be delayed or moved. Most high 
schools have started practices for fall sports, or will be 
scheduled to start practice this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``Fields are in rough shape right now. When you start running  
athletes on them, that's when you really lose them,'' said John 
Kohler, facilities director for the Lancaster School District. 
</P>
<P>
	His district has trucked in 6,000 gallons of out-of-state water  
at a cost of $132 per watering, to save a newly renovated track and 
field being put down this month. 
</P>
<P>
	In other areas, schools say they're worried about the hard  
fields but haven't gotten many calls about it from coaches. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is an unusually dry year, and until something happens, you  
usually don't think about it until you have to,'' said Walter 
Eaton, assistant director at the New York State Public High School 
Association. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
