<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Penguins Can Stay Afloat Until Sept. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Mario Lemieux doesn't have to close on his  
plan to buy the bankrupt team by the end of the week because the 
Penguins have enough money to stay afloat through the end of 
August. 
</P>
<P>
	The team's line of credit with a French bank runs out Friday,  
but the Penguins can borrow enough money to keep running if 
Lemieux's deal doesn't close by the end of this week, said James 
Walsh, a bankruptcy lawyer representing the Penguins. 
</P>
<P>
	The team could get more money from Societe Generale, the French  
bank that has financed the team since it filed for bankruptcy in 
October, Walsh said. 
</P>
<P>
	More relief for the franchise came Tuesday night, when the  
Allegheny Regional Asset District Board voted 6-1 to earmark sales 
tax revenue to help the city and county pay $16 million in bond 
debt on the Civic Arena, where the Penguins play. 
</P>
<P>
	Two months ago, the Public Auditorium Authority agreed to take  
over debt payments on the Civic Arena owed by the team and the 
arena's landlord, SMG. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything is moving in a very positive direction with both  
investors and SMG to bring this deal to completion,'' Lemieux 
spokesman John Brabender said. 
</P>
<P>
	Stephen Leeper, executive director of the Public Auditorium  
Authority, praised the vote, which he said is a ``big step'' toward 
finalizing the deal with Lemieux. 
</P>
<P>
	``It really translates into about $1 million a year in savings  
to that franchise,'' Leeper said of the Penguins. ``That coupled 
with the SMG commitments ... will really put that franchise on 
stable ground.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gordon St. Denis, director of the sports advisory group at SG  
Cowen, the French bank's subsidiary, said lending officials were 
aware that the deal might not be finalized by the end of the week. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to do whatever is in the best interest to keep the  
franchise in Pittsburgh and maintain the franchise value,'' St. 
Denis said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux needs $50 million in outside private investments to  
finance his takeover. A list circulated to prospective investors 
showed $51.4 million in commitments, but listed $5 million coming 
from a party ``to be announced,'' the Pittsburgh Post-Gazette 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Brabender said that money was in escrow with Lemieux's group and  
represents an actual investor. He was not sure why the investor's 
name had not been listed. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Rooney, nephew of late Pittsburgh Steelers founder Art  
Rooney, Sr., is a candidate to run the Penguins' business 
operations when Lemieux's deal closes. 
</P>
<P>
	Rooney told the Pittsburgh Tribune-Review that he recently  
interviewed with Lemieux. His job title with the team would likely 
be chief operating officer. General manager Craig Patrick would 
continue to run the hockey side of the operation. Lemieux's lawyer, 
Chuck Greenberg, declined comment. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
