<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> State Won't Have to Defend Nichols </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- A judge ordered the hiring of private  
attorneys at state expense to defend Terry Nichols in the Oklahoma 
City bombing Tuesday after the state public defenders agency said 
it didn't have enough money to represent him. 
</P>
<P>
	State District Judge Robert M. Murphy Jr. agreed Tuesday to let  
the Oklahoma Indigent Defense System withdraw from the case and 
ruled that the state Judicial Fund -- made up of excess court fees -- 
would be used to pay private attorneys to represent Nichols 
instead. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Bednar, executive director of public defenders agency, said  
the decision assures money will be available for Nichols' defense 
when he goes on trial on state murder charges, probably in about a 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The last thing in the world we want to look like in Oklahoma''  
are rednecks who ``want to kill Terry Nichols and not pay for his 
defense,'' Bednar said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Legislature set aside $1 million in 1998 to pay for Nichols'  
defense at his state trial, but the Legislature earlier this year 
withdrew $900,000 of that to help tornado victims instead. Bednar's 
group then asked to withdraw because it couldn't afford to 
represent Nichols. 
</P>
<P>
	The Judicial Fund is expected to have about $2.7 million  
available for the trial. Estimates are Nichols' defense could cost 
$5 million over two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Nichols is charged in state court with 160 counts of  
first-degree murder in the April 19, 1995, bombing of the Alfred P. 
Murrah Federal Building. He could get the death penalty. 
</P>
<P>
	Nichols is serving a life sentence in Colorado after being  
convicted on federal charges of conspiracy and involuntary 
manslaughter in the attack. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter to the judge, Nichols asked to keep the public  
defender who had been appointed to him. Murphy said no decision had 
been made but the possibility had not been ruled out. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
