<HEADLINE> Island Evacuated As Hurricane Nears </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JOHNSTON ISLAND (AP) -- Anticipating a close strike by Hurricane  
Dora, the U.S. Army today was evacuating the last of 1,100 military 
and civilian personnel from this small central Pacific island where 
old chemical weapons are destroyed. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials closed tanks and lines in the incinerator used to  
dispose of the toxic chemicals and secured the rest of the weapons 
in storm-proof bunkers as Dora approached the island, part of a 
four-island atoll 825 miles southwest of Honolulu. 
</P>
<P>
	The center of the storm initially was expected to pass 7 miles  
north of the island late tonight, close enough for National Weather 
Service forecaster Jeff Powell to call it a direct hit. Today, the 
storm was on a path that would put it 60 miles south of the island 
tonight, but that did not amount to a reprieve, the weather service 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Johnston Island will be on the bad side of it,'' forecaster  
Hans Rosendal said. ``They will get a lot of wind and rain and wave 
action.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Army decided early today to remove the last 200-some workers  
who were not evacuated Monday, said spokesman John Fairbank. 
</P>
<P>
	Evacuees were being flown to Hickam Air Force Base near  
Honolulu. 
</P>
<P>
	Also being evacuated were workers from the U.S. Fish and  
Wildlife Service, which operates a bird refuge on the atoll. 
</P>
<P>
	Dora had maximum sustained wind of about 85 mph with some higher  
gusts, compared with about 105 mph early Monday, Rosendal said. It 
was not expected to weaken any more in the next day. 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasters predicted waves of up to 12 feet, raising concerns  
about flooding on Johnston Island, which has a high point of only 7 
feet. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're not worried so much about winds as they are concerned  
about storm surge and seas,'' Powell said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
