<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pasta King Barilla Opens U.S. Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMES, Iowa (AP) -- Deep in the heart of corn country, a new  
factory processes thousands of bushels of grain a day, but it is 
not the commodity for which Iowa is known. It is durum wheat, 
shipped hundreds of miles from the fields of Arizona, the Dakotas 
and Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	The wheat is processed in central Iowa by Barilla, the world's  
largest pasta maker, into 22 different kinds of pasta. 
</P>
<P>
	The Parma, Italy-based company announced in 1997 that it had  
chosen Ames for its first U.S. factory. Its new 510,000-square-foot 
plant, mill and warehouse went into full production in June. 
</P>
<P>
	Barilla officials say they were sold on Ames by the Iowa work  
ethic, a central U.S. location, proximity to two major interstate 
highways and a rail line, and $6 million in local and state 
incentives. 
</P>
<P>
	``We did a national search of where to locate the plant and Ames  
really came out on top,'' said Dave Bramow, plant manager. ``With 
the combination of the highway and the rail traffic, it was just a 
real fit for us. 
</P>
<P>
	``Iowa is really an agribusiness area. And even though it's  
corn, it's still agriculture driven,'' he said. ``To bring wheat 
here, it really wasn't unknown to a lot of people in Iowa.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For years, Barilla shipped durum wheat grown in the United  
States and Canada to Italy and other European countries to be 
processed into pasta. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, it's a much shorter trip to ship that wheat to Iowa, where  
the Barilla plant can be seen for miles by drivers on the 
Interstate. 
</P>
<P>
	Barilla has taken full advantage of the opportunity, painting  
its distinctive red-white-and-blue logo on both sides of its mill, 
a building several stories high flanked by towering silos on one 
end of the factory. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ames plant, an exact duplicate of a new Barilla plant in  
Foggia, Italy, has a warehouse on the other end, from which it 
supplies pasta to wholesalers throughout the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	In the middle of the plant are the production and packaging  
areas, where water, a few vitamins and semolina -- wheat ground 
finer than flour -- are turned into the company's signature products 
and put into colorful boxes. 
</P>
<P>
	The plant is remarkably empty of people. Just 102 workers cover  
shifts that run 24 hours a day, seven days a week. A sophisticated 
computer system eliminates much of the need for hands-on work. 
</P>
<P>
	Coils of black computer cables snake throughout the plant,  
allowing production workers in a glass-enclosed computer lab to 
point and click their way through many maintenance checks of the 
lines. 
</P>
<P>
	``Thirty years ago, what now takes about 3 1/2 hours on our  
short-goods line used to take over 24 hours,'' production manager 
Bob Johnson said as he watched automated cutters chop thousands of 
pieces of campanelle pasta, which resemble tiny rosettes. 
</P>
<P>
	The short goods include campanelle and penne pasta, while  
spaghetti and fettuccine are typical long goods. 
</P>
<P>
	The plant can turn out 54,000 boxes of pasta each hour and about  
200 million pounds each year. Three production lines now are in 
use, with room for another if it is needed. 
</P>
<P>
	The Barilla family began its business in Italy in 1877. Barilla  
chairman Guido Barilla, 41, is the fourth generation of his family 
to lead the company. 
</P>
<P>
	Barilla now employs about 7,000 people worldwide and has annual  
sales of more than $2 billion. The company has nine 
pasta-manufacturing plants, with six in Italy, one in Greece, one 
in Turkey and one in Ames. Barilla sells its products in more than 
100 countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Barilla began shipping pasta to the United States in 1995 and  
began a national advertising campaign in March 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Gruca, an associate professor of marketing at Iowa State  
University who follows the pasta industry, said Barilla is making a 
strategic move by focusing on U.S. consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's only so much growth that you can get in Europe,'' he  
said. ``In the U.S., we eat significantly less pasta, but people 
feel very positively about it. It's considered a healthy food. 
Because of that, the trend is moving up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't really be an international brand unless you're in  
the United States because we're a huge, huge market,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gruca said Barilla also makes itself over into an American  
company by opening plants in this country, a move that could allow 
it to get around some import restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the U.S. Department of Commerce, companies that  
manufactured dry macaroni, spaghetti, vermicelli and noodles 
shipped out products worth $1.4 billion in 1992, the latest year 
for which figures are available. 
</P>
<P>
	Guido Barilla said during opening ceremonies in June that 90  
percent of U.S. retail outlets, or about 25,000 stores nationwide, 
now carry the company's product. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicos Sophocleous, general manager of Barilla America Inc., said  
the Ames plant should help the company make more inroads in the 
U.S. market. 
</P>
<P>
	``Based on consumption, the U.S. pasta market is second only to  
Italy,'' Sophocleous said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
