<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Factions of Indian Tribe Face Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOUNT PLEASANT, Mich. (AP) -- Opposing factions of the Saginaw  
Chippewa Indian Tribe faced off at tribal headquarters Tuesday 
without the violence that had been feared by some tribal members. 
</P>
<P>
	Council members removed from power last week by the federal  
government tried Tuesday to enter the building where their 
replacements were meeting. But tribal police blocked the building 
and turned them away. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal Bureau of Indian Affairs last Tuesday took the  
unusual step of intervening to recognize the new tribal council, 
citing the ousted tribal leadership's refusal to step down after 
losing four elections. 
</P>
<P>
	The ousted council claims that Kevin Gover, assistant secretary  
for Indian Affairs with the BIA, does not have the right to select 
leaders. They say he used the results of a tainted primary election 
to choose their replacements. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, members of the ousted leadership council plan to  
go to court in Bay City, where they have filed a federal lawsuit 
charging the BIA with overstepping its authority. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, they continued their struggle to regain power in  
Mount Pleasant. 
</P>
<P>
	About 150 people on both sides of the debate stood by and dozens  
more working inside pressed against windows as expelled leaders 
asked police to let them in. Supporters of the expelled leaders 
carried signs criticizing the new council and the BIA. 
</P>
<P>
	Ousted Chief Kevin Chamberlain said he was not advocating  
violence, but wanted to know why he couldn't enter his office. 
</P>
<P>
	Ron Jackson, spokesman for the new tribe, said Chamberlain was  
just staging a ``media circus'' by inviting the press to witness 
the confrontation. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're just dealing with a faction that can't stand losing  
four elections,'' Jackson said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
