<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dalai Lama Visits Indiana Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BLOOMINGTON, Ind. (AP) -- The Dalai Lama hopes his visit to this  
college town scarred by a deadly hate crime can inspire greater 
peace and harmony in the world. 
</P>
<P>
	Aside from using his visit to teach the Kalachakra Initiation --  
a revered Buddhist ritual for world peace -- the 1989 Nobel Peace 
Prize laureate also planned to participate in a panel discussion 
today on youth violence with former FBI Director William Sessions 
and others. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all have genuine, warm, human feelings. ... Humanity really  
needs that,'' he told about 200 supporters Monday night at a 
$500-a-plate dinner at Indiana University's Tibetan Cultural 
Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday marked the first day of a nearly two-week visit by the  
Dalai Lama to Bloomington, where today he will began teaching the 
Kalachakra. It will be the 25th time he has led the ritual whose 
name mean ``cycles of time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His visit to Bloomington, where his older brother lives, comes  
about six weeks after a white supremacist shot and killed a Korean 
graduate student outside a church in the southern Indiana city. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Monday, during a news conference in Indianapolis, the  
Dalai Lama said schools and media bear some of the responsibility 
for the culture of violence in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Schools pay great attention to developing intelligence, but  
``not enough attention for development of (a) warm heart,'' said 
the monk. He is the 14th Dalai Lama and as such is considered a 
reincarnation of the Buddha of compassion. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the media presents so much violence that some people  
take it for granted as human nature. 
</P>
<P>
	``So everybody has a responsibility, and also everybody has a  
potential to make a contribution for better society,'' he said. 
``So let us try to make common effort for transformation of better 
society, happier society.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As many as 5,000 people, some from as far away as Japan and  
Taiwan, are expected to attend daily sessions of the Kalachakra. 
The event is open to non-Buddhists. 
</P>
<P>
	The ceremony involves the creation of a mandala, a painting  
crafted from colored sand, representing a four-faced god with 24 
arms who subdues violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Daily admission to the Kalachakra is $50, although students, the  
elderly and Tibetans can get in for $40. The money will go to 
underwrite the cost of the Kalachakra ceremony and the Dalai Lama's 
visit, which organizers said exceeds $2 million. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
