<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Sheds 12.35 in Afternoon Trading / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were narrowly mixed today as a government  
report of a mild increase in consumer prices failed to hearten 
investors. Hewlett Packard, which soared on Monday, dragged 
blue-chips lower amid profit-taking today. 
</P>
<P>
	At 2 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 12.35 at 11,034.44. The index gave up an earlier gain of 
nearly 65 points, leading some analysts to suggest that the market 
remains troubled by worries that the Federal Reserve will raise 
interest rates in an effort to stifle inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were moving between modest gains and  
losses. In early afternoon, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 
2.37 at 1,333.14, and the Nasdaq composite index was up 4.12 at 
2,649.40. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market has rallied over the past few days, but on very  
light volume,'' said Ned Collins, a trader at Daiwa Securities 
America. ``There are some questions about whether this is the start 
of something major, or just a sucker's rally.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks initially rose today after the Labor Department said its  
Consumer Price Index, a closely watched gauge of inflation, rose 
0.3 percent in July. That matched analysts' expectations, and 
raised hopes that the Fed will take a moderate course in setting 
interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed raised short-term rates in June, and has indicated it  
will do so again if policy-makers determine higher rates would keep 
inflation at bay. The central bank's Open Market Committee will 
meet Aug. 24, and many analysts expect the group to raise rates a 
quarter-percentage point. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's report suggested that one increase may be enough,  
analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The biggest concern before today was that the Fed would keep  
pushing that interest rate lever, raising rates higher and 
higher,'' said Joseph V. Battipaglia, chief investment strategist 
at Gruntal &AMP; Co. ``That no longer seems to be the case.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The CPI report helped boost prices in the inflation-sensitive  
bond market. The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond dropped to 6.01 
percent from 6.08 percent late Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial services stocks, among the first to be affected by  
interest rate fluctuations, rose today. American Express gained 3 1/8 
to 139. 
</P>
<P>
	But those gains were outweighed by some major losses in the  
technology sector. 
</P>
<P>
	Hewlett Packard, which helped the Dow to a 73-point gain Monday,  
fell 5 1/16 to 105 3/16 today. After the close of trading Monday, 
the computer maker reported earnings that beat analysts' 
expectations, and many investors chose to take profits today. Also, 
some unpublished estimates had called for even stronger numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	Chip maker Micron Technology fell 2 3/8 to 58 3/16.  
</P>
<P>
	But online brokerage ETrade rose 1 15/16 to 28 13/16 after  
announcing it will offer individual investors access to after-hours 
trading through Instinet. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 7-to-6 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 464.10 million 
shares, well ahead of Monday's quiet pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was up 1.11 at 624.00, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index was down 1.08 at 778.42. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 0.21 to 433.61.  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
