<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-17 16:31:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Money Dispute Threatens Ryder Cup  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Get ready for the greatest event left in golf.  
</P>
<P>
	The prize for winning next month's matches is not a green  
jacket, a claret jug or even something called the Wanamaker. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a cup.  
</P>
<P>
	Actually, it looks like any other trophy, only this has some  
history. The cup was donated by a golf enthusiast in the 1920s who 
wanted to encourage competition between the best players on both 
sides of the Atlantic Ocean. 
</P>
<P>
	This is about team. About pride. About patriotism. It is a  
chance every two years for a select group of players to represent 
the Stars and Stripes without getting a dime. 
</P>
<P>
	It's one thing to be staring over Rae's Creek at the 12th green  
on Augusta National, trying to protect a one-stroke lead on Sunday. 
The pressure can be just as great standing over a 6-foot putt with 
your teammates -- your country -- counting on you. 
</P>
<P>
	If that sounds enticing, then book a flight to Scotland.  
</P>
<P>
	The Walker Cup begins Sept. 11.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest fear at the start of the season was that money would  
ruin golf, but not many had the Ryder Cup in mind. 
</P>
<P>
	Forget the $134 million purse on the PGA Tour or the $5 million  
World Golf Championship events that supposedly were going to cause 
players to reduce their schedules. 
</P>
<P>
	The number that ruined golf is $63 million, the estimated  
revenue from the Ryder Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	The debate is whether the players, those ultimately responsible  
for such revenues, should get a portion of the $23 million in 
profits to give to the charity of their choice -- or whether they 
should just shut up and play. 
</P>
<P>
	But without such a shocking figure, there would be no debate at  
all. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they were getting $1 million, that wouldn't change too many  
people's thoughts,'' Fred Couples said last week. ``But $63 million 
is a lot of money for a golf event, I can tell you that. I'd like 
to run it for a few years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before anyone suggests that U.S. players are greedy, keep in  
mind they are independent contractors whose pay is determined by 
their play. The top two players in the world, Tiger Woods and David 
Duval, each have made over $3 million this year -- 179 baseball 
players make at least that much. 
</P>
<P>
	As for the greed, does anyone really think Woods needs to be  
paid for playing in the Ryder Cup. Can anyone find where Duval ever 
said he wanted to be paid? 
</P>
<P>
	This is not about compensation, it's about control.  
</P>
<P>
	The PGA of America pumps $12.5 million into programs to ``grow  
the game of golf.'' Duval only wonders why a small portion can't go 
to a library or a soccer field in his community. 
</P>
<P>
	The precedent comes from the Presidents Cup, which allocated  
$100,000 to each player for them to designate to a charity of their 
choice. If PGA Tour commissioner Tim Finchem were in charge of the 
PGA of America, there probably would not have been a Tuesday night 
meeting at Medinah -- or a controversy. He specializes in putting 
out fires, and this one is out of control. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Ryder Cup captain Tom Kite saw the first sparks two years  
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told the PGA after (Valderrama) they'd better do something  
to fix this situation,'' Kite told Golf World magazine. ``I'm 
surprised they didn't. Something has to happen now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Something already has.  
</P>
<P>
	The Ryder Cup is tainted by money.  
</P>
<P>
	Woods and Sergio Garcia put on such a show in the PGA  
Championship that the controversy was forgotten, but not for long. 
It will be there next week at the NEC Invitational, the $5 million 
event where Ryder Cup players supposedly get rewarded for making 
the team. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Americans win back the cup, they will be perceived as  
greedy. If they lose, they will be crucified. No matter the 
outcome, the Ryder Cup will be remembered for the money -- $63 
million this year, who knows how much in 2003. 
</P>
<P>
	The only way to stop this is for the Americans to start beating  
the pants off Europe like they did for 50 years, when the Ryder Cup 
was about competition and not cash flow. 
</P>
<P>
	That would keep the PGA of America from raising the price tag on  
corporate hospitality, and it would keep the players from raising 
their eyebrows over where all the money is going. The PGA would 
have less to spend on the growth of golf, but the game has managed 
to survive just fine for 500 years. 
</P>
<P>
	With so much focus on money, and a backlash of disgust by the  
American public, some have suggested rooting for Europe next month 
at The Country Club. 
</P>
<P>
	But there's another alternative.  
</P>
<P>
	Go Matt Kuchar! You da man, Tom McKnight! Keep that Walker Cup  
in America. 
</P>
<P>
	It may be the most valuable cup left.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
