<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ripken May Stay Longer on DL </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Cal Ripken was eligible to come off the  
disabled list Tuesday, but it appears as if it will be several more 
days before he rejoins the Baltimore Orioles and resumes his quest 
for his 400th career homer. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken hasn't played since July 31 because of nerve irritation  
in his lower back. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just a matter of showing a little patience,'' he said.  
``It continues to improve. ... The big concern is that if I start 
back too soon it could drop me back to square one. I was hopeful 
and optimistic ... that I was going to be able to play today. I'm a 
little disappointed with that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The good news is that, for the moment, Ripken has dismissed back  
surgery as an option. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no indication now that that even has to be  
considered,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	It's the second stint on the disabled list this season for  
Ripken, who played in a major league record 2,632 consecutive games 
before voluntarily ending the streak last September. He had never 
been on the disabled list before this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Before I could will myself through things and you had some  
latitude. With this, I don't have much latitude,'' he said. ``The 
nerve irritation I feel is constant. When that goes away, that'll 
be my sign to start doing stuff.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Until that time, Orioles manager Ray Miller will continue to  
alternate Ryan Minor and Jeff Reboulet at third base. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's still a little irritation there,'' Miller said.  
``Until I see him take ground balls and grab a bat, I can't make 
any predictions (when he'll be back).'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken hit his 399th career homer on July 25, then went five  
straight days without a home run. He is also just 32 hits short of 
3,000. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
