<HEADLINE> Aaron Leads Ruth in All-Century Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Hank Aaron leads Babe Ruth by just over 2,000  
votes in the lastest results of the Major League Baseball 
All-Century team voting released on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Aaron, whose career 755 home runs broke Ruth's record of 714,  
has 300,531 to 298,476 for Ruth in the closest race on the ballot. 
Third place belongs to Ted Williams, basesball's last .400 hitter, 
with 291,496, just ahead of Willie Mays, who has 289,888. 
</P>
<P>
	Pete Rose, baseball's alltime hits leader, but who is on the  
sport's disqualified list because of gambling, is ninth with 
159,650. 
</P>
<P>
	In balloting conducted by Mastercard that ends Sept. 19, fans  
vote for two players at each infield poition, two catchers, six 
pitchers and nine outfielders. 
</P>
<P>
	Other leaders are catcher Johnny Bench (258,903); first baseman  
Lou Gehrig (313,137); second baseman Jackie Robinson (206,993); 
shortstop Cal Ripken, Jr., (178,594); third baseman Mike Schmidt 
(217,886); and pitchers Nolan Ryan (259,079) and Sandy Koufax 
(252,639). 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
