<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ban on Story Over Sealed Suit Lifted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A judge has withdrawn an order blocking the  
Los Angeles Daily Journal from publishing a story about a lawsuit 
that was mistakenly unsealed. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Reginald Dunn had refused Friday to lift another judge's  
restraining order that would have put the legal newspaper at risk 
of contempt of court if it ran the story. But Dunn reconsidered 
Monday and removed the ban, said Jonathan Levey, a lawyer for the 
newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	A state appellate court had asked for written arguments by  
Tuesday on whether the order violated freedom of the press. 
</P>
<P>
	A lawsuit was filed June 8 in Superior Court and was  
automatically sealed for 60 days under a state law covering certain 
insurance-related cases, the Daily Journal said. The law gives 
prosecutors time to review the private claims and decide if they 
want to join the civil suit or file criminal charges. 
</P>
<P>
	At the district attorney's request, Dunn extended the seal for  
another 90 days on July 29. But the suit was briefly made public 
last Wednesday ``through inadvertence and clerical error,'' court 
administrators said. 
</P>
<P>
	A Daily Journal reporter found the suit while reviewing court  
filings and contacted defendants, who said they were unaware of it. 
The newspaper said it was contacted Thursday by a state insurance 
fraud supervisor who confirmed that the state was conducting a 
criminal investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper planned a story Friday, but was blocked by the  
restraining order issued late Thursday by Judge Victor Chavez. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
