<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sound Bites: Audio Reviews </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	``Til The Medicine Takes'' (Capricorn Records) -- Widespread  
Panic 

</P>
<P>
	Coming out of the same college town that spawned R.E.M. and the  
B-52s, Widespread Panic has built a devoted following. But on ``Til 
The Medicine Takes,'' the band once hailed as the next Grateful 
Dead refocuses itself and its songs to make itself more appealing 
to pop audiences already familiar with its Athens, Ga., brethren -- 
with frustratingly mixed results. 
</P>
<P>
	Make no mistake, the sound -- a cross between the Southern rock  
of the '70s and psychedelia of the '60s -- will be familiar to 
longtime Spreadheads. But while each tune is shortened to managable 
lengths, the album is certainly no hit-single factory. 
</P>
<P>
	That's not necessarily a bad thing, as shown on ``Climb To  
Safety.'' With its harmony, power-chord hook and ragged electric 
piano, the pulsating tale of a scary train ride is the closest 
Widespread Panic can come to even approaching a Top 40 sound while 
retaining its distinctive style. 
</P>
<P>
	At least Widespread Panic can't be faulted for trying something  
new. 
</P>
<P>
	--James Pilcher, Associated Press Writer.  


</P>
<P>
	``Rough Harvest'' (Mercury Records) -- John Mellencamp  

</P>
<P>
	What appears on the surface as a throwaway project by one of the  
most prolific artists of the last two decades instead displays new 
weightiness in John Mellencamp's work. 
</P>
<P>
	Using stripped-down arrangements, Mellencamp offers socially  
challenging songs such as ``Love and Happiness'' and ``Jackie 
Brown,'' and the gravel in his voice -- the result of a lot of hard 
touring and even harder living in his early days -- doesn't do any 
harm to ``Minutes to Memories,'' a tale of an old man telling his 
life story on a bus ride through the Midwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Not that it's all serious. Mellencamp covers ``Under the  
Boardwalk'' and gets the carefree tone just right. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By James Pilcher, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
