<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Law Would Protect Computer Buyers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALLENTOWN, Pa. (AP) -- A state legislator wants to create a law  
to give Pennsylvania consumers greater legal protection if their 
Apple turns into a lemon or if their IBM is DOA. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. T.J. Rooney says his computer lemon law is the first  
proposal of its kind in the nation. He said he will introduce it 
this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``This will tilt the scales in favor of the computer consumers  
who presently have the decks stacked against them,'' said Rooney. 
He would speak only in broad terms about the bill. Rooney is 
expected to announced the bill in detail Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	He did say that the bill will closely follow the state's  
existing Automobile Lemon Law. Under that statute, new car dealers 
can be forced to buy back an automobile in certain cases in which a 
defect cannot be properly repaired. Similar protections were 
extended several years ago to those who buy dogs that later become 
ill under the so-called Puppy Lemon Law. 
</P>
<P>
	Most computer buyers spend more than $2,500 on a new system,  
after when adding software and components such as printers and 
scanners, Rooney said, making a computer among their top 
investments, next to a home and car. 
</P>
<P>
	And a growing number of buyers are finding that although most  
machines have warranties, some aren't worth the paper they're 
written on because of manufacturers refusing to back up their 
products, said Rooney. 
</P>
<P>
	``Consumers have little or no recourse when dealing with  
products that don't live up to warranties,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is designed to help people like Mike Hilton of  
Bethlehem, whose purchase of a personal computer two years ago has 
turned into ``an endless nightmare.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since first plugging it in, ``Basically, every major part has  
been replaced at least once,'' said Hilton, the director of 
investor relations for Air Products and Chemicals. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the repairs were covered under warranty, Hilton said  
the computer still doesn't work right and the maker has refused to 
replace it. 
</P>
<P>
	``There has to be something to hold manufacturers accountable  
for their products,'' said Hilton, who contacted Rooney about his 
problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Problems like those are increasing as the family computer  
becomes a necessity in most households, said Craig Thor Kimmel, a 
Montgomery County lawyer who specializes in car lemon law cases. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot more people are getting the run-around,'' said Kimmel,  
who helped Rooney draft the legislation. Kimmel said the bill will 
provide uniform rules computer makers and retailers ``have to play 
by.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
