<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> European Share Prices Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- European shares closed mostly higher Tuesday, with  
banking and financial services shares gaining support from U.S. 
consumer price data. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Ciba Specialty Chemicals fell 4 percent to 120 Swiss  
francs, however, after the company released weaker-than-expected 
first-half results. The investment bank Paribas said it was 
maintaining its sell stance on the stock. 
</P>
<P>
	In spite of bad news from Ciba, some observers said the chemical  
sector might have bottomed out in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	``With the U.S. on a steady noninflationary growth path, Asia  
recovering and European economies picking up, we believe the 
recovery in chemicals is at hand,'' said Jeremy Batstone, head of 
research at NatWest Stockbrokers. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. July consumer price index showed an increase of 0.3  
percent, which is what the market expected, and that eased some 
concern about inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of 592 European companies closed up  
0.5 points at 306.28. The chemicals index was the worst performer, 
with a drop of 1 percent, while the insurance index was the best, 
up 1.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In France, Paribas rose 2.4 percent and Banque Nationale de  
Paris moved up 1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	French regulatory authorities were meeting later Tuesday and  
again next week to decide on the future of all three banks, 
following BNP's six-month battle to gain full control of Paribas 
and Societe Generale. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index, which tracks 297 companies in  
countries that joined the single currency, closed up 1.80 points at 
320.82. The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 50 Index ended up 23.21 points at 
3,747.89, while the DJ Stoxx 50 Index closed up 8.55 points at 
3,679.79. 
</P>
<P>
	In domestic markets, Frankfurt's Xetra DAX index closed up 0.05  
percent to 5,259.91 the Paris CAC-40 index rose 0.5 percent to 
4,479.75 and London's Financial Times-Stock Exchange index slumped 
1.1 percent to 6,166.40. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
