<HEADLINE> Internet Mutual Funds Pose Dilemma </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Mutual funds that focus on technology pose a  
dilemma for investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Should they shoot for the moon and put money in funds that  
invest primarily in volatile Internet stocks? Or should they play 
it safe by investing in broad-based technology funds that may 
include risky Internet stocks, but that also hold blue-chip 
technology firms, such as Microsoft Inc. and Intel Inc? 
</P>
<P>
	What it basically comes down to is: ``How much emotional risk  
and pocketbook risk is the investor willing to endure?'' said Geoff 
Bobroff, an East Greenwich, R.I.-based mutual fund consultant. 
</P>
<P>
	The two opposing sides of the technology dilemma were never more  
apparent than earlier this month, when Internet stocks, which had 
been slipping gradually for months, suddenly fell, dragging down 
the performances of funds that track them. 
</P>
<P>
	One such fund, Monument's Internet Fund, fell 37 percent between  
mid-April, when many Internet stocks had reached all-time highs, 
and Aug. 4, when it looked like the bottom had fallen out. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the WWW Internet fund, a broader fund whose portfolio  
includes a number of time-tested companies -- such as Microsoft 
Corp., Intel Corp. and Sun Microsystems Inc. -- fell just 20 percent 
during the same period, according to Morningstar Inc., a Chicago 
firm that tracks mutual fund performance. 
</P>
<P>
	Ironically, WWW Internet was considered a ``real laggard when  
Internet stocks were going great guns'' early in 1999, said 
Christine Benz, domestic equity fund editor at Morningstar. 
</P>
<P>
	In the not-too-distant past, the phenomenal rise of unproven  
Internet stocks wouldn't have posed a problem for investors and 
fund managers. The stocks probably would have been ignored, 
according to longtime fund watchers. 
</P>
<P>
	Mutual funds were generally considered long-term investments,  
and consequently the portfolios generally stuck to companies whose 
futures were essentially guaranteed. 
</P>
<P>
	But that's no longer the case.  
</P>
<P>
	There are now over 7,500 mutual funds to select from, up from  
564 in 1980, according to the Investment Company Institute, an 
industry trade group in Washington, D.C. 
</P>
<P>
	The public's growing appetite for mutual funds has allowed fund  
companies to become creative, spawning numerous funds that focus 
primarily on thin slices of the overall market, such as the 
Internet sector. 
</P>
<P>
	And as the focus of mutual funds become more concentrated,  
investors have increasingly had to decide whether they want their 
investments to grow slowly and steadily, or rapidly and with gusto. 
</P>
<P>
	Bobroff said there are several risks inherent to investing in  
narrowly focused stock funds. For instance, investors tend to flee 
sectors all at once, he said, driving down stocks in that sector 
across the board, which means that a mutual fund that is narrow in 
focus will plummet if that group becomes unpopular for whatever 
reasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``The downsides can be very dramatic,'' Bobroff said.  
</P>
<P>
	Moreover, Internet stocks are particularly vulnerable to wild  
swings because they are a favorite target of so-called day traders, 
or amateur investors who play the market on the Internet and try to 
make money by buying and selling shares of rapidly moving stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Another advantage to broad-based technology funds is that if  
investors pull their money out of the Internet sector, it is likely 
to be shifted into some other technology sector, said Bobroff, 
which means a broad-based technology mutual fund will hold up 
better if one area of the technology sector falls out of favor. 
</P>
<P>
	 *End advance for use anytime    	

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
