<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Releases Media Software </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	REDMOND, Wash. (AP) -- Microsoft on Tuesday released a major  
upgrade of its software designed to play sound and video as it is 
sent in ``streams'' over the Internet. It's the company's latest 
bid to capture some of the customer base held by Seattle competitor 
RealNetworks. 
</P>
<P>
	The program, Windows Media Technologies 4.0, offers the sound  
quality of a compact disc and better video quality than in previous 
versions, said Will Poole, general manager of marketing and 
business development for Microsoft's streaming media division. 
</P>
<P>
	The software allows users to download music from the Internet as  
computer files. It allows greater compression than MP3, a format 
backed by RealNetworks, meaning it creates smaller files and uses 
less computer memory per song. 
</P>
<P>
	Sony Music and Warner Music Group are offering digital Internet  
downloads of some artists' music using the Microsoft software. 
</P>
<P>
	RealNetworks, whose RealPlayer G2 software holds a commanding  
lead in number of users, doesn't view the upgrade as a major 
challenge. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're always trying to play catch up, and they're always  
three steps behind,'' RealNetworks spokesman Jay Wampold said. 
</P>
<P>
	RealNetworks' share of streaming media usage runs from 65  
percent to 85 percent, depending on how the market is evaluated. 
Poole estimated that by the end of the year, half of all users 
would be using Microsoft's technology. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
