<HEADLINE> Politics 2000 Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore is viewed favorably by  
more than two-thirds of blacks overall and by three-of-four blacks 
in the South, according to a new poll. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore, the Democratic front-runner in the presidential contest,  
was viewed favorably by 69 percent of blacks and unfavorably by 17 
percent, according to a poll released Monday by the Joint Center 
for Political and Economic Studies. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey was viewed favorably by  
41 percent of blacks, unfavorably by 11 percent. Forty-two percent 
said they didn't know enough about him to say. Texas Gov. George W. 
Bush, the Republican front-runner, was viewed favorably by 43 
percent and unfavorably by 34 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``In terms of the presidential contest, the support among blacks  
for Al Gore is significant, especially in the South,'' said David 
Bositis, senior political analyst for the center. Blacks make up a 
large percentage of Democratic primary voters in many Southern 
states, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, two-thirds of blacks considered themselves Democrats  
and about a fourth considered themselves independent, while 5 
percent said they were Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	The findings were based on telephone interviews with 900 black  
adults. The poll had a margin of error of plus or minus 4 
percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- With Lamar Alexander out of the  
presidential race, George W. Bush was endorsed Tuesday by 
Alexander's Tennessee campaign manager -- Gov. Don Sundquist. 
</P>
<P>
	Sundquist is the 22nd governor to back Bush's bid for the  
Republican presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	``Gov. Bush is a proven leader who has the unique ability to  
unite people and accomplish success,'' he said at a news conference 
in his Capitol office. 
</P>
<P>
	Sundquist had been Tennessee campaign manager for Alexander, who  
dropped out of the crowded GOP presidential primary field Monday 
after a disappointing sixth-place finish in Iowa's straw poll. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Bush ``is my choice now. Lamar was my choice. I talked  
to him yesterday and he had no problem with this. I've known George 
W. for a long time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush called Sundquist ``a valued colleague and a good, close  
friend.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Minutes after the news conference ended, Sundquist said he  
received a thank-you call from former President Bush, father of the 
Texas governor. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Oxford Union invited Republican  
presidential candidates Steve Forbes and George W. Bush to debate 
in England next October. Forbes said yes Tuesday, but Bush 
declined. 
</P>
<P>
	``The students of Oxford would love to see such an event, as  
American politics has become even more popular than British 
politics in Oxford,'' Ben Seifert, president of the Oxford Union 
wrote Forbes. He proposed a debate the week of Oct. 10. 
</P>
<P>
	Accepting the invitation, Forbes said, ``We need a real  
discussion about America's role in the new global economy and the 
post-Cold War.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said the Texas governor would not  
attend. ``In the month of October, you're more likely to find him 
in a place like Londonderry, N.H.,'' she said. New Hampshire holds 
the first-in-the-nation primary. 
</P>
<P>
	The Oxford Union, the debating society at Oxford University, was  
established in 1823. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
