<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                          *Carlos Cachaca    	
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Carlos Cachaca, whose graceful,  
bittersweet compositions helped bring samba out of the slums to 
become Brazil's most popular music, died Monday of pneumonia. He 
was 97. 
</P>
<P>
	Mourners flocked to his wake at the rehearsal hall of the  
Mangueira samba school, Brazil's best-known carnival group, which 
Cachaca helped to found in 1928. 
</P>
<P>
	Cachaca, whose real name was Carlos Moreira de Castro, began  
composing in 1923, when samba was still largely unknown. He picked 
up his nickname from the cane liquor that animated the late-night 
samba sessions at the Mangueira hill shantytown, or ``favela.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His compositions spoke of life in the favelas, and were  
initially frowned on by much of Brazilian society. Among his 
best-known works was Alvorada -- ``Dawn'' in Portuguese -- written in 
partnership with the composer Cartola. It begins: ``Dawn, on the 
hill, such beauty, no one weeps in sadness, no one feels 
bitterness.'' 

</P>
<P>
                            *Hugh Casson    	
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Sir Hugh Casson, the former president of the Royal  
Academy and the artistic mentor of Prince Charles, died Sunday 
after a long illness. He was 89. 
</P>
<P>
	Always modest about his own abilities, Casson headed Britain's  
oldest and most prestigious art society from 1976 to 1984. But he 
first started molding Britain's artistic taste decades earlier upon 
his 1948 appointment as director of architecture for the Festival 
of Britain. 
</P>
<P>
	Born on May 23, 1910, Casson was educated at St. John's College,  
Cambridge. After graduating, he went to Greece as a Craven Scholar 
at the British School in Athens. 
</P>
<P>
	He returned to England in 1937 and set up a private  
architectural practice with the late Christopher Nicholson. World 
War II intervened, and Casson served as a camouflage officer in the 
Air Ministry from 1940 to 1944. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Sidney Cohlan    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Dr. Sidney Cohlan, a pediatrician long  
affiliated with the New York University medical school, died 
Thursday. He was 84. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1990, Cohlan retired from private practice and as a professor  
of pediatrics at what is now NYU's Tisch Hospital, where he once 
was head of the Department of Pediatrics. 
</P>
<P>
	In the early 1950s, Cohlan discovered the birth-deforming  
effects of too much vitamin A in a pregnant woman's diet. He 
published his findings in 1953 in the journal Science. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohlan also studied the impact of the antibiotic tetracycline on  
developing bones and teeth and provided insights into the effects 
of nutritional deficiencies in young children. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Thomas H. Maren    	
</P>
<P>
	GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- Dr. Thomas H. Maren, a founder of the  
University of Florida's medical college whose research led to the 
development of a top-selling drug for glaucoma, died Sunday after a 
long illness. He was 81. 
</P>
<P>
	He gained international recognition for his pioneering  
investigation of an enzyme called carbonic anhydrase and its role 
in fluid production and flow in the eyes, brain, spinal cord and 
lymph system. 
</P>
<P>
	His discoveries paved the way for the development of new drugs  
to treat heart and kidney disease, brain fluid disorders, altitude 
sickness and glaucoma. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest and most visible outcome of his research is an eye  
drop called Trusopt, which was released by Merck &AMP; Co. in 1995. 

</P>
<P>
                             *Ion Pacea    	
</P>
<P>
	BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) -- Romanian painter Ion Pacea, whose  
images of peasant women and shepherds have been exhibited on three 
continents, died Friday after a long illness. He was 74. 
</P>
<P>
	Pacea, famed for his simple oil paintings in vivid color, was  
inspired by peasant women, shepherds, birds, flowers and other 
symbols of the Romanian countryside. 
</P>
<P>
	During his career, he participated in numerous exhibitions in  
cities all over the world. His last exhibition was at Bucharest's 
National Art Museum in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1981, he was awarded the Italian Trionfo prize. He also was  
honored with a medal from the Caravaggio cultural center in Rome. 

</P>
<P>
                             *Tang Tsou    	
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Tang Tsou, a leading expert on modern China who  
was admired for his strong sense of intellectual curiosity, died 
Aug. 7. He was 80. 
</P>
<P>
	Tsou was a longtime political science professor at the  
University of Chicago. Born in Guangzhou, China, he came to the 
University of Chicago as a student in 1941. He earned his Ph.D. in 
1951 and retired as the Homer J. Livingston Professor in Political 
Science in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	During his years in Chicago, Tsou developed a reputation as an  
independent thinker. 
</P>
<P>
	In one of his six books, ``America's Failure in China:  
1941-1950,'' Tsou took on leaders in the United States, as well as 
in mainland China and Taiwan. 
</P>
<P>
	The professor argued that ``the Nationalist government lost to  
the communists in the Chinese Civil War because the Nationalist 
government was corrupt and riven by infighting,'' said Dali Yang, a 
professor at the University of Chicago. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
