<HEADLINE> Eagles Sign Kicker Norm Johnson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BETHLEHEM, Pa. (AP) -- Searching for more consistency on long  
field goals, the Philadelphia Eagles waived placekicker Chris 
Boniol on Tuesday and signed veteran Norm Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	The Eagles signed Johnson to a two-year deal. Terms were not  
disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the league's best kickers, Johnson, 39, is entering his  
18th NFL season after a four-year stint with the Pittsburgh 
Steelers. Johnson has made 348 of 452 field-goal attempts (77.0 
percent) and 613 of 620 extra point attempts (98.3 percent) to rank 
sixth on the NFL's career scoring list with 1,657 points. He hasn't 
missed a point-after kick since 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	In 16 career postseason games, Johnson has connected on 20 of 26  
field goals and 34 of 35 extra points. 
</P>
<P>
	Last season, Johnson was 26-of-31 overall and 11-of-14 from 40  
through 49 yards. Boniol was 7-of-20 from 40-49 yards the last two 
seasons with the Eagles. 
</P>
<P>
	``Norm, we felt, has proven his consistency and so we decided to  
bring him in and compete with David Akers for that position,'' 
coach Andy Reid said. ``It's an open competition as long as we keep 
Akers here. Obviously, we're bringing Norm in hoping that he is the 
guy.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
