<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Firestone Shutdown Blamed on Crisis / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- The Firestone Agricultural Tire Co.  
plant near Des Moines is blaming a one-week shutdown on the farm 
crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Depressed farm income has forced many farmers to cut back on  
equipment purchases, said Harvey Siegelman of the Iowa Economic 
Development Department. 
</P>
<P>
	The Firestone shutdown has idled about 1,300 production workers.  
And a union official said plant managers are looking for 234 
volunteers willing to be laid off from Sept. 1 to Dec. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Bianchi, president of United Steelworkers of America Local  
310, said about 50 other union members are already on a temporary 
voluntary layoff. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's tough,'' Bianchi said. ``But I don't know what you do.  
The poor farmers have been taking a beating.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most operations at the plant were shut down this week to reduce  
inventory and help bring production in line with reduced demand. 
Production is scheduled to resume Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Most laid-off workers can get about 80 percent of their normal  
pay through a combination of state unemployment and supplemental 
pay from the company. 
</P>
<P>
	The plant, a division of Bridgestone/Firestone Inc., based in  
Nashville, Tenn., makes large and small tires for farm equipment 
manufacturers, including Deere &AMP; Co. of Moline, Ill. The factory 
also makes individual tires sold by retail dealers. 
</P>
<P>
	Deere on Tuesday reported that its third-quarter earnings had  
taken a 76 percent plunge from the same period a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, Deere announced that its major farm-equipment plants,  
which include factories in Ankeny, Waterloo and Ottumwa, were 
scheduled to be shut down for about 25 percent of the working days 
through Oct. 31. 
</P>
<P>
	Deere recently announced retirement incentives for employees at  
its three Iowa factories, said Ken Golden, company spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, the cause of that is the continuing downturn of the  
ag economy,'' Golden said. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BELTSVILLE, Md. (AP) -- So far, this corn defies the drought, and  
it has hairy vetch to thank. 
</P>
<P>
	The legume is the key to sustaining the green sweet-corn plants  
that tower six feet above protective organic mulch in a government 
cornfield in Beltsville, Md. 
</P>
<P>
	Hairy vetch, a legume grown as a cover crop, forms a dense mat  
that lets rain or irrigation water seep in rather than flow across 
fields and erode the soil. The mulch also slows evaporation and 
supplies natural nitrogen fertilizer. 
</P>
<P>
	The 7,000-acre Beltsville Agricultural Research Center now uses  
hairy vetch to grow much of the corn needed for its livestock. 
Researchers have already developed vetch systems for tomatoes--now 
being adopted by some growers--and are testing similar cover crops 
with peppers, cantaloupes, snap beans and other vegetables. 
</P>
<P>
	Organic mulch is vital to the center's program in sustainable  
agriculture--that is, farming in ways both economical and 
environmentally friendly, and relying on renewable resources. 
</P>
<P>
	That's why biodiesel is the newest contribution to Beltsville's  
seven-year-old sustainable farming program. Beginning this month, 
biodiesel, a mix of 20 percent soybean oil and 80-percent regular 
diesel fuel, will power all farm and road crew diesel vehicles on 
the center's 6,000-acre east side. Researchers will compare the two 
fuels for engine performance and wear. The program is part of a 
federal effort to reduce reliance on petroleum while creating new 
markets for U.S. crops. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
