<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> PBS Celebrates Female Songwriters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- These titles have something special in common:  
``Don't Blame Me,'' ``Willow Weep for Me,'' ``My Silent Love'' and 
``Can't We Be Friends?'' 
</P>
<P>
	They are song standards from the 1920s and '30s, but there's  
more. At a time popular song writing was dominated by men, the 
tunes were created by women. 
</P>
<P>
	Those gifted women, lyricist Dorothy Fields and composers Ann  
Ronell, Dana Suesse and Kay Swift, are the subject of ``Yours for a 
Song: the Women of Tin Pan Alley,'' to be seen on PBS at 9 p.m. 
Wednesday as part of the American Masters series. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Women of Tin Pan Alley'' has eye-catching film clips of  
performances by Ella Fitzgerald, Joan Morris with Max Morath, 
Rosemary Clooney, Frank Sinatra, Robert White, Irene Dunne and Fred 
Astaire. One clip shows Fields with Perry Como. Michael Feinstein 
and Betty Buckley are featured in the program. 
</P>
<P>
	The show begins with ``I Can't Give You Anything but Love,  
Baby,'' Fields' first hit, written with composer Jimmy McHugh for 
the Broadway revue, ``Lew Leslie's Blackbirds of 1928.'' Fields' 
son, jazz pianist David Lahm, says she had about 450 songs 
published. When she died at 69, a new show with her lyrics was 
running on Broadway. 
</P>
<P>
	Suesse, who also wrote classical music -- two piano concertos  
were commissioned by Paul Whiteman -- is chiefly known for ``You 
Oughta Be in Pictures,'' ``My Silent Love'' and ``The Night Is 
Young and You're So Beautiful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ronell was the first woman to compose and conduct for films. Her  
``Who's Afraid of the Big Bad Wolf'' and ``Willow Weep for Me'' 
have endured. 
</P>
<P>
	Swift's still-popular songs are ``Can't We Be Friends?'' ``Can  
This Be Love?'' and ``Fine and Dandy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Swift, married three times, also had a long affair with George  
Gershwin, beginning in 1925 or '26, according to Katharine Swift 
Weber, her granddaughter, a novelist who teaches writing at Yale. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every day she'd leave her fancy townhouse and go across town  
to be rehearsal pianist for `A Connecticut Yankee.' George got her 
that job,'' Weber says. Swift began writing popular music, and so 
did her first husband, James Paul Warburg, a banker. 
</P>
<P>
	``My grandfather wrote lyrics for all her songs in that period,  
as Paul James,'' Weber says. ``It has always struck me that my 
grandfather may have thought if he couldn't hold on to his wife, 
maybe Paul James could. My grandparents wrote a Broadway musical, 
`Fine and Dandy,' in 1930, the first Broadway musical with a 
complete score by a woman. They wrote romantic songs; it's a 
touching monument to both of them trying to stay together. But her 
pull to Gershwin was too great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Her grandparents divorced in 1935, and shortly afterward  
Gershwin left New York for Hollywood. 
</P>
<P>
	``She sacrificed her career for Gershwin. She was at every  
rehearsal of `Porgy and Bess' and traveled with `Porgy' productions 
after his death,'' says Weber, who would love to see ``Fine and 
Dandy'' revived. 
</P>
<P>
	Fields' son Lahm says his mother's songs, all written for  
Broadway shows or movies, sought ``to bring a plot a step forward 
(and) ... tell an audience more about a character.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Fields started writing lyrics, witty verse was in vogue  
around New York, Lahm says. ``The American musical, radio and 
recording were coming alive. Music was something young people were 
excited about because it fit their need to have a world of their 
own.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fields showed songwriter J. Fred Coots her song lyrics at a  
party and he introduced her to McHugh, Lahm says. 
</P>
<P>
	She wrote for 10 years with McHugh, then went to Hollywood and  
wrote movie musicals. Three of her seven were written with Jerome 
Kern: ``Swing Time,'' ``I Dream Too Much'' and ``The Joy of 
Living.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She went back to Broadway and wrote ``Stars in Your Eyes,'' for  
Jimmy Durante and Ethel Merman, with Arthur Schwartz, ``Up in 
Central Park'' with Sigmund Romberg and ``Arms and the Girl'' with 
Morton Gould. She co-wrote the book of ``Annie Get Your Gun,'' as 
well as a TV spectacular, ``Junior Miss.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lahm, who writes songs for a cabaret act he does with his wife  
and whose latest CD is of Joni Mitchell songs, remains his mother's 
admirer. 
</P>
<P>
	He says, ``I look up to the sky and say, `Where are you now that  
I really need some help?''' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ....  
</P>
<P>
	LOT OF HOLLYWOOD GLAMOUR: A 1930s movie studio is the setting  
for ``The Lot,'' a four-part series starring Jonathan Frakes 
(``Star Trek: The Next Generation'') debuting at 8 p.m. Thursday 
and Friday on American Movie Classics. The goings-on of fictional 
characters -- starlets, gossip reporters, studio bosses -- are woven 
with real events of 1937. Allen Garfield and Holland Taylor 
co-star. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
