<HEADLINE> Several Injured in NM Prison Riot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ESTANCIA, N.M. (AP) -- A disturbance at a private prison Tuesday  
forced authorities to call in a SWAT team and led to the injuries 
of three inmates and two guards, state police said. 
</P>
<P>
	No one was seriously injured, Sgt. Robert Holguin said. There  
were no escapes. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 75 inmates were involved in the disturbance at the  
prison 55 miles southeast of Albuquerque. Holguin said the inmates 
were contained by 9:30 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
	Holguin did not know what triggered the disturbance.  
</P>
<P>
	The prison is operated by Corrections Corporation of America,  
based in Nashville, Tenn., Holguin said. The CCA did not return 
calls placed by The Associated Press late Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The prison, with 250 employees, houses about 500 inmates, mostly  
federal prisoners. Only about 70 of the inmates are state 
prisoners, Corrections Department spokesman Gerges Scott said. 
</P>
<P>
	About 30 percent of New Mexico's 4,720 male inmates are housed  
in private prisons operated either in Estancia by CCA or in Hobbs 
or Santa Rosa by Florida-based Wackenhut Corrections Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	In its first year, the Hobbs prison has been the site of three  
inmate stabbing deaths, six nonfatal stabbings, a near-riot and 
incidents of guards allegedly using excessive force. 
</P>
<P>
	Corrections Secretary Rob Perry last week said the state was  
implementing a management plan for all prisons in New Mexico. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
