<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ford Explorer Combines SUV, Pickup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. displayed its latest attempt to  
carve a new niche out of the highly profitable light-truck segment 
Tuesday: a combination sport utility vehicle and pickup called the 
Explorer Sport Trac. 
</P>
<P>
	A prototype of the Sport Trac was first shown at the Detroit  
auto show in January. The similar production version, which goes on 
sale early next year, was unveiled to enthusiastic dealers at this 
week's annual Ford dealers meeting in Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sport Trac combines the front end and cab of a four-door,  
five-passenger Explorer SUV with a 4-foot cargo bed. The idea is to 
provide the room and comfort of an SUV with the cargo utility of a 
pickup. 
</P>
<P>
	More such vehicles are in the pipeline from Ford, and other  
automakers plan to follow in the search for the next hit product in 
the increasingly crowded U.S. truck market. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford's F-150 SuperCrew will arrive next year shortly before the  
Sport Trac. It features a shortened bed from the full-size F-150 
pickup attached to the front end and cab of the large, four-door 
Expedition SUV. Ford's also planning to offer the luxury Lincoln 
Blackwood, which will combine a short pickup bed to the front end 
and cab of the pricey Lincoln Navigator SUV. The Blackwood should 
arrive in 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	General Motors Corp.'s Cadillac division is considering an  
SUV-pickup hybrid to counter the Blackwood, though no final 
decision or time frame have been announced. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's Nissan Motor Co., meanwhile, showed a concept called the  
``SUT,'' for sport utility truck, at the Detroit show. No decision 
has been announced, but a company insider says it's likely to go 
into production as soon as 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	The idea of mating pickup beds to other vehicles is nothing new,  
however. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1960s, Ford offered the Ranchero, which combined the  
front end of a Falcon compact coupe with a pickup bed. Chevrolet 
competed during that era with the similar El Camino. Then there was 
a pickup version of the Ford Econoline van, which also was based on 
the Falcon chassis. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford expects the Sport Trac to appeal to outdoor sports  
enthusiasts and do-it-yourself homeowners. 
</P>
<P>
	It will be powered only by Ford's 4-liter V6 engine, the most  
popular engine offered on the Explorer. It will be available with 
two- or four-wheel drive and standard antilock brakes. The truck 
also can be ordered with an option that extends the bed, as well as 
a lockable cargo cover. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford has not yet announced Sport Trac prices, but it's expected  
to sell for about the same price as a four-door Explorer, 
spokeswoman Wendi Parson said. Prices of the four-door 2000 
Explorer with four-wheel-drive start at $24,565. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
