<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Crude Oil Futures Surge  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Crude oil futures prices overcame a weak opening to surge in  
brisk trading Tuesday on the New York Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	On other commodity markets, grain and soybean futures prices  
were higher in reaction to government reports that the condition of 
the corn and soybean crops has deteriorated. Cotton futures were 
fractionally lower. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude oil futures tumbled in early trading, losing 20 cents at  
their lowest before rebounding. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market was basically surprised to find the buying  
interest,'' said analyst Tim Evans of Pegasus Econometric Group. 
</P>
<P>
	The market was slightly nervous about the weekly American  
Petroleum Institute inventory report, which is released after the 
close of trading and was been expected to show a decline from last 
week in stockpiles of crude oil and gasoline, Evans said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It (API data) wasn't expected to be bullish factor in the  
market,'' he said. ``But it turned into a compelling reason to 
buy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Light sweet crude for September delivery settled 38 cents higher  
at $21.74 a barrel; September heating oil was 1.47 cents higher at 
56.81 cents a gallon; September unleaded gasoline was 1.32 cents 
higher at 65.44 cents a gallon; September natural gas was 0.008 
cent higher at $2.708 per 1,000 cubic feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Grain and soybean futures prices rose on the Chicago Board of  
Trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures prices surged at the start of trading in response  
to the U.S. Department of Agriculture's rating of the crop as 58 
percent in good to excellent condition, a decline from the previous 
week. There also was concern that below-normal precipitation in 
coming days could further hurt the crop. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean futures prices surged early in the day in reaction to  
weather forecasts and the USDA's weekly soybean update, which 
indicates the poor condition of some of the crop could mean a drop 
in the 2.87 billion-bushel-harvest that was forecast Aug. 12. But 
the early gains were trimmed by profit-taking. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures were higher as the market reacted to news Algeria,  
Egypt and Tunisia are in the market for U.S. wheat. The USDA also 
announced the sale of 140,000 metric tons of wheat to Peru. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat prices also got a boost from an unexpected decline in the  
condition of the wheat crop. The USDA estimates 58 percent of the 
crop is in good to excellent condition. Expectations that the dry 
weather will help with the harvest trimmed the early gains. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for September delivery was 1/4 cent higher at $2.69 a  
bushel; September corn was 2 1/2 cents higher at $2.16 1/2 a bushel; 
September oats were 1 3/4 cents lower at 1.07 1/4 a bushel; August 
soybeans were 8 1/2 cents higher at $4.64 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Cotton futures fell on the New York Cotton Exchange despite the  
a decline in U.S. crop conditions because of the parched landscape 
in the cotton belt. 
</P>
<P>
	The USDA reported a major drop in the condition of cotton in  
Georgia and South Carolina. Only 29 percent of the Georgia crop is 
rated fair and 36 percent is good to excellent. The remainder is 
rated poor. 
</P>
<P>
	Forty-seven percent of the crop in South Carolina is rated fair,  
with only 18 percent good. The remainder is in poor or very poor 
condition. 
</P>
<P>
	October cotton was 0.02 cent lower at 53.66 cents a pound.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
