<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cool Weather Blankets Seattle Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Summer months usually offer Seattle residents a  
respite from the region's infamous clouds and rain. Not this year. 
</P>
<P>
	While much of the nation has been suffering through unusually  
hot weather, the Puget Sound area has been having its coolest 
summer since 1956, the National Weather Service says. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone is depressed knowing it's halfway into August and we  
haven't had a summer, at least psychologically,'' said Ted Buehner, 
a weather service meteorologist. 
</P>
<P>
	After some sunny weather in July, August arrived with a barrage  
of thunderstorms. Since then, occasional sun has been bracketed by 
drizzle or just grim gray overcast. 
</P>
<P>
	Seattle has had just two 80-degree days so far this month. Last  
August, there were seven 80-degree days by mid-month. 
</P>
<P>
	Through Sunday, the city had logged 0.82 inches of rain for the  
month, compared with just over a third of an inch of rain all of 
last August. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had a pretty lousy winter, and people got pretty doggone  
depressed,'' Buehner said. ``Everyone kept saying, `Where's the 
sun?' Then, June was ugly for the most part. ... July was the best 
so far, though a little cooler than normal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And August is off to a soggy start. Road crews had to delay  
pouring concrete on a stretch of Interstate 5 express lanes Sunday 
because of the rain. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
