<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Marine Faces Prison in Vaccine Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MAYPORT NAVAL STATION, Fla. (AP) -- A sailor who refused to take  
the anthrax vaccine will spend 10 days in jail and receive a bad 
conduct discharge after pleading guilty. 
</P>
<P>
	Capt. Raymond Kreichelt, the military judge, also sentenced  
Zachary A. Johnson to a reduction in rank. Johnson was sentenced to 
45 days in jail, but 35 days will be suspended under a plea 
bargain. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, 22, had faced up to six months in prison.  
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, an aviation electronics technician, pleaded guilty  
Tuesday to willfully disobeying a direct order and failing to obey 
a lawful regulation. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still believe the order to take the vaccine is wrong,''  
Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Although not the first sailor to refuse the vaccine, Johnson is  
the first in the Navy to face a court-martial. Other sailors who 
have refused the vaccine have taken a nonjudicial option known as a 
captain's mast, in which a commanding officer conducts a hearing 
and decides punishment. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, a Marine helicopter crew chief was sentenced to 30  
days in confinement and issued a bad conduct discharge for his 
refusal. 
</P>
<P>
	The vaccine is being given to all 2.4 million members of the  
armed services to protect them against deadly anthrax bacteria. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly 900,000 service members have been immunized so far. The  
Pentagon says more than 79 have reported adverse effects but all 
have recovered. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
