<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CNBC Marketwatch Debuts on NYSE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- CNBC's prime-time stock market program,  
``Business Center,'' was broadcast for the first time Monday from 
its new set on the floor of the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	The broadcast marked something of a victory for CNBC, which is  
battling CNN for viewers in the prime 6:30 p.m. to 7:30 p.m. time 
slot in which Business Center squares off against CNN's higher 
rated ``Moneyline.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both stations recently announced plans to broadcast shows from  
the floor of the NYSE. 
</P>
<P>
	CNN has said it will debut a new program called ``Street Sweep''  
sometime in the fall. The show will air daily at 3:59 p.m., one 
minute before the closing of U.S. stock markets. 
</P>
<P>
	With a highly recognizable backdrop of walls covered with  
computer trading screens, hosts Ron Insana and Sue Herera were 
forced to speak up a bit Monday to compensate for the wide-open 
acoustics of the trading floor and to be heard over the humming din 
of the Big Board's sleeping computer system. 
</P>
<P>
	NYSE Chairman Richard Grasso joined the hosts for a live, on-air  
interview in which he discussed the exchange's plans to complete an 
initial public offering. 
</P>
<P>
	Competition between CNBC and CNN has been intense in recent  
months. While CNBC is the leading business network, ``Moneyline'' 
consistently outrates ``Business Center'' and is more attractive to 
advertisers. 
</P>
<P>
	CNBC expanded ``Business Center'' to an hour earlier this summer  
after popular ``Moneyline'' host Lou Dobbs quit and cut into its 
rival's audience, but CNN has remained in the lead. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Stock Exchange first allowed live TV reports from  
the trading floor in 1995, requiring networks to use robotic 
cameras to minimize congestion. Twenty-two television stations are 
now accredited to report from the exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the Big Board is making space for desks so CNN and CNBC can  
deliver full shows there, although ongoing live shows won't be 
allowed during the midst of trading. The networks will pay a 
nominal production fee. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
