<HEADLINE> Hallmark Announces Expansion Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Hallmark Cards Inc. on Tuesday announced  
a plan to expand its business in six key areas as it seeks to 
triple the company's revenues in the next 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Irvine O. Hockaday Jr., president and chief executive officer of  
Hallmark, said the privately held company will continue to build 
and expand its core greeting card business. But it also will expand 
its efforts in five other areas, which Hockaday labeled ``caring 
gift solutions,'' memories, life celebrations, personal development 
and family entertainment. 
</P>
<P>
	The goal is to increase revenues from this year's $3.9 billion  
to $12 billion in 2010, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will continue to build and extend our core greeting card  
business,'' Hockaday said. ``But at the same time we have the 
opportunity to build emerging businesses that will create 
incremental, profitable growth consistent with the Hallmark brand's 
ability to reach a wider range of consumers.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
