<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 3:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Aug. 17, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	After-Hours Trading Coming to ETrade  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Individual investors will now get access to  
after-hours trading on ETrade via Instinet, the biggest market for 
buying and selling stock when traditional exchanges are closed. The 
new service would make ETrade Group the biggest online brokerage so 
far to provide its customers with entry to a market that until 
recently was the exclusive province of money managers and 
institutional investors. By teaming with Instinet, ETrade is 
bringing its customers a possibly safer way to take part in a 
volatile market where stock prices can swing wildly due to limited 
demand. ETrade shares were trading up 1 7/8 at 28 3/4. 

</P>
<P>
	Consumer Prices Rise 0.3 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Despite a sharp jump in gasoline prices and  
airline fares, consumer prices rose a moderate 0.3 percent in July. 
The Labor Department reported today that July's increase in its 
Consumer Price Index -- the most closely watched gauge of inflation 
-- followed two straight months in which prices remained frozen. 
July's inflation report was right in line with many analysts' 
expectations and was expected to further ease inflation concerns in 
financial markets. The 0.3 percent increase in the CPI was the 
biggest since a 0.7 percent surge in April. 

</P>
<P>
	HP Stock Drops After Solid Report  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Hewlett-Packard Co. stock, which shot up  
4 percent yesterday in advance of a strong quarterly profit report 
and gained even more in after-hours trading, slumped today to give 
up those gains. In late afternoon trading on the New York Stock 
Exchange, Hewlett-Packard was down 5 3/4, or 5.21 percent, at 104 1/2 a 
share. HP, the world's second largest computer company, yesterday 
credited a 37 percent rise in quarterly profit to its new efforts 
to focus on revenue growth. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Edge Higher; Dow Up 8.55  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were trading slightly higher today as a  
government report of a mild increase in consumer prices failed to 
hearten investors. Just before 3 p.m. EDT, the Dow Jones industrial 
average was up 8.55 at 11,055.34. The index gave up an earlier gain 
of nearly 65 points, leading some analysts to suggest that the 
market remains troubled by worries that the Federal Reserve will 
raise interest rates in an effort to stifle inflation. Broader 
stock indicators were moving between modest gains and losses. 

</P>
